// ===== CHAPTER: Sexual Reproduction in Flowering Plants =====
var allQuestions = [

  // ───── TOPIC: INTRODUCTION ─────
  { id: 1, topic: "Introduction", q: "Consider the following statements regarding reproduction:<br>(i) Reproduction is a vital process without which species cannot survive for long.<br>(ii) Individual organisms are immortal but species are not.<br>(iii) Sexual mode of reproduction enables creation of new variants.<br>(iv) Survival advantage is enhanced by sexual reproduction.<br><br>Which of the above statements are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is incorrect — individual organisms die without fail, but species continue to live through millions of years. Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are directly stated in NCERT. Sexual reproduction creates new variants which enhance survival advantage." },

  { id: 2, topic: "Introduction", q: "Which of the following contributions is/are correctly attributed to Panchanan Maheshwari?<br>(i) Popularised use of embryological characters in taxonomy.<br>(ii) Established Department of Botany, University of Delhi as a centre for embryology and tissue culture research.<br>(iii) Work on test tube fertilisation and intra-ovarian pollination.<br>(iv) Fellowship of Royal Society of London (FRS).<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are correctly attributed to Panchanan Maheshwari as per NCERT. He also contributed to school education by bringing out the first Biology textbooks for Higher Secondary Schools published by NCERT in 1964." },

  { id: 3, topic: "Introduction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> All flowering plants show sexual reproduction.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Flowers are the sites of sexual reproduction in angiosperms and show amazing adaptations to ensure formation of fruits and seeds.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are true as per NCERT. The reason correctly explains the assertion — all flowering plants reproduce sexually, and the diversity of floral structures represents adaptations ensuring successful sexual reproduction leading to fruits and seeds." },

  { id: 4, topic: "Introduction", q: "According to NCERT, which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a role of flowers mentioned in relation to human civilisation?", options: ["Aesthetic and ornamental value", "Social, religious and cultural value", "Symbols for conveying human feelings", "Primary source of nutrition in human diet"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT describes flowers as objects of aesthetic, ornamental, social, religious and cultural value, and as symbols for conveying feelings like love, affection, happiness, grief, and mourning. Flowers being a primary source of nutrition is NOT mentioned." },

  { id: 5, topic: "Introduction", q: "Which of the following correctly describes the term 'floriculture'?", options: ["Study of flower morphology and taxonomy", "Cultivation of flowers for commercial and ornamental purposes", "Study of fossil flowers from geological past", "Artificial hybridisation of flowering plants"], correct: 1, explanation: "Floriculture refers to the branch of horticulture dealing with the cultivation of flowers and ornamental plants for commercial and decorative purposes. NCERT mentions floriculture in the context of ornamental flowers cultivated at homes and gardens." },

  { id: 6, topic: "Introduction", q: "To a biologist, flowers are described as:<br>(i) Morphological marvels<br>(ii) Embryological marvels<br>(iii) Sites of asexual reproduction<br>(iv) Sites of sexual reproduction<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically states: 'To a biologist, flowers are morphological and embryological marvels and the sites of sexual reproduction.' Statement (iii) is wrong as flowers are sites of sexual, not asexual, reproduction." },

  { id: 7, topic: "Introduction", q: "Species continue to live through millions of years unless threatened by:", options: ["Natural extinction only", "Anthropogenic extinction only", "Natural or anthropogenic extinction", "Genetic drift and mutations"], correct: 2, explanation: "As per NCERT, species continue to live through millions of years unless threatened by natural or anthropogenic (human-caused) extinction. Both types of threats are specifically mentioned." },

  { id: 8, topic: "Introduction", q: "The two most important units of sexual reproduction in a flower develop in:", options: ["Sepals and petals", "Thalamus and pedicel", "Anther and ovule", "Filament and style"], correct: 2, explanation: "The two most important units of sexual reproduction — pollen grains (male gametophyte) and ovules (containing female gametophyte) — develop in the anther (part of androecium) and ovary (part of gynoecium), respectively." },

  // ───── TOPIC: PRE-FERTILISATION: STRUCTURES AND EVENTS ─────
  { id: 9, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following statements about floral development:<br>(i) The decision to flower occurs much before the actual flower appears.<br>(ii) Only hormonal changes are needed for floral primordium differentiation.<br>(iii) Inflorescences are formed which bear floral buds and then flowers.<br>(iv) Androecium and gynoecium differentiate and develop within the flower.<br><br>Which statements are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is incorrect because NCERT states 'several hormonal AND structural changes' are initiated — not only hormonal. Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are directly from NCERT text." },

  { id: 10, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> A typical angiosperm anther is described as dithecous.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Each anther lobe has two theca, making the anther a four-sided tetragonal structure with four microsporangia.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "A typical angiosperm anther is bilobed, each lobe having two theca (hence dithecous). The anther is tetragonal with four microsporangia located at the corners, two in each lobe. R correctly explains why the anther is dithecous." },

  { id: 11, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following is the correct sequence of wall layers in a microsporangium from <b>outermost to innermost</b>?", options: ["Endothecium → Epidermis → Middle layers → Tapetum", "Epidermis → Middle layers → Endothecium → Tapetum", "Epidermis → Endothecium → Middle layers → Tapetum", "Tapetum → Middle layers → Endothecium → Epidermis"], correct: 2, explanation: "As per NCERT, the four wall layers from outermost to innermost are: Epidermis → Endothecium → Middle layers → Tapetum. The outer three layers protect and help in dehiscence; the innermost tapetum nourishes developing pollen grains." },

  { id: 12, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a function of the outer three wall layers of a microsporangium?", options: ["Protection of microsporangium", "Help in dehiscence of anther", "Nourishment of developing pollen grains", "Structural support to the anther"], correct: 2, explanation: "Nourishment of developing pollen grains is the function of the tapetum (innermost wall layer), NOT the outer three layers. The outer three layers (epidermis, endothecium, middle layers) perform protection and help in dehiscence of the anther." },

  { id: 13, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following about tapetum:<br>(i) It is the innermost wall layer of microsporangium.<br>(ii) It nourishes developing pollen grains.<br>(iii) Tapetal cells possess dense cytoplasm.<br>(iv) Tapetal cells are always uninucleate.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["(i) only", "(iv) only", "(i) and (iii)", "(ii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iv) is incorrect. NCERT states tapetal cells 'generally have more than one nucleus.' They can be bi-nucleate or multinucleate. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are all correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 14, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The sporogenous tissue in a young anther is characterised as:", options: ["Loosely arranged heterogenous cells at the periphery", "Compactly arranged homogenous cells occupying the centre of each microsporangium", "Scattered cells with large vacuoles between endothecium and tapetum", "Single-layered cells surrounding the pollen sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'When the anther is young, a group of compactly arranged homogenous cells called the sporogenous tissue occupies the centre of each microsporangium.' This is the tissue that gives rise to microspore tetrads." },

  { id: 15, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Microsporogenesis refers to:", options: ["Formation of megaspores from megaspore mother cell", "Formation of microspores from pollen mother cell through meiosis", "Formation of male gametes from generative cell through mitosis", "Development of microspore into a mature pollen grain"], correct: 1, explanation: "Microsporogenesis is specifically defined as the process of formation of microspores from a pollen mother cell (PMC) through meiosis. Option C describes microgametogenesis. Option D describes pollen grain maturation." },

  { id: 16, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The ploidy of cells in a microspore tetrad is:", options: ["Diploid (2n)", "Haploid (n)", "Triploid (3n)", "Tetraploid (4n)"], correct: 1, explanation: "The pollen mother cell (PMC) is diploid (2n). It undergoes meiosis to form a microspore tetrad. Since meiosis is a reductional division, each cell of the tetrad is haploid (n)." },

  { id: 17, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Sporopollenin is one of the most resistant organic materials known.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> No enzyme that degrades sporopollenin has been discovered so far.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are true and directly from NCERT. Sporopollenin can withstand high temperatures and strong acids and alkali. The fact that no known enzyme can degrade it is evidence supporting its extreme resistance, making R the correct explanation of A." },

  { id: 18, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Pollen grains are well-preserved as fossils because of the presence of:", options: ["Cellulose in intine", "Pectin in intine", "Sporopollenin in exine", "Callose in pollen wall"], correct: 2, explanation: "Sporopollenin, present in the exine (outer layer) of pollen grain, is extremely resistant to chemical and biological degradation. This resistance allows pollen grains to be well-preserved as fossils over geological time periods." },

  { id: 19, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following about the pollen grain wall is <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["Exine is made up of sporopollenin", "Intine is a thin and continuous layer made of cellulose and pectin", "Germ pores are apertures in the exine where sporopollenin is absent", "Exine is a thin continuous layer while intine is thick and discontinuous"], correct: 3, explanation: "Statement (D) reverses the actual description. The exine is the hard outer layer (discontinuous at germ pores), while the intine is thin and continuous. NCERT clearly states intine is thin and continuous, made of cellulose and pectin." },

  { id: 20, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In a mature pollen grain, the vegetative cell is characterised by:<br>(i) Being larger than the generative cell.<br>(ii) Having abundant food reserves.<br>(iii) Having a large irregularly shaped nucleus.<br>(iv) Being spindle-shaped with dense cytoplasm.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) correctly describe the vegetative cell. Statement (iv) — 'spindle-shaped with dense cytoplasm' — describes the generative cell, NOT the vegetative cell. The generative cell is small, spindle-shaped, and floats in the cytoplasm of the vegetative cell." },

  { id: 21, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In over 60% of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at the:", options: ["1-celled stage", "2-celled stage", "3-celled stage", "4-celled stage"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states that in over 60% of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at the 2-celled stage (containing vegetative cell and generative cell). In the remaining species, the generative cell divides mitotically before shedding, resulting in the 3-celled stage." },

  { id: 22, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In pollen grains shed at the 3-celled stage, the third cell type is formed by:", options: ["Meiotic division of vegetative cell", "Mitotic division of generative cell", "Meiotic division of generative cell", "Mitotic division of vegetative cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "The generative cell divides mitotically (not meiotically) to give rise to two male gametes. This occurs before pollen shedding in species with 3-celled pollen. The vegetative cell does not divide further." },

  { id: 23, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following plants is known to cause severe pollen allergy and came to India as a contaminant with imported wheat?", options: ["Cannabis sativa", "Parthenium hysterophorus", "Amaranthus spinosus", "Chenopodium album"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically mentions Parthenium (carrot grass) as a plant that came into India as a contaminant with imported wheat, has become ubiquitous, and causes pollen allergy leading to chronic respiratory disorders like asthma and bronchitis." },

  { id: 24, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following about pollen grain viability:<br>(i) Pollen viability is highly variable across species.<br>(ii) In rice and wheat, pollen grains lose viability within 30 minutes.<br>(iii) Members of Rosaceae, Leguminoseae and Solanaceae maintain viability for months.<br>(iv) Pollen grains can be stored in liquid nitrogen at -196°C.<br><br>Which statements are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are directly from NCERT. Pollen viability depends on temperature and humidity. Rice and wheat pollen lose viability within 30 minutes. Rosaceae, Leguminoseae and Solanaceae maintain viability for months. Cryopreservation at -196°C in liquid nitrogen is used for pollen banks." },

  { id: 25, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Pollen banks are analogous to seed banks and are used in:", options: ["Forensic investigations", "Palaeopalynological studies", "Crop breeding programmes", "Bioremediation of soil"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Such stored pollen can be used as pollen banks, similar to seed banks, in crop breeding programmes.' Pollen stored in liquid nitrogen at -196°C retains viability for years and is useful in hybridisation and breeding." },

  { id: 26, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The size of pollen grains is generally:", options: ["5–10 micrometres in diameter", "25–50 micrometres in diameter", "100–200 micrometres in diameter", "250–500 micrometres in diameter"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states that pollen grains are generally spherical measuring about 25–50 micrometres in diameter. This is an important factual detail frequently tested in NEET." },

  { id: 27, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following statements about the generative cell of a pollen grain is <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["It is small and floats in the cytoplasm of the vegetative cell", "It is spindle-shaped with dense cytoplasm", "It has a large irregularly shaped nucleus", "It divides mitotically to form two male gametes"], correct: 2, explanation: "A 'large irregularly shaped nucleus' is the characteristic of the vegetative cell, NOT the generative cell. The generative cell is small, spindle-shaped, with dense cytoplasm and a nucleus. This is a common NEET trap." },

  { id: 28, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Germ pores are regions in the pollen grain where sporopollenin is absent.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Germ pores facilitate the emergence of pollen tube during germination.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are true. Germ pores are prominent apertures on the exine where sporopollenin is absent, precisely to allow the pollen tube to emerge during germination. R correctly explains the functional significance of A." },

  { id: 29, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following correctly describes the relationship between microsporangium and pollen sac?", options: ["Pollen sac develops into microsporangium at maturity", "Microsporangium develops further to become pollen sac", "Both are entirely different structures with no relation", "Microsporangium is present inside the pollen sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The microsporangia develop further and become pollen sacs.' So microsporangium is the developmental precursor of the pollen sac. They extend longitudinally through the anther length and are packed with pollen grains." },

  { id: 30, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Sporopollenin can withstand all of the following <b>EXCEPT</b>:", options: ["High temperatures", "Strong acids", "Strong alkali", "Enzymatic degradation by known enzymes"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states sporopollenin can withstand high temperatures, strong acids, and strong alkali. However, NCERT explicitly states 'no enzyme that degrades sporopollenin is so far known' — implying its resistance to known enzymatic degradation is the most defining property, making D the conceptually distinct answer in NEET context." },

  { id: 31, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "A bilobed anther has how many microsporangia in total?", options: ["Two", "Four", "Six", "Eight"], correct: 1, explanation: "A typical angiosperm anther is bilobed with each lobe having two theca. Each theca contains one microsporangium. So a bilobed anther has 4 microsporangia (2 per lobe). The anther is tetragonal with four microsporangia at the corners." },

  { id: 32, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The proximal end of the filament of a stamen is attached to:", options: ["Anther only", "Stigma or style", "Thalamus or petal of the flower", "Ovary wall"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The proximal end of the filament is attached to the thalamus or the petal of the flower.' The distal end bears the anther." },

  { id: 33, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Pollen grains have been claimed to:<br>(i) Cause severe allergies and bronchial afflictions.<br>(ii) Be rich in nutrients.<br>(iii) Increase performance of athletes and race horses.<br>(iv) Be available as tablets and syrups in western countries.<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four points are explicitly mentioned in NCERT. Pollen causes allergies (asthma, bronchitis), is rich in nutrients, used as food supplements (tablets and syrups) in western countries, and claimed to increase performance of athletes and race horses." },

  { id: 34, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following statements about the two parts of a stamen is correct?", options: ["The filament is terminal and bilobed, the anther is long and slender", "The filament is long and slender, the anther is terminal and generally bilobed", "Both filament and anther are bilobed structures", "The filament is bilobed and the anther is attached to the thalamus"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT describes a typical stamen as having a long and slender stalk called the filament, and a terminal generally bilobed structure called the anther. Option A reverses the descriptions — a common NEET trap." },

  { id: 35, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Tapetal cells could become binucleate by:", options: ["Meiotic division without cytokinesis", "Mitotic division without cytokinesis (endomitosis)", "Fusion of two adjacent tapetal cells", "Amitotic division followed by cytokinesis"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tapetal cells generally have more than one nucleus. This occurs through mitotic division of the nucleus without subsequent cytokinesis (endomitosis). This is the mechanism implied in NCERT when it asks how tapetal cells could become bi-nucleate." },

  { id: 36, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "A longitudinal groove running lengthwise in an anther separates:", options: ["The two microsporangia within a lobe", "The two theca of the same lobe", "The two lobes (theca) of the anther", "The epidermis from the endothecium"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Often a longitudinal groove runs lengthwise separating the theca.' This groove separates the two lobes of the bilobed anther, making the dithecous nature externally visible." },

  { id: 37, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following correctly matches the cell type with its description in a mature pollen grain?<br><br>(a) Vegetative cell — bigger, abundant food reserve, large irregularly shaped nucleus<br>(b) Generative cell — small, spindle-shaped, dense cytoplasm<br>(c) Vegetative cell — spindle-shaped, floats in generative cell cytoplasm<br>(d) Generative cell — bigger, abundant food reserve", options: ["(a) and (b) only", "(a) and (d) only", "(b) and (c) only", "(c) and (d) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Only (a) and (b) are correct. The vegetative cell is bigger with abundant food and an irregularly shaped nucleus. The generative cell is small, spindle-shaped, with dense cytoplasm, and floats in the cytoplasm of the vegetative cell." },

  { id: 38, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Each cell of the sporogenous tissue in a microsporangium is considered a potential:", options: ["Megaspore mother cell", "Pollen grain", "Pollen or microspore mother cell", "Male gamete"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As each cell of the sporogenous tissue is capable of giving rise to a microspore tetrad, each one is a potential pollen or microspore mother cell.' These cells undergo meiosis to form microspore tetrads." },

  // ───── TOPIC: THE PISTIL, MEGASPORANGIUM (OVULE) AND EMBRYO SAC ─────
  { id: 39, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Consider the following statements about the gynoecium:<br>(i) A monocarpellary gynoecium consists of a single pistil.<br>(ii) Syncarpous condition refers to free pistils in a multicarpellary gynoecium.<br>(iii) Apocarpous condition refers to fused pistils in a multicarpellary gynoecium.<br>(iv) Each pistil has three parts — stigma, style and ovary.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (ii) is incorrect — syncarpous refers to fused pistils, not free. Statement (iii) is incorrect — apocarpous refers to free pistils, not fused. These are commonly interchanged. Statements (i) and (iv) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 40, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The stigma of a pistil functions as:", options: ["The site of megaspore formation", "A landing platform for pollen grains", "The site of embryo sac development", "A passage for the movement of male gametes"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically states: 'The stigma serves as a landing platform for pollen grains.' The style is the elongated slender part beneath the stigma, and the ovary is the basal bulged part containing ovules." },

  { id: 41, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Match the following plants with the number of ovules present in their ovary:<br><br>(a) Wheat — (i) Many ovules<br>(b) Papaya — (ii) One ovule<br>(c) Mango — (iii) Many ovules<br>(d) Orchids — (iv) One ovule<br><br>Select the correct matching:", options: ["a-(ii), b-(i), c-(iv), d-(iii)", "a-(i), b-(ii), c-(iii), d-(iv)", "a-(ii), b-(iii), c-(ii), d-(i)", "a-(i), b-(iii), c-(iv), d-(ii)"], correct: 0, explanation: "As per NCERT: Wheat, paddy, and mango have one ovule in their ovary, while papaya, watermelon, and orchids have many ovules. So wheat-(one), papaya-(many), mango-(one), orchids-(many)." },

  { id: 42, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The hilum in an ovule represents:", options: ["The opening at the tip of integuments", "The basal part of the ovule opposite the micropyle", "The junction between the ovule and the funicle", "The mass of cells enclosed within the integuments"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The body of the ovule fuses with funicle in the region called hilum. Thus, hilum represents the junction between ovule and funicle.' Micropyle is the small opening at the tip. Chalaza is the basal part. Nucellus is the mass of cells." },

  { id: 43, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Consider the following structures in an ovule:<br>(i) Funicle — stalk attaching ovule to placenta<br>(ii) Integuments — one or two protective envelopes<br>(iii) Micropyle — small opening at the tip where integuments are absent<br>(iv) Chalaza — represents the micropylar end of the ovule<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is incorrect. Chalaza represents the basal part of the ovule, which is OPPOSITE the micropylar end. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct as per NCERT." },

  { id: 44, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The nucellus is a mass of cells enclosed within the integuments of the ovule.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Cells of the nucellus have abundant reserve food materials.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both statements are true and directly from NCERT. However, the reason (having abundant reserve food materials) does not explain why the nucellus is enclosed within integuments. The integuments provide protection, not related to food reserve. Hence R is not the correct explanation of A." },

  { id: 45, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The megaspore mother cell (MMC) in an ovule is:<br>(i) Differentiated in the micropylar region of the nucellus<br>(ii) A large cell with dense cytoplasm and a prominent nucleus<br>(iii) Generally single in each ovule<br>(iv) Undergoes mitotic division to form four megaspores<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iv) is incorrect — the MMC undergoes MEIOTIC division (not mitotic) to produce four megaspores. This is a very common NEET trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are all correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 46, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Megasporogenesis refers to:", options: ["Formation of megaspore mother cell from nucellus", "Formation of megaspores from the megaspore mother cell", "Development of embryo sac from functional megaspore", "Formation of egg cell from embryo sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT defines megasporogenesis as 'the process of formation of megaspores from the megaspore mother cell.' Option C describes female gametophyte development. Option A describes differentiation, not megasporogenesis." },

  { id: 47, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "In a majority of flowering plants, out of the four megaspores formed after meiosis:", options: ["All four megaspores are functional", "Two megaspores are functional and two degenerate", "One megaspore is functional and the other three degenerate", "Three megaspores are functional and one degenerates"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In a majority of flowering plants, one of the megaspores is functional while the other three degenerate. Only the functional megaspore develops into the female gametophyte (embryo sac).' This is termed monosporic development." },

  { id: 48, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The method of embryo sac formation from a single megaspore is termed:", options: ["Bisporic development", "Tetrasporic development", "Monosporic development", "Polysporic development"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT explicitly states: 'This method of embryo sac formation from a single megaspore is termed monosporic development.' In bisporic development, two megaspores participate; in tetrasporic, all four contribute — but these are not the majority pattern." },

  { id: 49, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The correct sequence of mitotic divisions during embryo sac development is:", options: ["Functional megaspore → 4-nucleate → 2-nucleate → 8-nucleate", "Functional megaspore → 2-nucleate → 8-nucleate → 4-nucleate", "Functional megaspore → 2-nucleate → 4-nucleate → 8-nucleate", "Functional megaspore → 8-nucleate → 4-nucleate → 2-nucleate"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT clearly describes: the functional megaspore nucleus divides mitotically to form 2 nuclei → two more sequential mitotic divisions result in 4-nucleate → then 8-nucleate stages. The sequence is 1→2→4→8." },

  { id: 50, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The mitotic divisions during embryo sac formation are strictly free nuclear divisions.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Nuclear divisions are not followed immediately by cell wall formation during embryo sac development.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are directly from NCERT and R correctly explains A. The term 'free nuclear' means nuclear divisions occur without accompanying cytokinesis (cell wall formation). Cell walls are laid down only after the 8-nucleate stage." },

  { id: 51, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "A typical angiosperm embryo sac at maturity is:", options: ["8-nucleate and 8-celled", "7-nucleate and 7-celled", "8-nucleate and 7-celled", "7-nucleate and 8-celled"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A typical angiosperm embryo sac, at maturity, though 8-nucleate is 7-celled.' Six of the eight nuclei are organised into cells, and the remaining two nuclei (polar nuclei) are in the large central cell. Total = 6 + 1 (central cell) = 7 cells with 8 nuclei." },

  { id: 52, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The egg apparatus in an embryo sac consists of:", options: ["One egg cell and one synergid", "Two egg cells and one synergid", "Two synergids and one egg cell", "Three egg cells"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The egg apparatus, in turn, consists of two synergids and one egg cell.' These three cells are grouped together at the micropylar end of the embryo sac." },

  { id: 53, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The filiform apparatus is found in:", options: ["Antipodal cells at the chalazal end", "Egg cell at the micropylar end", "Synergids at the micropylar tip", "Central cell containing polar nuclei"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The synergids have special cellular thickenings at the micropylar tip called filiform apparatus, which play an important role in guiding the pollen tubes into the synergid.' It is NOT found in egg cell or antipodals." },

  { id: 54, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The function of the filiform apparatus is:", options: ["Nourishment of the egg cell", "Protection of the embryo sac from pathogens", "Guiding the pollen tubes into the synergid", "Facilitating the fusion of polar nuclei"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT clearly states the filiform apparatus plays 'an important role in guiding the pollen tubes into the synergid.' This is crucial for successful fertilisation in angiosperms." },

  { id: 55, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The distribution of cells in a mature embryo sac is:<br>(i) 3 cells at micropylar end (egg apparatus)<br>(ii) 3 cells at chalazal end (antipodals)<br>(iii) 1 large central cell with 2 polar nuclei<br>(iv) 2 cells at micropylar end and 4 cells at chalazal end<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT. Statement (iv) is incorrect — the distribution is 3 cells at the micropylar end (2 synergids + 1 egg cell) and 3 cells at the chalazal end (antipodals), plus 1 central cell with 2 polar nuclei = 7 cells total." },

  { id: 56, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The ploidy of the following structures in an ovule is:<br>(a) Nucellus cells<br>(b) MMC<br>(c) Functional megaspore<br>(d) Cells of embryo sac<br><br>Select the correct combination:", options: ["a-2n, b-2n, c-n, d-n", "a-n, b-2n, c-n, d-2n", "a-2n, b-n, c-2n, d-n", "a-2n, b-2n, c-2n, d-n"], correct: 0, explanation: "Nucellus cells are diploid (2n) as they are somatic cells. MMC is also diploid (2n) as it has not yet undergone meiosis. After meiosis, the functional megaspore is haploid (n). The embryo sac develops from the megaspore by mitosis, so its cells remain haploid (n)." },

  { id: 57, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The polar nuclei in the embryo sac are located in:", options: ["The egg apparatus at the micropylar end", "The antipodal cells at the chalazal end", "The large central cell below the egg apparatus", "The synergids at the micropylar tip"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The remaining two nuclei, called polar nuclei are situated below the egg apparatus in the large central cell.' They are not enclosed in separate cells but remain as free nuclei in the central cell." },

  { id: 58, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following plants has only <b>one</b> ovule in its ovary?", options: ["Papaya", "Watermelon", "Paddy", "Orchid"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions that wheat, paddy and mango have one ovule in the ovary, while papaya, watermelon and orchids have many ovules. This is a direct factual question commonly asked in NEET." },

  { id: 59, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> An embryo sac at maturity has 7 cells but 8 nuclei.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> The central cell of the embryo sac contains two polar nuclei that are not separated by a cell wall.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are true. The embryo sac has 8 nuclei but only 7 cells because two polar nuclei share the same central cell without a cell wall between them. R correctly explains why 8 nuclei are present in only 7 cells." },

  { id: 60, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Cell walls are laid down in the developing embryo sac at the:", options: ["2-nucleate stage", "4-nucleate stage", "8-nucleate stage", "16-nucleate stage"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'After the 8-nucleate stage, cell walls are laid down leading to the organisation of the typical female gametophyte or embryo sac.' Before this, all divisions are strictly free nuclear (without cytokinesis)." },

  { id: 61, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The megasporangia arise from:", options: ["The ovary wall", "The style", "The placenta inside the ovarian cavity", "The stigmatic surface"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Arising from the placenta are the megasporangia, commonly called ovules.' The placenta is located inside the ovarian cavity (locule), and ovules are attached to it." },

  { id: 62, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "How many total mitotic divisions occur during the development of a mature embryo sac from a functional megaspore?", options: ["Two", "Three", "Four", "Five"], correct: 1, explanation: "The functional megaspore undergoes 3 successive mitotic divisions: 1st division → 2-nucleate, 2nd division → 4-nucleate, 3rd division → 8-nucleate embryo sac. So a total of 3 mitotic divisions occur." },

  { id: 63, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following is the correct description of the ovarian cavity?", options: ["It is also known as the locule", "It is the region between integuments and nucellus", "It is the space between the two polar nuclei", "It is the micropylar canal of the ovule"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Inside the ovary is the ovarian cavity (locule).' The locule contains the placenta from which ovules arise. Options B, C, and D describe structures unrelated to the ovarian cavity." },

  { id: 64, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Consider the following about the antipodal cells:<br>(i) They are three in number.<br>(ii) They are located at the micropylar end.<br>(iii) They are located at the chalazal end.<br>(iv) They have filiform apparatus.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Only (i) and (iii) are correct. Antipodals are three cells located at the chalazal end. Statement (ii) is wrong — the micropylar end has the egg apparatus. Statement (iv) is wrong — filiform apparatus is a feature of synergids, not antipodals." },

  { id: 65, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a part of the ovule?", options: ["Funicle", "Integuments", "Nucellus", "Filament"], correct: 3, explanation: "Filament is a part of the stamen (male reproductive structure), NOT the ovule. Funicle (stalk), integuments (protective envelopes), and nucellus (cell mass inside integuments) are all parts of the ovule as described in NCERT." },

  { id: 66, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The integuments in an ovule encircle the nucellus except at:", options: ["The chalazal end", "The hilum region", "The micropylar tip", "The funicle attachment point"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Integuments encircle the nucellus except at the tip where a small opening called the micropyle is organised.' The micropyle is the gap in the integuments at the tip, crucial for pollen tube entry during fertilisation." },

  { id: 67, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following represents the correct number of meiotic and mitotic divisions involved in the formation of a mature 8-nucleate embryo sac from a megaspore mother cell?", options: ["One meiotic and two mitotic divisions", "One meiotic and three mitotic divisions", "Two meiotic and three mitotic divisions", "One meiotic and four mitotic divisions"], correct: 1, explanation: "The MMC undergoes one meiotic division producing 4 megaspores (of which 3 degenerate). The single functional megaspore then undergoes 3 successive mitotic divisions (1→2→4→8 nuclei). Total = 1 meiotic + 3 mitotic divisions." },

  { id: 68, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The embryo sac is also called the female gametophyte.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> The embryo sac is located in the nucellus and is generally formed from a single megaspore.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both A and R are true and from NCERT. However, R describes the location and origin of the embryo sac, not the reason why it is called the female gametophyte. It is called the female gametophyte because it is the haploid structure that produces the female gamete (egg cell)." },

  // ───── TOPIC: POLLINATION ─────
  { id: 69, topic: "Pollination", q: "Pollination is defined as:", options: ["Fusion of male and female gametes", "Transfer of pollen grains from anther to the stigma of a pistil", "Germination of pollen grain on the stigma", "Transfer of male gametes to the embryo sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT defines pollination as 'Transfer of pollen grains (shed from the anther) to the stigma of a pistil.' It is NOT the fusion of gametes (which is fertilisation) or pollen germination." },

  { id: 70, topic: "Pollination", q: "Consider the following statements about autogamy:<br>(i) It involves transfer of pollen from anther to stigma of the same flower.<br>(ii) Complete autogamy is very common in flowers that open normally.<br>(iii) It requires synchrony in pollen release and stigma receptivity.<br>(iv) Anthers and stigma should lie close to each other for autogamy.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'In a normal flower which opens and exposes the anthers and the stigma, complete autogamy is rather rare.' Not common. Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are correct requirements for autogamy." },

  { id: 71, topic: "Pollination", q: "Cleistogamous flowers are found in:<br>(i) Viola (common pansy)<br>(ii) Oxalis<br>(iii) Commelina<br>(iv) Rosa<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT mentions Viola (common pansy), Oxalis, and Commelina as plants that produce both chasmogamous and cleistogamous flowers. Rosa is NOT mentioned in this context." },

  { id: 72, topic: "Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Cleistogamous flowers are invariably autogamous.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Cleistogamous flowers do not open at all, so there is no chance of cross-pollen landing on the stigma.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are directly from NCERT. Cleistogamous flowers never open, so anthers dehisce within the closed flower bud and pollen lands directly on the stigma. Since no external pollen can enter, they are invariably autogamous. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 73, topic: "Pollination", q: "Which of the following is an advantage of cleistogamous flowers?", options: ["They promote genetic variation", "They produce assured seed-set even in the absence of pollinators", "They attract diverse pollinators", "They allow cross-pollination under adverse conditions"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Cleistogamous flowers produce assured seed-set even in the absence of pollinators.' Since they self-pollinate within closed flowers, pollinator availability is not a limiting factor. However, they do not promote genetic variation." },

  { id: 74, topic: "Pollination", q: "Consider the following about geitonogamy:<br>(i) It involves transfer of pollen from anther to stigma of another flower of the same plant.<br>(ii) It is functionally cross-pollination.<br>(iii) It is genetically similar to autogamy.<br>(iv) It brings genetically different pollen to the stigma.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. NCERT states geitonogamy is 'genetically similar to autogamy since the pollen grains come from the same plant.' So it does NOT bring genetically different pollen. Only xenogamy brings genetically different pollen to the stigma." },

  { id: 75, topic: "Pollination", q: "The only type of pollination that brings genetically different types of pollen grains to the stigma is:", options: ["Autogamy", "Geitonogamy", "Xenogamy", "Cleistogamy"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Xenogamy — Transfer of pollen grains from anther to the stigma of a different plant. This is the only type of pollination which during pollination brings genetically different types of pollen grains to the stigma.'" },

  { id: 76, topic: "Pollination", q: "Geitonogamy is functionally cross-pollination but genetically similar to autogamy because:", options: ["Pollen is transferred by wind to another plant", "Pollen comes from a different flower but of the same plant", "Pollen comes from a flower of a different plant of the same species", "Both male and female gametes are produced in the same flower"], correct: 1, explanation: "In geitonogamy, pollen is transferred to the stigma of another flower of the same plant. It involves a pollinating agent (hence functionally cross-pollination), but since pollen comes from the same plant, the genetic makeup is the same as self-pollination (autogamy)." },

  { id: 77, topic: "Pollination", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a type of pollination based on the source of pollen?", options: ["Autogamy", "Geitonogamy", "Xenogamy", "Cleistogamy"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT classifies pollination into three types based on the source of pollen: autogamy, geitonogamy, and xenogamy. Cleistogamy is a mechanism/condition of flowers (closed flowers), not a type of pollination per se. It is a means of achieving autogamy." },

  { id: 78, topic: "Pollination", q: "Chasmogamous flowers differ from cleistogamous flowers in that:", options: ["Chasmogamous flowers are always cross-pollinated", "Chasmogamous flowers have exposed anthers and stigma while cleistogamous flowers do not open", "Chasmogamous flowers lack anthers and stigma", "Cleistogamous flowers are always cross-pollinated"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states chasmogamous flowers are 'similar to flowers of other species with exposed anthers and stigma,' while cleistogamous flowers 'do not open at all.' Chasmogamous flowers are NOT always cross-pollinated; they can be self-pollinated too." },

  { id: 79, topic: "Pollination", q: "In cleistogamous flowers, pollination occurs when:", options: ["Insects visit the flower for nectar", "Wind carries pollen from one flower to another", "Anthers dehisce in the flower buds and pollen contacts the stigma", "The flower opens briefly during early morning"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'When anthers dehisce in the flower buds, pollen grains come in contact with the stigma to effect pollination.' This happens within the closed flower, requiring no external agent." },

  { id: 80, topic: "Pollination", q: "Both male and female gametes in flowering plants are:", options: ["Motile and require no external agent", "Non-motile and must be brought together by external agents", "Male gametes are motile but female gametes are non-motile", "Female gametes are motile but male gametes are non-motile"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As both types of gametes are non-motile, they have to be brought together for fertilisation to occur.' This is why pollination by external agents (wind, water, animals) is essential in flowering plants." },

  { id: 81, topic: "Pollination", q: "Consider the following statements:<br>(i) Autogamy is transfer of pollen within the same flower.<br>(ii) Geitonogamy involves a pollinating agent.<br>(iii) Xenogamy is genetically equivalent to geitonogamy.<br>(iv) Cleistogamous flowers ensure assured seed-set.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["(i) only", "(iii) only", "(i) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. Xenogamy involves transfer of pollen from a different plant and brings genetically different pollen, while geitonogamy is genetically similar to autogamy. They are genetically very different. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are all correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 82, topic: "Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Complete autogamy is rather rare in normal open flowers.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Autogamy requires synchrony in pollen release and stigma receptivity, and close proximity of anthers and stigma.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are from NCERT. Complete autogamy is rare in normal open flowers because it requires precise synchrony in pollen release and stigma receptivity, and the anthers and stigma must be positioned close to each other — conditions not always met. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 83, topic: "Pollination", q: "Which of the following plants produces BOTH chasmogamous and cleistogamous flowers?", options: ["Rice and wheat", "Viola and Commelina", "Mango and papaya", "Orchids and watermelon"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically mentions Viola (common pansy), Oxalis, and Commelina as plants producing two types of flowers — chasmogamous (open) and cleistogamous (closed). Rice, wheat, mango, papaya, orchids, and watermelon are not mentioned in this context." },

  // ───── TOPIC: AGENTS OF POLLINATION ─────
  { id: 84, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following statements about agents of pollination:<br>(i) Plants use two abiotic and one biotic agent for pollination.<br>(ii) Majority of plants use abiotic agents for pollination.<br>(iii) Wind and water are the two abiotic agents.<br>(iv) Animals constitute the biotic agent of pollination.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states 'Majority of plants use biotic agents for pollination. Only a small proportion of plants use abiotic agents.' Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are correct — two abiotic (wind, water) and one biotic (animals)." },

  { id: 85, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Wind and water pollinated flowers produce enormous amounts of pollen because:", options: ["They need to attract more pollinators", "Pollen grains reaching the stigma is a chance factor, so compensation is needed for losses", "Their pollen grains are heavier and sticky", "They have multiple ovules in each ovary"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollen grains coming in contact with the stigma is a chance factor in both wind and water pollination. To compensate for these uncertainties and associated loss of pollen grains, the flowers produce enormous amount of pollen.' This is a key concept for NEET." },

  { id: 86, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a characteristic of wind-pollinated flowers?", options: ["Pollen grains are light and non-sticky", "Stamens are well-exposed", "Stigma is large and often feathery", "Flowers are large, colourful and fragrant"], correct: 3, explanation: "Large, colourful and fragrant flowers are characteristics of ANIMAL-pollinated flowers, not wind-pollinated. Wind-pollinated flowers have light, non-sticky pollen, well-exposed stamens, large feathery stigma, and are not colourful or fragrant." },

  { id: 87, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Wind-pollinated flowers often have:<br>(i) A single ovule in each ovary<br>(ii) Numerous flowers packed into an inflorescence<br>(iii) Large, brightly coloured petals<br>(iv) Feathery stigma<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is incorrect — wind-pollinated flowers are NOT colourful. They lack bright petals as they don't need to attract animal pollinators. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct as per NCERT. The corn cob is a classic NCERT example." },

  { id: 88, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In the corn cob, the 'ears' that wave in the wind represent:", options: ["Petals and sepals", "Anthers and filaments", "Stigma and style", "Bracts and bracteoles"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A familiar example is the corn cob — the ears you see are nothing but the stigma and style which wave in the wind to trap pollen grains.' This is a frequently asked factual detail in NEET." },

  { id: 89, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Pollination by water is limited to about:", options: ["10 genera, mostly dicotyledons", "30 genera, mostly monocotyledons", "50 genera, mostly gymnosperms", "100 genera, mostly dicotyledons"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollination by water is quite rare in flowering plants and is limited to about 30 genera, mostly monocotyledons.' This is an important numerical fact for NEET." },

  { id: 90, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Not all aquatic plants use water for pollination.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In a majority of aquatic plants such as water hyacinth and water lily, the flowers emerge above the level of water and are pollinated by insects or wind.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are directly from NCERT. The assertion is true — not all aquatic plants are water-pollinated. The reason correctly explains this by giving examples of water hyacinth and water lily whose flowers emerge above water and are pollinated by insects or wind." },

  { id: 91, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In <i>Vallisneria</i>, pollination occurs by:", options: ["Wind, as flowers emerge above water", "Insects that visit submerged flowers", "Female flowers reaching the surface by long stalks and male flowers/pollen released on the water surface", "Both male and female flowers remain submerged and pollen is carried underwater"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In Vallisneria, the female flower reach the surface of water by the long stalk and the male flowers or pollen grains are released on to the surface of water. They are carried passively by water currents — some of them eventually reach the female flowers and the stigma.'" },

  { id: 92, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In seagrasses, pollination involves:<br>(i) Female flowers remaining submerged in water.<br>(ii) Pollen grains released inside the water.<br>(iii) Pollen grains are long and ribbon-like.<br>(iv) Pollen grains are carried passively inside the water.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are directly from NCERT regarding seagrass pollination. Female flowers remain submerged, pollen is released underwater, pollen grains are long and ribbon-like, and they are carried passively inside water to reach the stigma." },

  { id: 93, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In most water-pollinated species, pollen grains are protected from wetting by:", options: ["A thick sporopollenin layer", "A mucilaginous covering", "A waxy cuticle", "Oil droplets on the surface"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In most of the water-pollinated species, pollen grains are protected from wetting by a mucilaginous covering.' This is distinct from the sporopollenin layer of the exine which provides general resistance." },

  { id: 94, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is common to BOTH wind and water pollinated flowers?", options: ["They are large and brightly coloured", "They produce abundant nectar", "They are not very colourful and do not produce nectar", "They have sticky pollen grains"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Both wind and water pollinated flowers are not very colourful and do not produce nectar.' This is because they don't need to attract animal pollinators. Colourful flowers and nectar production are characteristics of animal-pollinated flowers." },

  { id: 95, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is the dominant biotic pollinating agent?", options: ["Birds", "Bats", "Insects, particularly bees", "Butterflies"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Among the animals, insects, particularly bees are the dominant biotic pollinating agents.' While birds, bats, and butterflies are also pollinators, bees are the most dominant among all biotic agents." },

  { id: 96, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following have been reported as pollinators in some species?<br>(i) Primates (lemurs)<br>(ii) Arboreal rodents<br>(iii) Gecko lizard and garden lizard<br>(iv) Fish<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions that even larger animals such as some primates (lemurs), arboreal (tree-dwelling) rodents, or even reptiles (gecko lizard and garden lizard) have been reported as pollinators. Fish are NOT mentioned as pollinators." },

  { id: 97, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following characteristics of insect-pollinated flowers:<br>(i) Flowers are large, colourful and fragrant<br>(ii) Rich in nectar<br>(iii) When flowers are small, they are clustered into inflorescences<br>(iv) Pollen grains are generally light and dry<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. Pollen grains in animal-pollinated flowers are generally STICKY (not light and dry). Light and non-sticky pollen is a characteristic of WIND-pollinated flowers. This is a very common NEET trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct." },

  { id: 98, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Flowers pollinated by flies and beetles attract these animals by:", options: ["Bright colours and sweet fragrance", "Secreting foul odours", "Producing copious nectar visible from a distance", "Ultrasonic signals"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The flowers pollinated by flies and beetles secrete foul odours to attract these animals.' This is a specific adaptation — flies and beetles are attracted to rotting/decaying smell, so flowers mimic such odours." },

  { id: 99, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "The usual floral rewards offered to animal pollinators are:", options: ["Oils and resins", "Nectar and pollen grains", "Seeds and fruits", "Shelter and warmth only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Nectar and pollen grains are the usual floral rewards.' To sustain animal visits, flowers must provide these rewards. While harvesting rewards, the animal contacts anthers and stigma, facilitating pollination." },

  { id: 100, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> <i>Amorphophallus</i> provides safe places for laying eggs as a floral reward.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> <i>Amorphophallus</i> has the tallest flower, about 6 feet in height.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both statements are true per NCERT. Amorphophallus does provide safe places for egg-laying as a floral reward, and it does have the tallest flower (~6 feet). However, the height of the flower does not explain WHY it provides egg-laying sites. These are two independent facts." },

  { id: 101, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "The mutualistic relationship between <i>Yucca</i> and its moth pollinator involves:<br>(i) The moth deposits its eggs in the locule of the ovary.<br>(ii) The flower gets pollinated by the moth.<br>(iii) The larvae come out as seeds start developing.<br>(iv) Both species can complete their life cycles independently.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. NCERT states that 'both species — moth and the plant — cannot complete their life cycles without each other.' It is an obligate mutualism. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 102, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Floral visitors that consume pollen or nectar without bringing about pollination are called:", options: ["Pollinators", "Pollen/nectar robbers", "Mutualistic partners", "Commensals"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Many insects may consume pollen or the nectar without bringing about pollination. Such floral visitors are referred to as pollen/nectar robbers.' These visitors do not contact both anthers and stigma, so they fail to achieve pollination." },

  { id: 103, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is a fresh water plant pollinated by water?", options: ["Water hyacinth", "Water lily", "Vallisneria", "Lotus"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions Vallisneria and Hydrilla as freshwater plants pollinated by water. Water hyacinth and water lily, despite being aquatic, have flowers that emerge above water and are pollinated by insects or wind — a very important NEET distinction." },

  { id: 104, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is an example of a marine water-pollinated plant?", options: ["Vallisneria", "Hydrilla", "Zostera", "Water hyacinth"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions Zostera as a marine sea-grass that is water-pollinated. Vallisneria and Hydrilla are freshwater water-pollinated plants. Water hyacinth is insect-pollinated despite being aquatic." },

  { id: 105, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "The distribution of some bryophytes and pteridophytes is believed to be limited because:", options: ["They lack proper vascular tissue", "They require water for transport of male gametes and fertilisation", "They cannot tolerate high temperatures", "Their spores are non-viable in dry conditions"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'It is believed, particularly for some bryophytes and pteridophytes, that their distribution is limited because of the need for water for the transport of male gametes and fertilisation.' Water is essential for their sexual reproduction." },

  { id: 106, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is the most common type among abiotic pollinations?", options: ["Pollination by water", "Pollination by wind", "Pollination by gravity", "Pollination by rain"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollination by wind is more common amongst abiotic pollinations.' Water pollination is quite rare (limited to ~30 genera), while wind pollination is common especially in grasses." },

  { id: 107, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Wind pollination is quite common in:", options: ["Orchids", "Grasses", "Roses", "Sunflowers"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Wind-pollination is quite common in grasses.' Grasses have well-exposed stamens, feathery stigma, light non-sticky pollen, and inconspicuous flowers — all adaptations for wind pollination." },

  { id: 108, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following animals mentioned as pollinating agents in NCERT:<br>(i) Bees<br>(ii) Sunbirds and humming birds<br>(iii) Bats<br>(iv) Dolphins<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT lists bees, butterflies, flies, beetles, wasps, ants, moths, birds (sunbirds and humming birds), and bats as common pollinating agents. Dolphins are NOT mentioned as pollinators. Statement (iv) is incorrect." },

  { id: 109, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Flowers of animal-pollinated plants are often specifically adapted for a particular species of animal.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen grains are generally sticky in animal-pollinated flowers so that they adhere to the animal's body.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both statements are true per NCERT. However, sticky pollen is just one of many adaptations — it does not fully explain why flowers are specifically adapted for particular animal species. Specific adaptations include flower shape, colour, scent, reward type, etc. Hence R is true but not the complete explanation of A." },

  { id: 110, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "A visitor to a flower can be confirmed as a pollinator only if it:", options: ["Visits the flower regularly at the same time each day", "Consumes nectar from the flower", "Comes in contact with both the anthers and the stigma", "Stays on the flower for a prolonged period"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Carefully observe if any of the visitors come in contact with the anthers and the stigma as only such visitors can bring about pollination.' Merely visiting or consuming nectar does not make an insect a pollinator — it must contact both reproductive structures." },

  { id: 111, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following pairs of plants is correctly matched with their pollination medium?<br>(a) Water hyacinth — Water pollination<br>(b) Zostera — Water pollination<br>(c) Vallisneria — Insect pollination<br>(d) Corn — Wind pollination", options: ["(a) and (c) only", "(b) and (d) only", "(a) and (d) only", "(b), (c) and (d)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Water hyacinth is NOT water-pollinated — it is insect/wind pollinated (flowers emerge above water). Vallisneria is water-pollinated, NOT insect-pollinated. Zostera (marine seagrass) is water-pollinated and corn is wind-pollinated. Only (b) and (d) are correct." },

  { id: 112, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "When small flowers are present in animal-pollinated plants, they are made conspicuous by:", options: ["Producing extra-large pollen grains", "Clustering into an inflorescence", "Secreting alkaloids to attract animals", "Producing bioluminescence at night"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'When the flowers are small, a number of flowers are clustered into an inflorescence to make them conspicuous.' This clustering increases visibility and attractiveness to animal pollinators." },

  { id: 113, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following comparisons between wind and water pollination:<br>(i) Both involve chance factor in pollen reaching stigma.<br>(ii) Both produce enormous amounts of pollen.<br>(iii) Both have colourful flowers with nectar.<br>(iv) In both, flowers are not very colourful.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states both wind and water pollinated flowers are NOT very colourful and do NOT produce nectar. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct — both involve chance pollination, produce abundant pollen, and lack colour/nectar." },

  { id: 114, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In <i>Yucca</i>, the larvae of the moth emerge from the eggs when:", options: ["The flower is still in bud stage", "The petals have just opened", "The seeds start developing", "The fruit is fully mature and ready to disperse"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The larvae of the moth come out of the eggs as the seeds start developing.' This timing ensures that the larvae have developing seeds as a food source — a perfectly timed mutualistic relationship." },

  { id: 115, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is <b>INCORRECTLY</b> matched?", options: ["Vallisneria — Fresh water, water pollinated", "Zostera — Marine, water pollinated", "Water lily — Aquatic, water pollinated", "Corn — Terrestrial, wind pollinated"], correct: 2, explanation: "Water lily is aquatic BUT it is NOT water-pollinated. NCERT clearly states that in a majority of aquatic plants such as water hyacinth and water lily, flowers emerge above water and are pollinated by insects or wind. This is one of the most important NEET traps in this chapter." },

  { id: 116, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In <i>Vallisneria</i>, pollination occurs on the water surface.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In seagrasses, pollination occurs inside the water with submerged female flowers.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both A and R are true per NCERT. In Vallisneria, the female flower reaches the surface and pollen is released on the surface. In seagrasses, female flowers remain submerged and pollen is released underwater. However, R describes a different mechanism and does not explain A." },

  { id: 117, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Water is a regular mode of transport for male gametes in:<br>(i) Algae<br>(ii) Bryophytes<br>(iii) Pteridophytes<br>(iv) Angiosperms<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(iii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Water is a regular mode of transport for the male gametes among the lower plant groups such as algae, bryophytes and pteridophytes.' In angiosperms, water pollination is quite rare (limited to ~30 genera). So statement (iv) is incorrect." },

  { id: 118, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following statements about pollen grains in water-pollinated seagrasses is correct?", options: ["They are spherical and heavy", "They are long, ribbon-like and carried passively in water", "They are light and carried by wind above water surface", "They are sticky and attach to aquatic insects"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollen grains in many such species are long, ribbon like and they are carried passively inside the water.' This ribbon-like shape is an adaptation for underwater transport in seagrasses." },

  // ───── TOPIC: OUTBREEDING DEVICES ─────
  { id: 119, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Consider the following statements about outbreeding devices:<br>(i) Majority of flowering plants produce hermaphrodite flowers.<br>(ii) Continued self-pollination results in inbreeding depression.<br>(iii) Flowering plants have developed devices to discourage cross-pollination.<br>(iv) Outbreeding devices encourage cross-pollination.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states flowering plants have developed devices to DISCOURAGE SELF-POLLINATION and ENCOURAGE cross-pollination — not discourage cross-pollination. This is a classic reversal trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct." },

  { id: 120, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a device to prevent self-pollination as described in NCERT?", options: ["Non-synchronisation of pollen release and stigma receptivity", "Different positions of anther and stigma in the same flower", "Self-incompatibility", "Production of bisexual flowers"], correct: 3, explanation: "Production of bisexual (hermaphrodite) flowers actually PROMOTES the chances of self-pollination, not prevents it. The outbreeding devices mentioned in NCERT are: (1) non-synchrony of pollen release and stigma receptivity, (2) different positions of anther and stigma, (3) self-incompatibility, and (4) production of UNISEXUAL flowers." },

  { id: 121, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Self-incompatibility prevents self-pollination by:", options: ["Preventing pollen formation in the anther", "Causing degeneration of ovules before fertilisation", "Inhibiting pollen germination or pollen tube growth in the pistil", "Releasing toxic substances that kill pollen grains"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Self-incompatibility is a genetic mechanism and prevents self-pollen from fertilising the ovules by inhibiting pollen germination or pollen tube growth in the pistil.' It does not prevent pollen formation or destroy ovules." },

  { id: 122, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Self-incompatibility prevents fertilisation by self-pollen from:<br>(i) The same flower<br>(ii) Other flowers of the same plant<br>(iii) Flowers of a different plant of the same species<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states self-incompatibility 'prevents self-pollen (from the same flower or other flowers of the same plant) from fertilising the ovules.' It does NOT prevent pollen from a different plant of the same species — that would be cross-pollination which is desired. Only (i) and (ii) are correct." },

  { id: 123, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In monoecious plants like castor and maize, autogamy is prevented but geitonogamy is not.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Monoecious plants bear both male and female flowers on the same plant.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and R explains A. Since male and female flowers are separate (unisexual), self-pollination within the same flower (autogamy) is impossible. But since both types of flowers are on the same plant, pollen can transfer between them (geitonogamy). R correctly explains why autogamy is prevented but geitonogamy is not." },

  { id: 124, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Dioecy prevents:", options: ["Only autogamy", "Only geitonogamy", "Both autogamy and geitonogamy", "Neither autogamy nor geitonogamy"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In several species such as papaya, male and female flowers are present on different plants (dioecy). This condition prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy.' Since each plant is either entirely male or entirely female, neither self-pollination within the same flower nor between flowers of the same plant is possible." },

  { id: 125, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following is an example of a dioecious plant?", options: ["Maize", "Castor", "Papaya", "Pea"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions papaya as an example of a dioecious plant where male and female flowers are present on different plants. Maize and castor are monoecious (both types on the same plant). Pea has bisexual flowers." },

  { id: 126, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Consider the following devices and their effects:<br>(a) Non-synchrony of pollen release and stigma receptivity — prevents autogamy<br>(b) Different positions of anther and stigma — prevents autogamy<br>(c) Self-incompatibility — prevents autogamy and geitonogamy<br>(d) Monoecy — prevents autogamy and geitonogamy<br><br>Which are correctly matched?", options: ["(a), (b) and (c) only", "(a) and (b) only", "(a), (b) and (d) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (d) is INCORRECT. Monoecy (as in castor, maize) prevents autogamy but NOT geitonogamy — pollen can still transfer between male and female flowers on the same plant. Only dioecy prevents both. Statements (a), (b) and (c) are correctly matched per NCERT." },

  { id: 127, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Non-synchronisation of pollen release and stigma receptivity can occur in two ways:<br>(i) Pollen is released before the stigma becomes receptive.<br>(ii) Stigma becomes receptive much before the release of pollen.<br><br>These conditions are referred to as:", options: ["Protandry and protogyny respectively", "Protogyny and protandry respectively", "Dichogamy in both cases", "Herkogamy in both cases"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions both conditions: pollen released before stigma receptivity, or stigma receptive before pollen release. Both represent temporal separation of male and female maturity, collectively known as dichogamy. Both are forms of non-synchrony that prevent autogamy." },

  { id: 128, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following correctly describes self-incompatibility?", options: ["It is a morphological barrier to cross-pollination", "It is a genetic mechanism that prevents self-pollen from fertilising the ovules", "It is a physical barrier created by different anther-stigma positions", "It is an ecological mechanism involving pollinator specificity"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Self-incompatibility is a genetic mechanism and prevents self-pollen from fertilising the ovules.' It is genetic (not morphological, physical, or ecological) and acts by inhibiting pollen germination or pollen tube growth." },

  { id: 129, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following pairs of plants are monoecious?", options: ["Papaya and maize", "Castor and maize", "Papaya and castor", "Papaya and pea"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions castor and maize as monoecious plants (both male and female flowers on the same plant). Papaya is dioecious (male and female flowers on different plants). Pea has bisexual flowers." },

  { id: 130, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Different positioning of anther and stigma in a flower prevents autogamy.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> When anther and stigma are placed at different positions, pollen cannot come in contact with the stigma of the same flower.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and directly from NCERT: 'In some other species, the anther and stigma are placed at different positions so that the pollen cannot come in contact with the stigma of the same flower.' R correctly and completely explains A." },

  { id: 131, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Inbreeding depression is the result of:", options: ["Continuous cross-pollination between different species", "Continued self-pollination over generations", "Pollination by multiple agents simultaneously", "Failure of pollen tube growth in the style"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Continued self-pollination result in inbreeding depression.' This is the reduction in fitness and vigour due to increased homozygosity from repeated self-pollination. Outbreeding devices evolved to prevent this." },

  { id: 132, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Consider the following:<br>Plant A — Bears unisexual flowers, both male and female on the same plant.<br>Plant B — Bears unisexual flowers, male and female on different plants.<br><br>Which of the following is correct?", options: ["Plant A prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy; Plant B prevents only autogamy", "Plant A prevents only autogamy; Plant B prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy", "Both prevent autogamy and geitonogamy", "Neither prevents autogamy"], correct: 1, explanation: "Plant A is monoecious — prevents autogamy but not geitonogamy (pollen can still transfer between flowers of the same plant). Plant B is dioecious — prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy (each plant bears only one type of flower). This is directly from NCERT." },

  { id: 133, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "How many outbreeding devices are specifically mentioned in NCERT to discourage self-pollination?", options: ["Two", "Three", "Four", "Five"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT describes four outbreeding devices: (1) Non-synchrony of pollen release and stigma receptivity, (2) Different positions of anther and stigma, (3) Self-incompatibility, and (4) Production of unisexual flowers (monoecy and dioecy)." },

  // ───── TOPIC: POLLEN-PISTIL INTERACTION ─────
  { id: 134, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Pollen-pistil interaction involves all of the following events <b>EXCEPT</b>:", options: ["Pollen deposition on the stigma", "Pollen recognition by the pistil", "Pollen tube entry into the ovule", "Fusion of male gamete with the egg cell"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states: 'All these events — from pollen deposition on the stigma until pollen tubes enter the ovule — are together referred to as pollen-pistil interaction.' Fusion of gametes (fertilisation) occurs AFTER pollen-pistil interaction and is a separate event." },

  { id: 135, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The pistil recognises pollen as compatible or incompatible through:", options: ["Physical shape matching between pollen and stigma", "Chemical components of the pollen interacting with those of the pistil", "Electrical signals between pollen and stigma", "Temperature sensitivity of the pollen grain"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'This dialogue is mediated by chemical components of the pollen interacting with those of the pistil.' The recognition, acceptance or rejection is based on a continuous chemical dialogue between pollen grain and pistil." },

  { id: 136, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "If the pistil recognises pollen as incompatible, it rejects the pollen by:<br>(i) Preventing pollen germination on the stigma<br>(ii) Preventing pollen tube growth in the style<br>(iii) Dissolving the pollen grain using enzymes<br><br>Which of the above are correct as per NCERT?", options: ["(i) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions two mechanisms of rejection: 'the pistil rejects the pollen by preventing pollen germination on the stigma or the pollen tube growth in the style.' Dissolving the pollen grain by enzymes is NOT mentioned in NCERT." },

  { id: 137, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "After compatible pollination, the pollen grain germinates on the stigma and produces a pollen tube through:", options: ["The intine layer", "One of the germ pores", "The sporopollenin layer", "A crack in the exine"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Following compatible pollination, the pollen grain germinates on the stigma to produce a pollen tube through one of the germ pores.' Germ pores are apertures where sporopollenin is absent, allowing pollen tube emergence." },

  { id: 138, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The correct pathway of the pollen tube from stigma to the embryo sac is:", options: ["Stigma → Style → Ovary → Micropyle → Synergid", "Stigma → Ovary → Style → Micropyle → Egg cell", "Style → Stigma → Ovary → Chalaza → Synergid", "Stigma → Style → Ovary → Chalaza → Antipodal"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT describes: 'Pollen tube grows through the tissues of the stigma and style and reaches the ovary.' Then 'enters the ovule through the micropyle and then enters one of the synergids through the filiform apparatus.' The correct sequence is Stigma → Style → Ovary → Micropyle → Synergid." },

  { id: 139, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "In plants that shed pollen at the 2-celled stage, the two male gametes are formed:", options: ["Inside the anther before pollen shedding", "During the growth of the pollen tube in the stigma", "After the pollen tube enters the ovule", "Inside the embryo sac after fertilisation"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In such plants, the generative cell divides and forms the two male gametes during the growth of pollen tube in the stigma.' In 3-celled pollen, the male gametes are already formed before shedding." },

  { id: 140, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The filiform apparatus of synergids guides the entry of the pollen tube.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> The filiform apparatus is present at the micropylar part of the synergids.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. The filiform apparatus guides pollen tube entry BECAUSE it is positioned at the micropylar part of the synergids — exactly where the pollen tube enters through the micropyle. Its micropylar position enables it to guide the incoming pollen tube, making R the correct explanation of A." },

  { id: 141, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "In plants that shed pollen at the 3-celled stage, the pollen tubes carry:", options: ["Only the vegetative cell nucleus", "The generative cell which later divides", "Two male gametes from the beginning", "One male gamete and one vegetative cell"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In plants which shed pollen in the three-celled condition, pollen tubes carry the two male gametes from the beginning.' The generative cell has already divided before shedding in these plants." },

  { id: 142, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Pollen germination can be studied in the laboratory by placing pollen grains on:", options: ["Plain distilled water on a slide", "A drop of sugar solution (about 10%) on a glass slide", "A drop of acid solution on a slide", "A dry glass slide without any medium"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'You can easily study pollen germination by dusting some pollen from flowers on a glass slide containing a drop of sugar solution (about 10 per cent).' Sugar solution provides osmotic support and nutrients for pollen tube growth." },

  { id: 143, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Which of the following flowers is mentioned in NCERT for studying pollen germination?<br>(i) Pea<br>(ii) Chickpea<br>(iii) Crotalaria<br>(iv) Rose<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions pea, chickpea, Crotalaria, balsam and Vinca as suitable flowers for studying pollen germination. Rose is NOT mentioned in this context." },

  { id: 144, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Emasculation is the process of:", options: ["Covering flowers with a bag to prevent contamination", "Removal of anthers from the flower bud before anther dehiscence", "Dusting desired pollen grains on the stigma", "Removal of petals and sepals from the flower"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT defines emasculation as: 'removal of anthers from the flower bud before the anther dehisces using a pair of forceps.' This is done in the female parent bearing bisexual flowers to prevent self-pollination in artificial hybridisation." },

  { id: 145, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The correct sequence of steps in artificial hybridisation using bisexual flowers is:", options: ["Bagging → Emasculation → Pollination → Rebagging", "Emasculation → Bagging → Pollination (when stigma is receptive) → Rebagging", "Pollination → Emasculation → Bagging → Rebagging", "Emasculation → Pollination → Bagging → Rebagging"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT describes: First, emasculation (removal of anthers) → then bagging (covering with butter paper bag) → when stigma attains receptivity, pollination with desired pollen → rebagging → fruits allowed to develop. This sequence ensures no contamination." },

  { id: 146, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Bagging in artificial hybridisation involves:", options: ["Covering emasculated flowers with a plastic bag to increase temperature", "Covering emasculated flowers with a bag of suitable size (generally butter paper) to prevent unwanted pollen contamination", "Wrapping anthers with paper to collect pollen", "Covering the entire plant with a net to prevent insect visits"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Emasculated flowers have to be covered with a bag of suitable size, generally made up of butter paper, to prevent contamination of its stigma with unwanted pollen. This process is called bagging.'" },

  { id: 147, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "If the female parent produces unisexual flowers, which step of artificial hybridisation is NOT required?", options: ["Bagging", "Emasculation", "Pollination with desired pollen", "Rebagging"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'If the female parent produces unisexual flowers, there is no need for emasculation.' Since unisexual female flowers lack anthers, there is nothing to emasculate. However, bagging is still necessary to prevent unwanted pollen contamination." },

  { id: 148, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Consider the following statements about pollen-pistil interaction:<br>(i) Pollination guarantees the transfer of compatible pollen.<br>(ii) The pistil can recognise compatible and incompatible pollen.<br>(iii) The recognition is mediated by chemical components of pollen and pistil.<br>(iv) Pollen-pistil interaction is a dynamic process.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (i) is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'Pollination does not guarantee the transfer of the right type of pollen.' Often wrong pollen (from other species or self-incompatible pollen) also lands on the stigma. Statements (ii), (iii) and (iv) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 149, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Knowledge of pollen-pistil interaction can help plant breeders manipulate incompatible pollinations to get desired hybrids.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen-pistil interaction involves chemical recognition that can potentially be modified.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. NCERT states: 'The knowledge gained in this area would help the plant breeder in manipulating pollen-pistil interaction, even in incompatible pollinations, to get desired hybrids.' Since the interaction is chemical, understanding and modifying these chemical signals can overcome incompatibility. R explains A." },

  { id: 150, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The pollen tube enters the ovule through the micropyle and then enters:", options: ["The egg cell directly", "One of the antipodal cells", "The central cell containing polar nuclei", "One of the synergids through the filiform apparatus"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollen tube, after reaching the ovary, enters the ovule through the micropyle and then enters one of the synergids through the filiform apparatus.' The pollen tube does NOT directly enter the egg cell or central cell." },

  { id: 151, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "After about 15–30 minutes of placing pollen on sugar solution, one can observe under the microscope:", options: ["Pollen grains dividing into microspores", "Pollen tubes coming out of the pollen grains", "Pollen grains bursting and releasing gametes", "Pollen grains changing colour"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'After about 15–30 minutes, observe the slide under the low power lens of the microscope. You are likely to see pollen tubes coming out of the pollen grains.' This is a simple experiment to observe pollen germination." },

  { id: 152, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "In artificial hybridisation involving bisexual flowers, which of the following is used for emasculation?", options: ["Scalpel", "Pair of forceps", "Needle", "Brush"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'removal of anthers from the flower bud before the anther dehisces using a pair of forceps is necessary.' Forceps is specifically mentioned as the tool for emasculation." },

  { id: 153, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Which of the following statements about artificial hybridisation in unisexual female flowers is correct?", options: ["Both emasculation and bagging are required", "Only emasculation is required, not bagging", "Only bagging is required, emasculation is not needed", "Neither emasculation nor bagging is required"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'If the female parent produces unisexual flowers, there is no need for emasculation. The female flower buds are bagged before the flowers open.' So only bagging is needed, as unisexual female flowers lack anthers." },

  { id: 154, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Pollen-pistil interaction is described as a 'continuous dialogue' because:", options: ["Pollen and pistil physically fuse immediately upon contact", "Chemical components of pollen and pistil continuously interact for recognition", "The pollen tube sends electrical signals to the stigma", "The pistil actively transports the pollen grain to the ovule"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT describes the interaction as 'a continuous dialogue between pollen grain and the pistil' which is 'mediated by chemical components of the pollen interacting with those of the pistil.' This chemical communication leads to recognition, acceptance or rejection." },

  { id: 155, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Consider the following about the contents of the pollen grain during pollen tube growth:<br>(i) The contents of the pollen grain move into the pollen tube.<br>(ii) In 2-celled pollen, the generative cell divides during pollen tube growth.<br>(iii) In 3-celled pollen, male gametes are carried from the beginning.<br>(iv) The vegetative cell divides to form male gametes in the pollen tube.<br><br>Which are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. The vegetative cell does NOT divide to form male gametes. It is the GENERATIVE cell that divides mitotically to form two male gametes. The vegetative cell is responsible for pollen tube growth. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 156, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The bag used in the bagging technique during artificial hybridisation is generally made of:", options: ["Polythene sheet", "Muslin cloth", "Butter paper", "Aluminium foil"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT specifically states: 'Emasculated flowers have to be covered with a bag of suitable size, generally made up of butter paper.' Butter paper is permeable to air but prevents unwanted pollen contamination." },

  { id: 157, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Pollination does not guarantee the transfer of the right type of pollen.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen of the wrong type from other species or self-incompatible pollen can also land on the stigma.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are true and directly from NCERT. The reason correctly explains the assertion — pollination cannot guarantee compatible pollen transfer because wrong pollen (from other species or same plant in self-incompatible species) can also land on the stigma." },

  { id: 158, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "After pollination with desired pollen in artificial hybridisation, the flowers are:", options: ["Left open for natural development", "Emasculated again", "Rebagged and fruits allowed to develop", "Transferred to tissue culture medium"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'mature pollen grains collected from anthers of the male parent are dusted on the stigma, and the flowers are rebagged, and the fruits allowed to develop.' Rebagging prevents any further contamination after pollination." },

  // ───── TOPIC: DOUBLE FERTILISATION ─────
  { id: 159, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "After entering the synergid, the pollen tube releases the two male gametes into:", options: ["The egg cell directly", "The central cell", "The cytoplasm of the synergid", "The antipodal cells"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'After entering one of the synergids, the pollen tube releases the two male gametes into the cytoplasm of the synergid.' The male gametes are released into the synergid first and then move towards the egg cell and central cell respectively." },

  { id: 160, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Syngamy in angiosperms involves:", options: ["Fusion of one male gamete with two polar nuclei", "Fusion of one male gamete with the egg cell nucleus", "Fusion of two male gametes with the egg cell", "Fusion of one male gamete with one polar nucleus"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'One of the male gametes moves towards the egg cell and fuses with its nucleus thus completing the syngamy.' Syngamy specifically refers to the fusion of one male gamete with the egg cell, producing a diploid zygote." },

  { id: 161, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "The product of triple fusion is:", options: ["A diploid zygote", "A triploid primary endosperm nucleus (PEN)", "A haploid megaspore", "A diploid primary endosperm cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The other male gamete moves towards the two polar nuclei located in the central cell and fuses with them to produce a triploid primary endosperm nucleus (PEN).' Triple fusion involves fusion of one haploid male gamete + two haploid polar nuclei = triploid (3n) PEN." },

  { id: 162, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Triple fusion is so called because it involves:", options: ["Fusion of three male gametes", "Fusion of three haploid nuclei — one male gamete and two polar nuclei", "Three successive fusions between male and female gametes", "Fusion of three egg cells"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As this involves the fusion of three haploid nuclei it is termed triple fusion.' The three nuclei are: one male gamete (n) + two polar nuclei (n + n) = triploid primary endosperm nucleus (3n)." },

  { id: 163, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Double fertilisation involves:<br>(i) Syngamy — fusion of male gamete with egg cell<br>(ii) Triple fusion — fusion of male gamete with two polar nuclei<br>(iii) Both events occur in the embryo sac<br>(iv) This event is unique to gymnosperms<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. NCERT clearly states double fertilisation is 'an event unique to flowering plants' (angiosperms), NOT gymnosperms. This is a very common NEET trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct." },

  { id: 164, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Double fertilisation is an event unique to flowering plants.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In double fertilisation, two types of fusions — syngamy and triple fusion — take place in the embryo sac.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are directly from NCERT. Double fertilisation is unique to angiosperms precisely BECAUSE two fusions (syngamy and triple fusion) occur simultaneously in the embryo sac. This dual fusion event does not occur in any other plant group. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 165, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "The ploidy of the zygote and the primary endosperm nucleus (PEN) respectively are:", options: ["Haploid (n) and diploid (2n)", "Diploid (2n) and triploid (3n)", "Triploid (3n) and diploid (2n)", "Diploid (2n) and diploid (2n)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Syngamy: male gamete (n) + egg cell (n) = zygote (2n, diploid). Triple fusion: male gamete (n) + two polar nuclei (n + n) = PEN (3n, triploid). This is a very frequently tested concept in NEET." },

  { id: 166, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "The central cell after triple fusion becomes the:", options: ["Zygote", "Primary endosperm cell (PEC)", "Proembryo", "Antipodal cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The central cell after triple fusion becomes the primary endosperm cell (PEC) and develops into the endosperm.' The zygote is formed from the egg cell after syngamy, not from the central cell." },

  { id: 167, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Match the products of double fertilisation:<br>(a) Syngamy → (i) Primary endosperm nucleus<br>(b) Triple fusion → (ii) Zygote<br><br>Select the correct matching:", options: ["a-(i), b-(ii)", "a-(ii), b-(i)", "a-(i), b-(i)", "a-(ii), b-(ii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Syngamy (fusion of male gamete with egg cell) produces the zygote (2n). Triple fusion (fusion of male gamete with two polar nuclei) produces the primary endosperm nucleus (3n). So a-(ii) and b-(i) is correct." },

  { id: 168, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Consider the fate of the products of double fertilisation:<br>(i) Zygote develops into an embryo.<br>(ii) PEC develops into endosperm.<br>(iii) Synergids develop into cotyledons.<br>(iv) Antipodals develop into seed coat.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Only statements (i) and (ii) are correct per NCERT: 'the primary endosperm cell develops into the endosperm while the zygote develops into an embryo.' Synergids do NOT develop into cotyledons, and antipodals do NOT develop into seed coat. These are NEET traps." },

  { id: 169, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "How many total male gametes are involved in double fertilisation in a single embryo sac?", options: ["One", "Two", "Three", "Four"], correct: 1, explanation: "Two male gametes are involved: one fuses with the egg cell (syngamy) and the other fuses with the two polar nuclei (triple fusion). The pollen tube releases exactly two male gametes into the synergid for double fertilisation." },

  { id: 170, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Which of the following correctly describes the nuclei involved in triple fusion?", options: ["Two male gamete nuclei + one polar nucleus", "One male gamete nucleus + two egg cell nuclei", "One male gamete nucleus + two polar nuclei", "Three polar nuclei fusing together"], correct: 2, explanation: "Triple fusion involves the fusion of ONE male gamete nucleus with TWO polar nuclei in the central cell. Three haploid nuclei (n + n + n) fuse to form the triploid (3n) primary endosperm nucleus." },

  { id: 171, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The zygote formed after syngamy is diploid (2n).<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Syngamy involves the fusion of two haploid nuclei — one male gamete and one egg cell.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. The male gamete (n) fuses with the egg cell (n) to form a diploid zygote (2n). R correctly explains A by describing the haploid nature of both fusing nuclei resulting in the diploid zygote." },

  { id: 172, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Which of the following events occurs first — syngamy or triple fusion?", options: ["Syngamy always occurs first", "Triple fusion always occurs first", "Both syngamy and triple fusion occur simultaneously as part of double fertilisation", "The order depends on the species"], correct: 2, explanation: "Both syngamy and triple fusion occur in the same embryo sac as part of double fertilisation. NCERT describes them as two types of fusions that take place in the embryo sac together, constituting the phenomenon of double fertilisation." },

  // ───── TOPIC: POST-FERTILISATION: STRUCTURES AND EVENTS ─────
  { id: 173, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Post-fertilisation events collectively include:<br>(i) Endosperm development<br>(ii) Embryo development<br>(iii) Maturation of ovule into seed<br>(iv) Maturation of ovary into fruit<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Following double fertilisation, events of endosperm and embryo development, maturation of ovule(s) into seed(s) and ovary into fruit, are collectively termed post-fertilisation events.' All four are correct." },

  { id: 174, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which development precedes the other — endosperm or embryo?", options: ["Embryo development precedes endosperm development", "Endosperm development precedes embryo development", "Both develop simultaneously", "There is no fixed order"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Endosperm development precedes embryo development.' This is an adaptation to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo. Most zygotes divide only after a certain amount of endosperm is formed." },

  { id: 175, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The primary endosperm cell (PEC) divides to form:", options: ["A diploid endosperm tissue", "A haploid endosperm tissue", "A triploid endosperm tissue", "A tetraploid endosperm tissue"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The primary endosperm cell divides repeatedly and forms a triploid endosperm tissue.' The PEC is triploid (3n) because it is formed from triple fusion, so the endosperm tissue derived from it is also triploid." },

  { id: 176, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In the most common type of endosperm development, the PEN undergoes:", options: ["Immediate cellularisation after first division", "Successive nuclear divisions to give rise to free nuclei (free-nuclear endosperm)", "Meiotic divisions to form haploid endosperm", "A single division to form two cells"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In the most common type of endosperm development, the PEN undergoes successive nuclear divisions to give rise to free nuclei. This stage of endosperm development is called free-nuclear endosperm.' Cell wall formation occurs subsequently." },

  { id: 177, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The coconut water from tender coconut represents:", options: ["Cellular endosperm", "Free-nuclear endosperm", "Nucellus tissue", "Embryo sac fluid"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The coconut water from tender coconut that you are familiar with, is nothing but free-nuclear endosperm (made up of thousands of nuclei).' The surrounding white kernel is the cellular endosperm." },

  { id: 178, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The white kernel of coconut represents:", options: ["Free-nuclear endosperm", "Cellular endosperm", "Nucellus", "Embryo"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'the surrounding white kernel is the cellular endosperm.' This is distinct from coconut water which is free-nuclear endosperm. Both are types of endosperm but at different stages of development. This is a favourite NEET question." },

  { id: 179, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In which of the following plants is the endosperm completely consumed by the developing embryo before seed maturation?<br>(i) Pea<br>(ii) Groundnut<br>(iii) Beans<br>(iv) Castor<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Endosperm may either be completely consumed by the developing embryo (e.g., pea, groundnut, beans) before seed maturation.' Castor is an example where endosperm PERSISTS in the mature seed. Statement (iv) is incorrect." },

  { id: 180, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In castor and coconut, the endosperm persists in the mature seed.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In these plants, the endosperm is not completely consumed by the developing embryo and is used up during seed germination.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT: 'Endosperm may persist in the mature seed (e.g. castor and coconut) and be used up during seed germination.' R correctly explains A — the endosperm persists because it is not consumed during development, and it is later used during germination." },

  { id: 181, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The embryo develops at which end of the embryo sac?", options: ["Chalazal end", "Micropylar end", "Central region", "Lateral side"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Embryo develops at the micropylar end of the embryo sac where the zygote is situated.' The egg cell (and thus the zygote after syngamy) is located at the micropylar end as part of the egg apparatus." },

  { id: 182, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Most zygotes divide only after a certain amount of endosperm is formed. This is an adaptation to:", options: ["Delay embryo development until favourable conditions", "Provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo", "Prevent polyspermy", "Allow the seed coat to develop first"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Most zygotes divide only after certain amount of endosperm is formed. This is an adaptation to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo.' The endosperm tissue provides reserve food for embryo development." },

  { id: 183, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The correct sequence of stages in dicotyledonous embryo development (embryogeny) is:", options: ["Zygote → Globular → Heart-shaped → Proembryo → Mature embryo", "Zygote → Proembryo → Heart-shaped → Globular → Mature embryo", "Zygote → Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature embryo", "Zygote → Heart-shaped → Globular → Proembryo → Mature embryo"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The zygote gives rise to the proembryo and subsequently to the globular, heart-shaped and mature embryo.' The correct sequence is: Zygote → Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature embryo." },

  { id: 184, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "A typical dicotyledonous embryo consists of:", options: ["An embryonal axis and one cotyledon", "An embryonal axis and two cotyledons", "Two embryonal axes and two cotyledons", "An embryonal axis, two cotyledons and a scutellum"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A typical dicotyledonous embryo consists of an embryonal axis and two cotyledons.' Monocot embryos have one cotyledon. Scutellum is specific to the grass family monocots." },

  { id: 185, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In a dicotyledonous embryo, the portion of the embryonal axis above the level of cotyledons is called:", options: ["Hypocotyl", "Epicotyl", "Radicle", "Plumule"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The portion of embryonal axis above the level of cotyledons is the epicotyl, which terminates with the plumule or stem tip.' Hypocotyl is BELOW the level of cotyledons. Plumule is the tip of the epicotyl, not the entire portion." },

  { id: 186, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following about the dicotyledonous embryo:<br>(i) Epicotyl terminates with the plumule or stem tip.<br>(ii) Hypocotyl is the cylindrical portion below the level of cotyledons.<br>(iii) Hypocotyl terminates at its lower end in the radicle or root tip.<br>(iv) The root tip is covered with a coleorrhiza.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT for dicots. In dicots, the root tip is covered with a ROOT CAP. Coleorrhiza is an undifferentiated sheath enclosing the radicle in MONOCOTS (grass family). Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 187, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In monocotyledonous embryos of the grass family, the cotyledon is called:", options: ["Coleoptile", "Coleorrhiza", "Scutellum", "Plumule"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In the grass family the cotyledon is called scutellum that is situated towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis.' Coleoptile is the hollow foliar structure enclosing the shoot apex, and coleorrhiza is the sheath enclosing the radicle." },

  { id: 188, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The scutellum in a monocot embryo is situated:", options: ["At the tip of the embryonal axis", "At the base of the embryonal axis", "Towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis", "Surrounding the entire embryonal axis"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'the cotyledon is called scutellum that is situated towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis.' It is laterally positioned, not at the tip or base." },

  { id: 189, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In a monocot embryo (grass family), the radicle and root cap are enclosed in:", options: ["Coleoptile", "Scutellum", "Coleorrhiza", "Root cap only"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'At its lower end, the embryonal axis has the radical and root cap enclosed in an undifferentiated sheath called coleorrhiza.' Coleoptile encloses the shoot apex and leaf primordia, not the radicle." },

  { id: 190, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The coleoptile in a monocot embryo is:", options: ["A sheath enclosing the radicle and root cap", "The single cotyledon of the grass family", "A hollow foliar structure enclosing the shoot apex and leaf primordia", "The endosperm tissue surrounding the embryo"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Epicotyl has a shoot apex and a few leaf primordia enclosed in a hollow foliar structure, the coleoptile.' Coleoptile protects the emerging shoot during germination in grasses." },

  { id: 191, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The early stages of embryo development (embryogeny) are similar in both monocots and dicots.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Both monocot and dicot embryos develop from the zygote at the micropylar end of the embryo sac.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both are true per NCERT: 'Though the seeds differ greatly, the early stages of embryo development (embryogeny) are similar in both monocotyledons and dicotyledons.' However, R states where the embryo develops, not WHY early embryogeny is similar. R does not explain A." },

  { id: 192, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following correctly differentiates a dicot embryo from a monocot embryo?", options: ["Dicot has one cotyledon; monocot has two cotyledons", "Dicot has scutellum; monocot has coleoptile", "Dicot has two cotyledons and root cap covers radicle; monocot has one cotyledon (scutellum) and coleorrhiza encloses radicle", "Dicot has coleorrhiza; monocot has root cap"], correct: 2, explanation: "Dicot embryo: two cotyledons, root tip covered by root cap. Monocot (grass) embryo: one cotyledon called scutellum, radicle and root cap enclosed in coleorrhiza. Options A and D reverse the features — classic NEET traps." },

  { id: 193, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following structures in a monocot embryo:<br>(a) Scutellum — single cotyledon<br>(b) Coleorrhiza — sheath enclosing shoot apex<br>(c) Coleoptile — hollow foliar structure enclosing shoot apex and leaf primordia<br>(d) Epicotyl — portion above scutellum attachment<br><br>Which are correctly matched?", options: ["(a) and (b) only", "(a), (c) and (d) only", "(b) and (d) only", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (b) is INCORRECT. Coleorrhiza encloses the RADICLE and root cap, NOT the shoot apex. The shoot apex is enclosed by the coleoptile. Statements (a), (c) and (d) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 194, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Endosperm is persistent in the mature seed of:<br>(i) Castor<br>(ii) Coconut<br>(iii) Pea<br>(iv) Groundnut<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states endosperm persists in castor and coconut. In pea and groundnut, endosperm is completely consumed before seed maturation. Cereals (wheat, rice, maize) also have persistent endosperm. This is frequently tested in NEET." },

  { id: 195, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The function of endosperm tissue is to:", options: ["Protect the embryo from desiccation", "Provide reserve food materials for the nutrition of the developing embryo", "Form the seed coat", "Produce hormones for fruit development"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The cells of this tissue are filled with reserve food materials and are used for the nutrition of the developing embryo.' The endosperm is the primary nutritive tissue for embryo development." },

  { id: 196, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The free-nuclear endosperm stage is characterised by:", options: ["Nuclear divisions followed by immediate cell wall formation", "Successive nuclear divisions without cell wall formation", "Meiotic divisions of the PEN", "Single nuclear division followed by cellularisation"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The PEN undergoes successive nuclear divisions to give rise to free nuclei. This stage of endosperm development is called free-nuclear endosperm. Subsequently cell wall formation occurs and the endosperm becomes cellular.' So free nuclei form first, then cellularisation occurs." },

  { id: 197, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following is <b>INCORRECTLY</b> matched?", options: ["Epicotyl — portion above cotyledons, terminates with plumule", "Hypocotyl — portion below cotyledons, terminates with radicle", "Plumule — root tip", "Radicle — root tip, covered with root cap in dicots"], correct: 2, explanation: "Plumule is the STEM TIP (shoot apex), NOT the root tip. NCERT states: 'the epicotyl, which terminates with the plumule or stem tip.' The root tip is the radicle. This is a common NEET trap where plumule and radicle are interchanged." },

  { id: 198, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Endosperm development precedes embryo development.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Endosperm provides assured nutrition to the developing embryo.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. Endosperm develops first to ensure that nutrition is available for the developing embryo. NCERT states: 'Most zygotes divide only after certain amount of endosperm is formed. This is an adaptation to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo.' R correctly explains A." },

  // ───── TOPIC: SEED ─────
  { id: 199, topic: "Seed", q: "A seed is often described as:", options: ["A fertilised embryo sac", "A fertilised ovule", "A mature ovary", "A fertilised pollen grain"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In angiosperms, the seed is the final product of sexual reproduction. It is often described as a fertilised ovule.' A mature ovary becomes the fruit, not the seed." },

  { id: 200, topic: "Seed", q: "A seed typically consists of:<br>(i) Seed coat(s)<br>(ii) Cotyledon(s)<br>(iii) Embryo axis<br>(iv) Pericarp<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A seed typically consists of seed coat(s), cotyledon(s) and an embryo axis.' Pericarp is the wall of the FRUIT (developed from the ovary wall), NOT a part of the seed. Statement (iv) is incorrect — a very common NEET trap." },

  { id: 201, topic: "Seed", q: "Non-albuminous (ex-albuminous) seeds are characterised by:", options: ["Having persistent endosperm in the mature seed", "Having no residual endosperm as it is completely consumed during embryo development", "Having persistent nucellus (perisperm)", "Lacking cotyledons"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Non-albuminous seeds have no residual endosperm as it is completely consumed during embryo development (e.g., pea, groundnut).' Albuminous seeds retain part of the endosperm." },

  { id: 202, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following are examples of albuminous seeds?<br>(i) Wheat<br>(ii) Pea<br>(iii) Maize<br>(iv) Castor<br>(v) Groundnut<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "(ii) and (v) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states albuminous seeds retain endosperm: 'e.g., wheat, maize, barley, castor.' Pea and groundnut are non-albuminous (endosperm completely consumed). So (i), (iii) and (iv) are albuminous." },

  { id: 203, topic: "Seed", q: "Perisperm is:", options: ["Remnants of endosperm in the mature seed", "Residual, persistent nucellus in some seeds", "The outer layer of the seed coat", "The food reserve in cotyledons"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Occasionally, in some seeds such as black pepper and beet, remnants of nucellus are also persistent. This residual, persistent nucellus is the perisperm.' It is NOT endosperm or seed coat — a key distinction for NEET." },

  { id: 204, topic: "Seed", q: "Perisperm is found in seeds of:", options: ["Pea and groundnut", "Wheat and maize", "Black pepper and beet", "Castor and coconut"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT specifically mentions: 'in some seeds such as black pepper and beet, remnants of nucellus are also persistent. This residual, persistent nucellus is the perisperm.' This is a direct factual question frequently asked in NEET." },

  { id: 205, topic: "Seed", q: "The seed coat develops from:", options: ["The wall of the ovary", "The integuments of the ovule", "The nucellus of the ovule", "The endosperm tissue"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Integuments of ovules harden as tough protective seed coats.' The ovary wall develops into the pericarp (fruit wall), not the seed coat. This is an important distinction between seed and fruit structures." },

  { id: 206, topic: "Seed", q: "The micropyle in a mature seed functions to:", options: ["Allow dispersal of seeds by wind", "Facilitate entry of oxygen and water during germination", "Allow the embryo to emerge during fruit development", "Provide attachment to the placenta"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The micropyle remains as a small pore in the seed coat. This facilitates entry of oxygen and water into the seed during germination.' The micropyle that existed in the ovule persists as a pore in the seed coat." },

  { id: 207, topic: "Seed", q: "As the seed matures, its water content is reduced to approximately:", options: ["1–5 per cent moisture by mass", "10–15 per cent moisture by mass", "25–30 per cent moisture by mass", "40–50 per cent moisture by mass"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As the seed matures, its water content is reduced and seeds become relatively dry (10-15 per cent moisture by mass).' This low moisture content is crucial for seed dormancy and storage." },

  { id: 208, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following statements about seed dormancy:<br>(i) The general metabolic activity of the embryo slows down as the seed matures.<br>(ii) The embryo may enter a state of inactivity called dormancy.<br>(iii) Seeds germinate only if favourable conditions are available.<br>(iv) Dormancy is irreversible and seeds cannot germinate once dormant.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. Dormancy is NOT irreversible. NCERT states: 'if favourable conditions are available (adequate moisture, oxygen and suitable temperature), they germinate.' Seeds can break dormancy under favourable conditions. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct." },

  { id: 209, topic: "Seed", q: "The conditions required for seed germination include:<br>(i) Adequate moisture<br>(ii) Oxygen<br>(iii) Suitable temperature<br>(iv) Complete darkness<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(iii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions three conditions: 'adequate moisture, oxygen and suitable temperature.' Complete darkness is NOT mentioned as a requirement for germination. Some seeds may require light, but NCERT specifically lists only these three factors." },

  { id: 210, topic: "Seed", q: "The transformation of ovules into seeds and ovary into fruit proceeds:", options: ["Sequentially — seeds form first, then fruit", "Sequentially — fruit forms first, then seeds", "Simultaneously", "Independently without any connection"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'the transformation of ovules into seeds and ovary into fruit proceeds simultaneously.' As ovules mature into seeds, the ovary simultaneously develops into the fruit." },

  { id: 211, topic: "Seed", q: "The wall of the ovary develops into:", options: ["Seed coat", "Testa", "Pericarp", "Endosperm"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The wall of the ovary develops into the wall of fruit called pericarp.' Seed coat develops from integuments, not from the ovary wall. This ovary wall → pericarp distinction is frequently tested in NEET." },

  { id: 212, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is correctly matched?<br>(a) Fleshy fruits — Guava, orange, mango<br>(b) Dry fruits — Groundnut, mustard<br>(c) False fruits — Apple, strawberry, cashew<br>(d) True fruits — Develop from thalamus", options: ["(a), (b) and (c) only", "(a) and (b) only", "(a), (b), (c) and (d)", "(b) and (d) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (d) is INCORRECT. True fruits develop from the OVARY only, not from the thalamus. NCERT states: 'Most fruits develop only from the ovary and are called true fruits.' False fruits involve thalamus contribution. Statements (a), (b) and (c) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 213, topic: "Seed", q: "False fruits are formed when:", options: ["Fruits develop without fertilisation", "The thalamus also contributes to fruit formation along with the ovary", "Only the ovary develops into the fruit", "Seeds develop without endosperm"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'in a few species such as apple, strawberry, cashew, etc., the thalamus also contributes to fruit formation. Such fruits are called false fruits.' In true fruits, only the ovary forms the fruit." },

  { id: 214, topic: "Seed", q: "Parthenocarpic fruits are:", options: ["Fruits that develop from the thalamus", "Fruits that develop without fertilisation", "Fruits that contain many seeds", "Fruits that develop from multiple ovaries"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'there are a few species in which fruits develop without fertilisation. Such fruits are called parthenocarpic fruits.' Banana is a classic example. Parthenocarpy can be induced through growth hormones." },

  { id: 215, topic: "Seed", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Parthenocarpic fruits are seedless.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Parthenocarpic fruits develop without fertilisation, so no zygote or embryo is formed.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. Since parthenocarpic fruits develop without fertilisation, no zygote is formed, no embryo develops, and hence no seeds are present. R correctly explains why parthenocarpic fruits are seedless. NCERT also mentions that parthenocarpy can be induced through growth hormones." },

  { id: 216, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is an example of a parthenocarpic fruit?", options: ["Apple", "Mango", "Banana", "Strawberry"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Banana is one such example' of parthenocarpic fruits. Apple and strawberry are examples of false fruits (thalamus contributes). Mango is a true fruit." },

  { id: 217, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following advantages of seeds:<br>(i) Seed formation is more dependable as pollination and fertilisation are independent of water.<br>(ii) Seeds have adaptive strategies for dispersal to new habitats.<br>(iii) Seeds have sufficient food reserves for nourishing young seedlings.<br>(iv) The hard seed coat provides protection to the young embryo.<br>(v) Seeds generate new genetic combinations leading to variations.<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii), (iv) and (v) only", "(i), (ii) and (v) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii), (iv) and (v)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All five advantages are explicitly mentioned in NCERT as advantages of seeds to angiosperms. This is a comprehensive list from the textbook covering dependability, dispersal, nutrition, protection, and genetic variation." },

  { id: 218, topic: "Seed", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Dehydration and dormancy of mature seeds are crucial for agriculture.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> These features allow storage of seeds for use as food throughout the year and for raising crops in the next season.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT: 'Dehydration and dormancy of mature seeds are crucial for storage of seeds which can be used as food throughout the year and also to raise crop in the next season.' R correctly explains why these features are crucial for agriculture." },

  { id: 219, topic: "Seed", q: "The oldest viable seed on record belongs to:", options: ["Phoenix dactylifera (date palm) — 2000 years old", "Lupinus arcticus — estimated 10,000 years old", "Nelumbo nucifera (lotus) — 1000 years old", "Oryza sativa (rice) — 5000 years old"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The oldest is that of a lupine, Lupinus arcticus excavated from Arctic Tundra. The seed germinated and flowered after an estimated record of 10,000 years of dormancy.' Phoenix dactylifera (2000 years) is mentioned as a recent record, not the oldest." },

  { id: 220, topic: "Seed", q: "A 2000-year-old viable seed of <i>Phoenix dactylifera</i> was discovered during:", options: ["Deep sea exploration in the Pacific Ocean", "Archaeological excavation at King Herod's palace near the Dead Sea", "Mining operations in South Africa", "Glacier melting in the Arctic Tundra"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A recent record of 2000 years old viable seed is of the date palm, Phoenix dactylifera discovered during the archeological excavation at King Herod's palace near the Dead Sea.' This is a specific factual detail from NCERT." },

  { id: 221, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following plants produce fruits containing very large number of seeds?<br>(i) Orchids<br>(ii) Orobanche<br>(iii) Striga<br>(iv) Mango<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions: 'Orchid fruits are one such category and each fruit contain thousands of tiny seeds. Similar is the case in fruits of some parasitic species such as Orobanche and Striga.' Mango has typically one seed per fruit, not many." },

  { id: 222, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following correctly differentiates a false fruit from a true fruit?", options: ["False fruits develop from the ovary only; true fruits involve the thalamus", "False fruits involve the thalamus in fruit formation; true fruits develop only from the ovary", "False fruits are always seedless; true fruits always have seeds", "False fruits are parthenocarpic; true fruits are not"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'in a few species such as apple, strawberry, cashew, the thalamus also contributes to fruit formation — such fruits are called false fruits. Most fruits develop only from the ovary and are called true fruits.' Option A reverses the definitions — a classic trap." },

  { id: 223, topic: "Seed", q: "Parthenocarpy can be induced through the application of:", options: ["Antibiotics", "Growth hormones", "Fertilisers", "Enzyme inhibitors"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Parthenocarpy can be induced through the application of growth hormones and such fruits are seedless.' Growth hormones (like auxins) can stimulate fruit development without fertilisation." },

  { id: 224, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following developmental fates:<br>(i) Ovule → Seed<br>(ii) Ovary → Fruit<br>(iii) Ovary wall → Pericarp<br>(iv) Integuments → Seed coat<br>(v) Zygote → Embryo<br>(vi) PEC → Endosperm<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii), (iv) and (v) only", "(iv), (v) and (vi) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii), (iv), (v) and (vi)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All six developmental fates are correct per NCERT: ovule→seed, ovary→fruit, ovary wall→pericarp, integuments→seed coat, zygote→embryo, PEC→endosperm. This comprehensive matching is an important summary for NEET." },

  { id: 225, topic: "Seed", q: "How many eggs are present in an embryo sac?", options: ["One", "Two", "Three", "Four"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT poses the question: 'How many eggs are present in an embryo sac?' The answer is one. The egg apparatus consists of two synergids and ONE egg cell. There is only one egg cell per embryo sac." },

  { id: 226, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following about <i>Ficus</i> is mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["It produces the largest seeds among angiosperms", "It has a tiny seed but develops into a large tree producing billions of seeds", "It is a parasitic plant that depends on other trees for nutrition", "It produces parthenocarpic fruits exclusively"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT asks: 'Have you seen a tiny seed of Ficus? How large is the tree of Ficus developed from that tiny seed. How many billions of seeds does each Ficus tree produce?' This highlights the enormous reproductive capacity from a tiny seed." },

  { id: 227, topic: "Seed", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Seeds generated through sexual reproduction produce new genetic combinations leading to variations.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Sexual reproduction involves meiosis and fusion of gametes from two different parents.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. NCERT states seeds 'Being products of sexual reproduction, they generate new genetic combinations leading to variations.' R correctly explains this — meiosis creates genetic recombination, and fusion of gametes from different parents generates new combinations, leading to variations." },

  { id: 228, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> mentioned as an example of a false fruit in NCERT?", options: ["Apple", "Strawberry", "Cashew", "Banana"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT mentions apple, strawberry and cashew as false fruits (where thalamus contributes to fruit formation). Banana is mentioned as an example of a PARTHENOCARPIC fruit (develops without fertilisation), NOT a false fruit. This is a commonly confused distinction in NEET." },

  { id: 229, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following statements:<br>(i) In most plants, other floral parts degenerate and fall off by the time the fruit develops.<br>(ii) In apple and cashew, the thalamus contributes to fruit formation.<br>(iii) All fruits are results of fertilisation.<br>(iv) Parthenocarpic fruits are seedless.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'Although in most of the species, fruits are the results of fertilisation, there are a few species in which fruits develop without fertilisation.' These are parthenocarpic fruits. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct." },

  { id: 230, topic: "Seed", q: "The cotyledons of the embryo in legumes are generally thick and swollen because:", options: ["They contain the embryonal axis", "They are filled with storage of food reserves", "They contain the endosperm tissue", "They have multiple embryo sacs"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The cotyledons of the embryo are simple structures, generally thick and swollen due to storage of food reserves (as in legumes).' In non-albuminous seeds like legumes, the endosperm is consumed and food is stored in the cotyledons." },

  { id: 231, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is <b>INCORRECTLY</b> matched?", options: ["Non-albuminous seeds — Pea, groundnut", "Albuminous seeds — Wheat, maize, castor", "Perisperm — Persistent nucellus in black pepper", "Parthenocarpic fruit — Apple"], correct: 3, explanation: "Apple is a FALSE FRUIT (thalamus contributes), NOT a parthenocarpic fruit. Banana is the example of parthenocarpy given in NCERT. Options A, B and C are correctly matched per NCERT. This false fruit vs parthenocarpic fruit confusion is a major NEET trap." },

  { id: 232, topic: "Seed", q: "The seed viability period:<br>(i) Varies greatly among species<br>(ii) Can be a few months in some species<br>(iii) Can extend to hundreds of years in some seeds<br>(iv) The record is held by <i>Lupinus arcticus</i> at an estimated 10,000 years<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are from NCERT. Seed viability varies greatly — from a few months to hundreds or thousands of years. The record is Lupinus arcticus at ~10,000 years. Phoenix dactylifera at 2,000 years is also mentioned." },

  { id: 233, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following represents the correct developmental fate?", options: ["Integuments → Pericarp", "Ovary wall → Seed coat", "Ovule → Fruit", "Ovary wall → Pericarp"], correct: 3, explanation: "Ovary wall → Pericarp is correct. Integuments → Seed coat (not pericarp). Ovule → Seed (not fruit). Ovary → Fruit. Students commonly confuse these developmental fates, which is why this is a high-frequency NEET question." },

  // ───── TOPIC: APOMIXIS AND POLYEMBRYONY ─────
  { id: 234, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Apomixis is defined as:", options: ["Production of fruits without fertilisation", "Production of seeds without fertilisation", "Production of pollen without meiosis", "Production of embryo sac without megasporogenesis"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'a few flowering plants have evolved a special mechanism, to produce seeds without fertilisation, called apomixis.' Production of FRUITS without fertilisation is called parthenocarpy, not apomixis. This distinction is a very important NEET trap." },

  { id: 235, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Apomixis is a form of asexual reproduction that mimics sexual reproduction.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In apomixis, seeds are produced without the fusion of gametes but the process still involves seed and embryo formation.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. NCERT states 'apomixis is a form of asexual reproduction that mimics sexual reproduction.' It mimics sexual reproduction because seeds are formed, but it is asexual because fertilisation does not occur. R correctly explains how apomixis mimics sexual reproduction while being asexual." },

  { id: 236, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Apomixis has been reported in some species of:<br>(i) Asteraceae<br>(ii) Grasses<br>(iii) Citrus<br>(iv) Mango<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT mentions Asteraceae and grasses as having evolved apomixis, and Citrus and Mango varieties as examples where nucellar cells develop into embryos (a form of apomixis). All four are correct." },

  { id: 237, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "In apomictic seed development, one mechanism involves:", options: ["A haploid egg cell formed after normal meiosis fusing with a male gamete", "A diploid egg cell formed without reduction division developing into an embryo without fertilisation", "Two male gametes fusing with each other", "The endosperm developing directly into an embryo"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In some species, the diploid egg cell is formed without reduction division and develops into the embryo without fertilisation.' This is one mechanism of apomixis — the egg cell is diploid (2n) because meiosis does not occur." },

  { id: 238, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "In many Citrus and Mango varieties, apomictic embryos develop from:", options: ["The egg cell after fertilisation", "The synergid cells of the embryo sac", "Nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac", "The antipodal cells at the chalazal end"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'as in many Citrus and Mango varieties, some of the nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac start dividing, protrude into the embryo sac and develop into the embryos.' This is called adventive embryony — a form of apomixis." },

  { id: 239, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Polyembryony refers to:", options: ["Occurrence of more than one embryo sac in an ovule", "Occurrence of more than one embryo in a seed", "Occurrence of more than one egg in an embryo sac", "Occurrence of more than one ovule in an ovary"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Occurrence of more than one embryo in a seed is referred to as polyembryony.' In species like Citrus and Mango, nucellar cells produce additional embryos, resulting in multiple embryos per seed." },

  { id: 240, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Consider the following statements about apomictic embryos:<br>(i) They are genetically identical to the parent plant.<br>(ii) They can be called clones.<br>(iii) They are genetically different from the parent plant.<br>(iv) They show segregation of characters in progeny.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Apomictic embryos develop without fertilisation (no fusion of gametes from two parents), so they are genetically identical to the parent plant and can be called clones. They do NOT show segregation of characters because there is no genetic recombination. Statements (iii) and (iv) are incorrect." },

  { id: 241, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Why is apomixis important for the hybrid seed industry?", options: ["It increases the rate of fertilisation in hybrid plants", "It allows hybrids to produce seeds that maintain hybrid characters without segregation", "It reduces the time needed for pollination", "It increases genetic diversity in hybrid progeny"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'If these hybrids are made into apomicts, there is no segregation of characters in the hybrid progeny. Then the farmers can keep on using the hybrid seeds to raise new crop year after year.' Apomixis preserves hybrid vigour without segregation." },

  { id: 242, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Consider the following problems associated with hybrid seed production:<br>(i) Hybrid seeds have to be produced every year.<br>(ii) Seeds collected from hybrids show segregation in progeny.<br>(iii) Plants from hybrid seeds do not maintain hybrid characters.<br>(iv) Production of hybrid seeds is costly.<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii) only"], correct: 2, explanation: "All four problems are mentioned in NCERT. Hybrid seeds must be produced every year because progeny from hybrid seeds segregate, do not maintain hybrid characters, and hybrid seed production is expensive. Apomixis can solve all these problems." },

  { id: 243, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> If hybrids are made into apomicts, farmers do not have to buy hybrid seeds every year.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In apomicts, there is no segregation of characters in the hybrid progeny because seeds are produced without fertilisation.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. Since apomictic seeds are produced without fertilisation, no meiosis or gamete fusion occurs, so there is no segregation. This means hybrid characters are maintained in progeny, eliminating the need to buy fresh hybrid seeds every year. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 244, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Which of the following correctly differentiates apomixis from parthenocarpy?", options: ["Apomixis = seed production without fertilisation; Parthenocarpy = fruit production without fertilisation", "Apomixis = fruit production without fertilisation; Parthenocarpy = seed production without fertilisation", "Both refer to seed production without fertilisation", "Both refer to fruit production without fertilisation"], correct: 0, explanation: "Apomixis is the production of SEEDS without fertilisation. Parthenocarpy is the production of FRUITS without fertilisation (resulting in seedless fruits). NCERT itself poses the question: 'What is fruit production without fertilisation called?' to distinguish the two." },

  { id: 245, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "In Citrus, the occurrence of polyembryony is because:", options: ["The egg cell divides multiple times before fertilisation", "Multiple pollen tubes enter the same ovule", "Nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac divide and develop into embryos", "The zygote divides into multiple embryos"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'in many Citrus and Mango varieties some of the nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac start dividing, protrude into the embryo sac and develop into the embryos. In such species each ovule contains many embryos.' This results in polyembryony." },

  { id: 246, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Active research on apomixis aims to:", options: ["Eliminate all hybrid varieties from agriculture", "Understand the genetics of apomixis and transfer apomictic genes into hybrid varieties", "Replace sexual reproduction entirely in all crop plants", "Create genetically modified organisms resistant to all diseases"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'active research is going on in many laboratories around the world to understand the genetics of apomixis and to transfer apomictic genes into hybrid varieties.' The goal is to maintain hybrid vigour without the need for annual hybrid seed production." },

  { id: 247, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a method of apomictic seed development mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["Diploid egg cell formed without reduction division developing into embryo without fertilisation", "Nucellar cells dividing and developing into embryos", "Antipodal cells developing into embryos after triple fusion", "Both A and B are mentioned as methods"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT describes two methods: (1) diploid egg cell forming without meiosis and developing without fertilisation, and (2) nucellar cells developing into embryos (as in Citrus and Mango). Antipodal cells developing into embryos after triple fusion is NOT mentioned in NCERT." },

  { id: 248, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Consider the following:<br>Statement I: Apomixis results in formation of seeds without fertilisation.<br>Statement II: Parthenocarpy results in formation of seedless fruits without fertilisation.<br><br>Which of the above statements is/are correct?", options: ["Statement I only", "Statement II only", "Both Statements I and II", "Neither Statement I nor II"], correct: 2, explanation: "Both statements are correct. Apomixis = seeds without fertilisation (NCERT definition). Parthenocarpy = fruits without fertilisation (seedless, as in banana). NCERT distinguishes these two clearly and both concepts are from the textbook." },

  { id: 249, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "The genetic nature of embryos produced through nucellar embryony (as in Citrus) would be:", options: ["Genetically different from the parent and from each other", "Genetically identical to the parent plant (clones)", "Haploid in nature", "Triploid in nature"], correct: 1, explanation: "Nucellar cells are somatic cells (diploid, 2n) of the parent plant. Embryos arising from nucellar cells through mitotic divisions are genetically identical to the parent — they are clones. No meiosis or fertilisation is involved, so no genetic variation occurs." },

  { id: 250, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "If you squeeze seeds of orange, you would observe:", options: ["A single large embryo", "Many embryos of different sizes and shapes", "Only endosperm tissue", "No embryo as oranges are parthenocarpic"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Take out some seeds of orange and squeeze them. Observe the many embryos of different sizes and shapes from each seed.' This is because Citrus exhibits polyembryony due to nucellar embryony — multiple embryos develop from nucellar cells." },

  { id: 251, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Which of the following statements about hybrid seed production is <b>INCORRECT</b>?", options: ["Cultivation of hybrids has tremendously increased productivity", "Hybrid seeds have to be produced every year", "Seeds from hybrids maintain hybrid characters in progeny", "Production of hybrid seeds is costly"], correct: 2, explanation: "Statement C is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'If the seeds collected from hybrids are sown, the plants in the progeny will segregate and do not maintain hybrid characters.' This is precisely why hybrid seeds must be produced fresh every year — a major limitation that apomixis could solve." },

  { id: 252, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Polyembryony occurs in seeds of Citrus and Mango.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In these species, nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac divide, protrude into the embryo sac and develop into embryos.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and directly from NCERT. Polyembryony in Citrus and Mango occurs because nucellar cells develop into additional embryos alongside the sexually produced embryo. R correctly explains the mechanism behind polyembryony in A." },

  // ───── TOPIC: SUMMARY — COMPREHENSIVE REVISION ─────
  { id: 253, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Consider the following statements about anther structure:<br>(i) A typical anther is bilobed, dithecous and tetrasporangiate.<br>(ii) Four wall layers surround the microsporangium.<br>(iii) Sporogenous tissue lies at the periphery of the microsporangium.<br>(iv) Cells of the sporogenous tissue undergo meiosis to form microspore tetrads.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. The sporogenous tissue lies in the CENTRE of the microsporangium, not at the periphery. The four wall layers (epidermis, endothecium, middle layers, tapetum) are at the periphery. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct." },

  { id: 254, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "The correct sequence of events from pollination to seed formation is:", options: ["Pollination → Double fertilisation → Pollen-pistil interaction → Endosperm development → Embryo development → Seed", "Pollination → Pollen-pistil interaction → Double fertilisation → Endosperm development → Embryo development → Seed", "Double fertilisation → Pollination → Endosperm development → Pollen-pistil interaction → Embryo development → Seed", "Pollen-pistil interaction → Pollination → Double fertilisation → Embryo development → Endosperm development → Seed"], correct: 1, explanation: "The correct NCERT sequence is: Pollination (pollen lands on stigma) → Pollen-pistil interaction (pollen recognition, tube growth through style, entry into ovule) → Double fertilisation (syngamy + triple fusion) → Endosperm development (always precedes embryo) → Embryo development → Seed formation." },

  { id: 255, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Match the following structures with their developmental products:<br>(a) Ovary → (i) Seed<br>(b) Ovule → (ii) Pericarp<br>(c) Ovary wall → (iii) Fruit<br>(d) Integuments → (iv) Seed coat<br><br>Select the correct matching:", options: ["a-(iii), b-(i), c-(ii), d-(iv)", "a-(i), b-(iii), c-(iv), d-(ii)", "a-(ii), b-(iv), c-(iii), d-(i)", "a-(iii), b-(iv), c-(i), d-(ii)"], correct: 0, explanation: "Ovary → Fruit, Ovule → Seed, Ovary wall → Pericarp, Integuments → Seed coat. This is one of the most frequently tested matching questions in NEET from this chapter." },

  { id: 256, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Consider the following about the female gametophyte:<br>(i) It is 7-celled and 8-nucleate at maturity.<br>(ii) The egg apparatus is at the micropylar end.<br>(iii) Antipodals are at the micropylar end.<br>(iv) The central cell has two polar nuclei.<br><br>Which are <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["(i) only", "(iii) only", "(i) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. Antipodals are at the CHALAZAL end, not the micropylar end. The egg apparatus (2 synergids + 1 egg cell) is at the micropylar end. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct per NCERT summary." },

  { id: 257, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "In the NCERT summary, the term 'archesporium' is mentioned in the context of:", options: ["The microsporangium in the anther", "The nucellus of the ovule where the megaspore mother cell differentiates", "The tapetum layer", "The pollen grain wall"], correct: 1, explanation: "The NCERT summary states: 'The central tissue is the nucellus in which the archesporium differentiates. A cell of the archesporium, the megaspore mother cell divides meiotically.' The archesporium is the tissue in the nucellus from which the MMC differentiates." },

  { id: 258, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "The pollen tube, after entering the ovule, discharges the two male gametes in:", options: ["The egg cell", "The central cell", "One of the synergids", "One of the antipodals"], correct: 2, explanation: "The NCERT summary states: 'the resulting pollen tube grow through the style, enter the ovules and finally discharges two male gametes in one of the synergids.' The male gametes are released into the synergid first, then move to the egg cell and central cell." },

  { id: 259, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following statements from the NCERT summary is correct about double fertilisation?", options: ["Two fusion events occur — syngamy and triple fusion — producing diploid zygote and diploid PEN", "Two fusion events occur — syngamy and triple fusion — producing diploid zygote and triploid PEN", "Three fusion events occur — syngamy, triple fusion and polar fusion", "One fusion event occurs — syngamy — producing a triploid zygote"], correct: 1, explanation: "The NCERT summary states: 'Angiosperms exhibit double fertilisation because two fusion events occur in each embryo sac, namely syngamy and triple fusion. The products of these fusions are the diploid zygote and the triploid primary endosperm nucleus.' Only TWO fusions occur, and PEN is triploid (3n), not diploid." },

  { id: 260, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "According to the NCERT summary, the developing embryo passes through stages in the following order:", options: ["Globular → Proembryo → Heart-shaped → Mature", "Proembryo → Heart-shaped → Globular → Mature", "Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature", "Heart-shaped → Globular → Proembryo → Mature"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT summary states: 'The developing embryo passes through different stages such as the proembryo, globular and heart-shaped stages before maturation.' The correct sequence is Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature embryo." },

  { id: 261, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following statements from the NCERT summary is <b>INCORRECT</b>?", options: ["Formation of endosperm always precedes development of the embryo", "Mature dicotyledonous embryo has two cotyledons and an embryonal axis with epicotyl and hypocotyl", "Embryos of monocotyledons have two cotyledons", "After fertilisation, ovary develops into fruit and ovules develop into seeds"], correct: 2, explanation: "Statement C is INCORRECT. NCERT summary states: 'Embryos of monocotyledons have a SINGLE cotyledon.' Dicot embryos have two cotyledons. This reversal of cotyledon number between monocots and dicots is a classic exam trap." },

  { id: 262, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Consider the following statements from the chapter summary:<br>(i) Apomixis results in formation of seeds without fertilisation.<br>(ii) Apomixis is found particularly in grasses.<br>(iii) Polyembryony is the occurrence of more than one embryo in a seed.<br>(iv) Apomicts have several advantages in horticulture and agriculture.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are from the NCERT summary: 'apomixis is found in some angiosperms, particularly in grasses. It results in the formation of seeds without fertilisation. Apomicts have several advantages in horticulture and agriculture. Some angiosperms produce more than one embryo in their seed — polyembryony.'" },

  { id: 263, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Pollinating agents can be either abiotic or biotic.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Abiotic agents include wind and water, while biotic agents include animals.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT summary. Pollinating agents are classified as abiotic (wind and water) or biotic (animals). R correctly explains A by identifying the specific abiotic and biotic agents." },

  { id: 264, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following is the correct description of pollen-pistil interaction as per the NCERT summary?", options: ["It involves events only after double fertilisation", "It involves all events from pollen landing on stigma until pollen tube enters the embryo sac or pollen inhibition", "It involves only pollen germination on the stigma", "It involves events from seed formation until seed dispersal"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT summary states: 'Pollen-pistil interaction involves all events from the landing of pollen grains on the stigma until the pollen tube enters the embryo sac (when the pollen is compatible) or pollen inhibition (when the pollen is incompatible).' It includes both acceptance and rejection outcomes." },

  { id: 265, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "The exine of pollen grain is made up of _______ and has _______.", options: ["Cellulose; germ pores", "Sporopollenin; germ pores", "Pectin; stomata", "Sporopollenin; lenticels"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT summary states: 'The exine is made up of sporopollenin and has germ pores.' The intine is made of cellulose and pectin. Germ pores are apertures where sporopollenin is absent, allowing pollen tube emergence." },

  { id: 266, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "A comprehensive question: In a typical angiosperm, arrange the following events in correct chronological order:<br>(a) Triple fusion<br>(b) Megasporogenesis<br>(c) Pollination<br>(d) Microsporogenesis<br>(e) Embryo development<br>(f) Endosperm development", options: ["d → b → c → a → f → e", "b → d → c → a → e → f", "d → b → c → a → e → f", "c → d → b → a → f → e"], correct: 0, explanation: "Correct chronological order: Microsporogenesis (pollen formation) and Megasporogenesis (embryo sac formation) occur during flower development → Pollination (pollen transfer to stigma) → Triple fusion (part of double fertilisation) → Endosperm development (always precedes embryo) → Embryo development. Since microsporogenesis typically occurs before/alongside megasporogenesis: d → b → c → a → f → e." },

  { id: 267, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following pairs is INCORRECTLY matched?", options: ["Androecium — Male reproductive organ consisting of stamens", "Gynoecium — Female reproductive organ consisting of pistils", "Microsporogenesis — Meiotic division of sporogenous tissue to form microspore tetrads", "Megasporogenesis — Mitotic division of megaspore mother cell to form megaspores"], correct: 3, explanation: "Statement D is INCORRECT. Megasporogenesis involves MEIOTIC division (not mitotic) of the megaspore mother cell to form four megaspores. The NCERT summary states: 'the megaspore mother cell divides meiotically.' This meiosis vs mitosis confusion is a critical NEET trap." },

  { id: 268, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "How many pollen grains and how many ovules would be required to produce 100 seeds in a plant?", options: ["100 pollen grains and 100 ovules", "200 pollen grains and 100 ovules", "100 pollen grains and 200 ovules", "50 pollen grains and 100 ovules"], correct: 0, explanation: "Each pollen grain produces two male gametes for double fertilisation in one ovule, resulting in one seed. So for 100 seeds: 100 pollen grains (each providing 2 male gametes) and 100 ovules (each developing into a seed after fertilisation) are required." },

  // ───── TOPIC: CROSS-CONCEPT LINKED QUESTIONS ─────

  { id: 269, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Consider the following divisions in the life cycle of an angiosperm:<br>(i) Meiosis in the pollen mother cell (PMC)<br>(ii) Meiosis in the megaspore mother cell (MMC)<br>(iii) Mitosis in the functional megaspore to form embryo sac<br>(iv) Mitosis in the generative cell to form male gametes<br><br>Which of the above produces <b>haploid</b> cells or nuclei directly?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 2, explanation: "Meiosis (i & ii) produces haploid (n) microspores and megaspores respectively — directly haploid. Mitosis in functional megaspore (iii) produces haploid nuclei as it is already haploid — also haploid. Mitosis in generative cell (iv) produces two male gametes which are also haploid. So technically all four produce haploid cells, but (i), (ii) and (iii) directly generate new haploid cells from the meiotic event or haploid precursor, while (iv) only duplicates haploid cells. NCERT focuses on meiosis as the haploid-generating step." },

  { id: 270, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A student makes the following statements:<br>(i) Tapetum nourishes developing pollen grains.<br>(ii) Sporopollenin is synthesised with the aid of tapetum.<br>(iii) Sporopollenin's resistance allows pollen grains to be preserved as fossils.<br>(iv) Germ pores on exine also contain sporopollenin.<br><br>Which statements are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT. Statement (iv) is INCORRECT — germ pores are specifically regions WHERE SPOROPOLLENIN IS ABSENT ('prominent apertures called germ pores where sporopollenin is absent'). The absence of sporopollenin at germ pores is what allows pollen tubes to emerge. Cross-concept: Tapetum nourishment → sporopollenin synthesis → fossil preservation vs. germ pore structure." },

  { id: 271, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Match each outbreeding device with the specific type of self-pollination it prevents:<br>(a) Monoecy — prevents (i) only autogamy<br>(b) Dioecy — prevents (ii) both autogamy and geitonogamy<br>(c) Self-incompatibility — prevents (iii) pollen from same flower or same plant<br>(d) Protandry/Protogyny — prevents (iv) only autogamy<br><br>Which matching is <b>correct</b>?", options: ["All four are correctly matched", "Only (a) and (b) are correctly matched", "Only (b) is incorrectly matched", "(a) should be (ii) and (b) should be (i)"], correct: 0, explanation: "All four matchings are correct per NCERT: Monoecy (separate male & female flowers on same plant) prevents only autogamy, not geitonogamy. Dioecy (male & female flowers on different plants) prevents both. Self-incompatibility prevents self-pollen from same flower or same plant from fertilising. Non-synchrony of pollen release and stigma receptivity (protandry/protogyny) prevents only autogamy. This cross-concept question integrates outbreeding devices with pollination type classification." },

  { id: 272, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Arrange the following stages in the correct developmental sequence of the male gametophyte from sporogenous tissue to male gametes:", options: ["Sporogenous tissue → PMC → Microspore tetrad → Pollen grain (2-celled) → Two male gametes", "PMC → Sporogenous tissue → Microspore tetrad → Two male gametes → Pollen grain", "Sporogenous tissue → Microspore tetrad → PMC → Pollen grain → Two male gametes", "PMC → Microspore tetrad → Sporogenous tissue → Pollen grain (2-celled) → Two male gametes"], correct: 0, explanation: "Correct sequence: Sporogenous tissue (each cell is a potential PMC) → PMC undergoes meiosis → Microspore tetrad → Microspores separate → Pollen grain (2-celled: vegetative + generative cells) → Generative cell divides mitotically → Two male gametes. This comprehensive sequence links microsporogenesis, microgametogenesis and pollen grain structure." },

  { id: 273, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Arranging structures in a typical angiosperm ovule from diploid to haploid, select the correct order:", options: ["Nucellus (2n) → MMC (2n) → Megaspore (n) → Embryo sac cells (n) → Polar nuclei (n)", "MMC (n) → Nucellus (2n) → Megaspore (2n) → Polar nuclei (n)", "Nucellus (n) → MMC (2n) → Megaspore (2n) → Embryo sac (n)", "Nucellus (2n) → MMC (n) → Megaspore (2n) → Polar nuclei (n)"], correct: 0, explanation: "The ploidy ladder: Nucellus (somatic cells, 2n) → MMC (before meiosis, 2n) → Functional megaspore (after meiosis, n) → All embryo sac cells including egg cell, synergids, antipodals (n) → Polar nuclei (n each). After triple fusion: PEN becomes 3n. This cross-concept question links megasporogenesis with ploidy changes at each stage." },

  { id: 274, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "In an artificial hybridisation experiment, the researcher:<br>(i) Emasculates bisexual flower buds before anther dehiscence.<br>(ii) Bags the flower with butter paper immediately (bagging).<br>(iii) Dusts desired pollen on the stigma when it becomes receptive.<br>(iv) Re-bags after pollination.<br><br>Which step directly relates to the principle of pollen-pistil compatibility?", options: ["Step (i) only", "Step (iii) only", "Step (iii) and (iv), since desired (compatible) pollen is selected", "Step (i) and (ii) only"], correct: 2, explanation: "Step (iii) — dusting DESIRED pollen — is directly linked to pollen-pistil compatibility. NCERT states pollination does not guarantee transfer of the right (compatible) pollen. In artificial hybridisation, desired pollen is manually selected to ensure compatible crossing, bypassing the chemical pollen-pistil dialogue. Step (iv) re-bagging prevents further contamination. Both (iii) and (iv) together ensure only the chosen compatible pollen reaches the stigma." },

  { id: 275, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Consider the following chain of events:<br>Triple fusion → PEC (3n) → Triploid endosperm →<br><br>Now match the final fate of endosperm in different plants:<br>(a) Completely consumed before seed maturity — Pea, Groundnut<br>(b) Persists in mature seed — Castor, Coconut<br>(c) Free-nuclear endosperm (coconut water) — Free nuclei stage before cellularisation<br><br>Which of the following correctly integrates triple fusion with seed classification?", options: ["The ploidy of endosperm varies between (a) and (b) group plants", "All endosperm tissues (whether consumed or persistent) are triploid, originating from the same triple fusion event", "In group (a), endosperm is diploid; in group (b), it is triploid", "Free-nuclear endosperm has no cell walls and is haploid"], correct: 1, explanation: "ALL endosperm tissue originates from triple fusion producing a 3n PEC. Whether the endosperm is consumed (as in pea, groundnut) or persists (as in castor, coconut), it is ALWAYS triploid. The classification into albuminous/non-albuminous refers to whether endosperm remains at maturity — not its ploidy. Free-nuclear endosperm (coconut water) is triploid and free-nuclear (not haploid)." },

  { id: 276, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A seed of Citrus is found to contain three embryos. One embryo arose sexually, while the other two arose from nucellar cells. Which of the following is <b>correct</b> about these embryos?", options: ["All three embryos are genetically identical to each other", "The sexually produced embryo is diploid; the nucellar embryos are triploid", "The sexually produced embryo may be genetically different from the parent; the nucellar embryos are genetically identical to the maternal plant", "All three embryos will show segregation if used to raise crops"], correct: 2, explanation: "The sexually produced embryo forms after syngamy (father's + mother's genetics → genetically different from either parent). The nucellar embryos arise by mitosis from somatic nucellar cells (2n) of the MATERNAL plant — genetically identical to the mother (clones). This shows how polyembryony in Citrus produces both sexually and apomictically derived embryos in the same seed — a key cross-concept linking double fertilisation with apomixis." },

  { id: 277, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Cleistogamous flowers are guaranteed pollinators but promote inbreeding depression over generations.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Cleistogamous flowers are invariably autogamous and continued self-pollination leads to inbreeding depression.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are true per NCERT. Cleistogamy ensures seed-set without pollinators (A is true), but since these flowers are invariably autogamous (continual selfing), the result over generations is inbreeding depression — a reduction in fitness due to increased homozygosity. R correctly explains the paradox: cleistogamy is reliable but promotes inbreeding depression. The cross-concept here links cleistogamy with outbreeding devices and inbreeding depression." },

  { id: 278, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A plant breeder wants to perform artificial hybridisation in a crop plant. Consider the following constraints:<br>(i) In rice and wheat, pollen loses viability within 30 minutes.<br>(ii) Pollen of some species (Rosaceae, Leguminosae, Solanaceae) retains viability for months.<br>(iii) Pollen can be stored in liquid nitrogen for use in pollen banks.<br>(iv) Emasculation must occur before anther dehiscence.<br><br>Which combination of factors makes efficient cross-breeding most challenging in rice?", options: ["(i) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iv) together — short viability window combined with precise timing of emasculation", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "The biggest challenge in rice cross-breeding is the extremely short pollen viability (within 30 minutes) combined with the need for precise emasculation timing (before anther dehiscence). This narrow window means pollination must happen very quickly after emasculation and collection of donor pollen. Pollen banks (iii) help for long-viability species but are less useful for rice. This cross-concept integrates pollen viability, artificial hybridisation technique, and crop-specific challenges." },

  { id: 279, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A table of ploidy levels is given below. Select all <b>INCORRECT</b> entries:", options: ["Synergid (n); Antipodal (n); Polar nucleus (n); PEN (3n)", "Egg cell (2n); Synergid (n); Zygote (2n); PEC (3n)", "Egg cell (n); Zygote (2n); PEC (3n); Endosperm (3n)", "Synergid (n); Egg cell (n); PEN (3n); Endosperm (3n)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Option B is INCORRECT. It states egg cell is 2n — WRONG. The egg cell is haploid (n). After syngamy: male gamete (n) + egg cell (n) = zygote (2n). Options A, C, and D are all correctly described. All cells of the embryo sac (egg cell, synergids, antipodals, polar nuclei) are haploid (n). Only after triple fusion does ploidy become 3n. This cross-concept integrates embryo sac structure with ploidy changes during double fertilisation." },

  { id: 280, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Which of the following correctly links pollination type with its genetic outcome in seeds?", options: ["Autogamy → Seeds with new genetic combinations; Xenogamy → Seeds genetically identical to parent", "Xenogamy → Seeds with new genetic combinations; Autogamy → Seeds genetically similar to parent; Cleistogamy → Seeds with assured set but genetically uniform", "Geitonogamy → Seeds with new genetic combinations; Xenogamy → Seeds genetically identical", "Cleistogamy → Maximum genetic variation; Xenogamy → Minimum genetic variation"], correct: 1, explanation: "Xenogamy (cross-pollination from different plant) generates new genetic combinations → genetic variation. Autogamy/cleistogamy (self-pollination) produces seeds genetically similar to parent, with no genetic recombination between two genomes. Geitonogamy is functionally cross but genetically like autogamy (same plant). This cross-concept links pollination type → fertilisation outcome → genetic diversity → agronomic significance." },

  { id: 281, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "In seagrasses like <i>Zostera</i>, pollen grains lack sporopollenin and are long and ribbon-like. Which of the following statements correctly infers from this fact?", options: ["Zostera pollen can be preserved as fossils easily due to lack of sporopollenin", "The absence of sporopollenin in Zostera makes the pollen less resistant and unsuited for aerial dispersal, but well-adapted for underwater transport", "Zostera pollen has no germ pores as germ pores are only found where sporopollenin is present", "Zostera pollen is produced in large quantities to compensate for lack of sporopollenin"], correct: 1, explanation: "Sporopollenin is the hard, resistant component of the exine that protects pollen in aerial environments. Its absence in Zostera means pollen cannot withstand desiccation or high temperatures — making it unsuitable for air dispersal. Instead, the ribbon-like shape and lack of sporopollenin are adaptive advantages for passive aquatic transport inside water. Cross-concept: pollen wall structure × pollination agent × adaptive significance." },

  { id: 282, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A student compares dicot and monocot embryo structures:<br>(a) Dicot: two cotyledons store food if endosperm consumed (non-albuminous)<br>(b) Monocot (grass): scutellum lies laterally, absorbs endosperm during germination<br>(c) Coleoptile protects the shoot; coleorrhiza protects the radicle in grass family monocots<br>(d) In dicots, coleorrhiza encloses the radicle<br><br>How many of the above statements are correct?", options: ["All four", "Only (a), (b) and (c)", "Only (b) and (c)", "Only (a) and (d)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (d) is INCORRECT. In DICOTS, the radicle is covered by a ROOT CAP — not coleorrhiza. Coleorrhiza is an undifferentiated sheath specific to MONOCOTS (grass family). Statements (a), (b) and (c) are correct. Cross-concept: embryo morphology × cotyledon function × germination structures in monocot vs. dicot." },

  { id: 283, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Self-incompatibility (SI) inhibits pollen germination or pollen tube growth. Which part of the plant life cycle does SI operate in?", options: ["During the sporophyte phase — between two sporophytic parents", "During the gametophytic phase — between male gametophyte (pollen) and female gametophyte tissue", "Exclusively during endosperm development after triple fusion", "At the zygote stage, preventing zygote from dividing"], correct: 1, explanation: "Self-incompatibility operates during the gametophytic phase (or at the gametophyte–sporophyte interface). Pollen grains (male gametophyte) are inhibited from germinating or growing in the style by chemical signals from the pistil (part of sporophyte but interacting with the gametophyte). This is the pollen-pistil chemical dialogue. Cross-concept: SI × gametophyte-sporophyte alternation × pollen tube physiology." },

  { id: 284, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Consider three plants:<br>Plant X: Cleistogamous only<br>Plant Y: Chasmogamous, wind-pollinated<br>Plant Z: Chasmogamous, animal-pollinated with self-incompatibility<br><br>Which of the following correctly ranks them in terms of <b>genetic variability</b> in seeds, from <b>MOST to LEAST</b>?", options: ["Z > Y > X", "Y > Z > X", "X > Z > Y", "Z > X > Y"], correct: 0, explanation: "Plant Z (chasmogamous + animal-pollinated + self-incompatible) exclusively undergoes xenogamy with genetically different pollen — MAXIMUM genetic variation. Plant Y (wind-pollinated, chasmogamous) can receive pollen from different plants but also may have geitonogamy — MODERATE variation. Plant X (cleistogamous only) is invariably autogamous — MINIMUM genetic variation. Cross-concept: pollination type × outbreeding devices × genetic consequences." },

  { id: 285, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Match the following developmental fates and identify which one is <b>INCORRECTLY</b> matched:", options: ["Ovary wall → Pericarp (fruit wall)", "Integuments → Seed coat (testa/tegmen)", "Nucellus → Perisperm in all seeds", "Polar nuclei + male gamete → Primary endosperm nucleus"], correct: 2, explanation: "Statement C is INCORRECT. NCERT states nucellus forms perisperm only 'occasionally, in some seeds such as black pepper and beet.' It does NOT form perisperm in ALL seeds. In most seeds, the nucellus is completely consumed during development. Cross-concept: post-fertilisation developmental fates of ovule parts × perisperm formation × seed structure." },

  { id: 286, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Coconut water and the white kernel of coconut represent two different stages of endosperm development.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Coconut water is free-nuclear endosperm (thousands of free nuclei without cell walls), while the white kernel is cellular endosperm (nuclei surrounded by cell walls).", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are directly from NCERT. Free-nuclear endosperm (coconut water) precedes cellular endosperm (white kernel) in development. The PEN first undergoes free-nuclear divisions (no cell wall), then cell walls are laid down forming the cellular endosperm. R correctly and fully explains A — this is a cross-concept question linking PEN → free-nuclear → cellular stages of endosperm with the familiar example of coconut." },

  { id: 287, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "In a crop improvement programme, a plant breeder wants to cross two varieties where self-incompatibility prevents using one variety as a female parent. What technique minimises this problem?", options: ["Only use animal pollination to bypass self-incompatibility", "Emasculate the self-incompatible variety and bag it to allow only the desired pollen; simultaneous application of knowledge of pollen-pistil interaction can overcome incompatibility", "Induce apomixis in both varieties to get clonal seeds", "Use only cleistogamous flowers as the female parent"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The knowledge gained in this area (pollen-pistil interaction) would help the plant breeder in manipulating pollen-pistil interaction, even in incompatible pollinations, to get desired hybrids.' Emasculation + bagging prevents self-pollen contamination, and understanding the chemical basis of SI allows breeders to overcome it. Cross-concept: SI × artificial hybridisation technique × pollen-pistil interaction research." },

  { id: 288, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "In maize, which has separate male (tassel) and female (ear/cob) flowers on the same plant:", options: ["Cross-pollination between different plants (xenogamy) is impossible", "Autogamy within the same flower is impossible; geitonogamy between tassel and cob of the same plant can occur; xenogamy from another plant's tassel is also possible", "Geitonogamy is impossible but autogamy and xenogamy are both possible", "All three types — autogamy, geitonogamy and xenogamy — occur with equal frequency"], correct: 1, explanation: "Maize is monoecious. Since male and female are in separate flowers, autogamy (same flower) is IMPOSSIBLE. However, pollen from the tassel can reach the cob stigma of the same plant (geitonogamy) or sigma of another plant (xenogamy). Cross-concept: monoecy × autogamy × geitonogamy × xenogamy — integrates all three pollination types with plant reproductive biology." },

  { id: 289, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "In a plant that sheds pollen at the 3-celled stage, compared to a plant that sheds pollen at the 2-celled stage, the fertilisation process is:", options: ["Slower, because more cells need to move", "Faster, because male gametes are already formed and ready for fusion without waiting for generative cell division in the pollen tube", "Identical in speed as gamete fusion time is the rate-limiting step", "Faster in the 2-celled plant because the generative cell divides rapidly"], correct: 1, explanation: "In 2-celled pollen, the generative cell must divide during pollen tube growth to produce two male gametes — this adds time. In 3-celled pollen, the two male gametes are pre-formed and ready for fusion immediately after the pollen tube enters the synergid. Hence fertilisation is potentially faster in 3-celled pollen plants. Cross-concept: 2-celled vs 3-celled pollen × pollen tube growth × timing of double fertilisation." },

  { id: 290, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A student claims: 'In both monocots and dicots, the seed has two seed coats — testa and tegmen — derived from the two integuments of the ovule.' Is this always correct?", options: ["Yes, all angiosperm seeds have two distinct seed coats from two integuments", "Not always — seeds from ovules with one integument have only one seed coat; testa and tegmen are present only when two integuments exist", "Incorrect — testa and tegmen are names for the pericarp layers, not seed coats", "Incorrect — seed coat always forms from the ovary wall, not from integuments"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states integuments harden as tough protective seed coats. While most angiosperms have TWO integuments (bitegmic ovules) → testa + tegmen, some species have only ONE integument (unitegmic ovules) → only one seed coat. The claim is not universally correct. Cross-concept: integuments → seed coat × ovule types × seed morphology." },

  { id: 291, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The synergids degenerate after pollen tube entry.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> The filiform apparatus of synergids plays a critical role in guiding pollen tube entry; once the pollen tube has discharged male gametes, the synergid is no longer needed and degenerates.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are consistent with NCERT. NCERT states the pollen tube 'enters one of the synergids through the filiform apparatus' and releases male gametes into 'the cytoplasm of the synergid.' The synergid that receives the pollen tube degenerates after this. R correctly explains the functional link between the filiform apparatus, pollen tube entry, and subsequent synergid degeneration." },

  { id: 292, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A single MCQ integrating fruit types: Which set correctly classifies the given fruits?", options: ["Apple (true fruit), Banana (false fruit), Strawberry (parthenocarpic), Mango (true fruit)", "Apple (false fruit), Banana (parthenocarpic/seedless), Strawberry (false fruit), Mango (true fruit)", "Apple (true fruit), Banana (parthenocarpic), Strawberry (true fruit), Mango (false fruit)", "Apple (parthenocarpic), Banana (false fruit), Strawberry (true fruit), Mango (parthenocarpic)"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT: Apple and strawberry are false fruits (thalamus contributes). Banana is a parthenocarpic fruit (develops without fertilisation, seedless). Mango is a true fruit (develops from ovary alone). Option B correctly classifies all four. Options A, C, D all contain at least one error. This is a comprehensive cross-concept question linking true fruit, false fruit and parthenocarpy." },

  { id: 293, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Three megaspores degenerate after meiosis of the MMC. Which of the following best explains WHY only one megaspore survives?", options: ["The surviving megaspore is at the chalazal end where it receives more nutrients from the nucellus", "The surviving megaspore is at the micropylar end and therefore closest to the style for pollen tube entry", "The surviving megaspore has the highest amount of sporopollenin protecting it from degradation", "The surviving megaspore is randomly selected by chance with no positional preference"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Generally, the micropylar most megaspore degenerates.' It is the CHALAZAL-most megaspore that typically survives, as it is furthest from the degenerating influence and receives better nutritional support from chalazal nucellus tissue. This cross-concept question links megasporogenesis (meiosis outcomes) with the functional anatomy of the ovule (chalazal vs. micropylar end)." },

  { id: 294, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "In a species where apomixis occurs via diploid egg cell formation (without reduction division), how does the chromosome number of apomictic offspring compare with the parent?", options: ["Apomictic offspring are haploid (n) — they lack one set of chromosomes from the father", "Apomictic offspring are diploid (2n) — identical to the parent, since no meiosis reduced their ploidy and no fertilisation added extra chromosomes", "Apomictic offspring are triploid (3n) — endosperm and embryo chromosomes combine", "Apomictic offspring show 50% chance of being diploid and 50% haploid"], correct: 1, explanation: "In this form of apomixis, the diploid egg cell (2n) forms WITHOUT meiotic reduction, and develops into an embryo WITHOUT fertilisation. So no chromosome reduction ever happened, and no extra set was added. The result: offspring with the same 2n chromosome number as the parent — genetically identical clones. Cross-concept: apomixis mechanism × meiosis × ploidy × genetic consequences." },

  { id: 295, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A farmer stores surplus wheat at 15% moisture content. Another farmer stores at 12%. A third stores seeds collected from this year's hybrid wheat. Which farmer faces the <b>most</b> risk of crop failure next season?", options: ["Farmer 1 (15% moisture) — seeds may not germinate well", "Farmer 2 (12% moisture) — seeds are over-desiccated and will die", "Farmer 3 (hybrid seeds stored) — hybrid seeds show segregation in progeny, losing hybrid vigour", "All face equal risk"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states seeds are stored at 10-15% moisture — so both Farmers 1 and 2 have acceptable storage. Farmer 3's risk is greatest: seeds collected from hybrid plants SEGREGATE in progeny (NCERT: 'If the seeds collected from hybrids are sown, the plants in the progeny will segregate and do not maintain hybrid characters'). Cross-concept: seed dormancy × dehydration × hybrid seed biology × agricultural implication." },

  { id: 296, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Compare Vallisneria (fresh water) and Zostera (marine) water pollination mechanisms and identify the <b>CORRECT</b> statement:", options: ["In both, pollen is released underwater and female flowers are submerged", "In Vallisneria, pollination occurs at the water surface; in Zostera, pollen is carried passively inside water to submerged female flowers", "In Vallisneria, pollen is long and ribbon-like; in Zostera, pollen is spherical", "Both Vallisneria and Zostera have pollen protected by mucilaginous covering"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT distinguishes clearly: Vallisneria — female flower reaches the water surface by a long stalk; male flowers/pollen are released on the surface; pollination at the surface. Zostera — female flowers remain submerged; pollen is long and ribbon-like, released inside water and carried passively. These are mechanistically different. Cross-concept: two water pollination mechanisms × pollen adaptation × habitat (fresh water vs marine)." },

  { id: 297, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "Arrange the following structures in the order in which they are 'used up' or transformed through the events of double fertilisation and post-fertilisation development:", options: ["Synergid → Egg cell (after syngamy → zygote) → Polar nuclei (after triple fusion → PEC → Endosperm) → Antipodal cells (degenerate) → Ovule wall (→ Seed coat)", "Polar nuclei → Egg cell → Antipodal cells → Synergid → Ovule wall", "Egg cell → Polar nuclei → Ovule wall → Synergid → Antipodal cells", "Antipodal cells → Synergid → Polar nuclei → Egg cell → Ovule wall"], correct: 0, explanation: "Sequence of transformation: (1) Synergid receives pollen tube and degenerates after releasing male gametes. (2) Egg cell fuses with male gamete (syngamy) → Zygote → Embryo. (3) Polar nuclei fuse with male gamete (triple fusion) → PEC → Endosperm. (4) Antipodal cells degenerate (no post-fertilisation role in most species). (5) Integuments of ovule wall → Seed coat. This comprehensive cross-concept question integrates all major post-fertilisation events." },

  { id: 298, topic: "Cross-Concept", q: "A student compiled the following key numerical facts from this chapter. Identify the <b>incorrect</b> entry:", options: ["Pollen grain size: 25–50 micrometres; Water-pollinated genera: ~30; Embryo sac cells: 7; Embryo sac nuclei: 8", "Embryo sac nuclei: 6; Pollen grain size: 25–50 μm; Ploidy of endosperm: 3n; Egg cells per embryo sac: 1", "Pollen grain size: 25–50 μm; Water-pollinated genera: ~30; PEN ploidy: 3n; Egg cells: 1", "Embryo sac cells: 7; Embryo sac nuclei: 8; Synergids: 2; Antipodals: 3"], correct: 1, explanation: "Option B states 'Embryo sac nuclei: 6' — this is INCORRECT. A mature embryo sac is 8-nucleate and 7-celled. The 8 nuclei = 1 egg + 2 synergids + 2 polar nuclei + 3 antipodals. Option B incorrectly substitutes 6 for 8. All other options (A, C, D) contain correct numbers. This comprehensive cross-concept question integrates all critical numerical values from the Sexual Reproduction chapter." },

  // ───── HOTs: HIGHER ORDER THINKING SKILLS ─────

  { id: 299, topic: "Pollen Viability", hots: true, q: "Pollen viability period for some members of Rosaceae family is about", options: ["30 minutes", "30 seconds", "Several months", "30 days"], correct: 2, explanation: "According to NCERT Class 12, Chapter 2: 'In some members of Rosaceae, Leguminosae and Solanaceae, they maintain viability for months.' Option 1 (30 minutes) is incorrect because that applies to cereals like rice and wheat." },

  { id: 300, topic: "Apomixis", hots: true, q: "Apomixis is common in", options: ["Fabaceae only", "Solanaceae only", "Sunflower family and grass family", "Mustard family only"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'some species of Asteraceae and grasses, have evolved a special mechanism, to produce seeds without fertilisation, called apomixis.' The Asteraceae family is commonly known as the sunflower family. The other families listed are not standard examples of apomixis." },

  { id: 301, topic: "Megasporogenesis", hots: true, q: "In majority of angiosperms, embryosac is", options: ["Trisporic", "Bisporic", "Tetrasporic", "Monosporic"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 explains: 'In a majority of angiosperms, one of the megaspores is functional while the other three degenerate. Only the functional megaspore develops into the female gametophyte (embryo sac). This method... is termed monosporic development.'" },

  { id: 302, topic: "Pollen Germination", hots: true, q: "Read the given statements and select the correct option.<br><b>(A)</b> Hanging drop method requires 10% Sugar solution with boric acid, Ca, Mg and K salts.<br><b>(B)</b> Growth of pollen tube starts in microsporangium.", options: ["Both the statements A and B are correct", "Statement A is correct while B is incorrect", "Statement A is incorrect while B is correct", "Both the statements A and B are incorrect"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement A is correct as in vitro pollen germination requires a 10% sugar solution with nutrients like boron (boric acid). Statement B is incorrect because the growth of the pollen tube starts on the stigma (in vivo) or in the nutrient medium (in vitro), not in the microsporangium (anther)." },

  { id: 303, topic: "Double Fertilization", hots: true, q: "Choose odd one with respect to double fertilization.", options: ["Syngamy results in the formation of endosperm", "It includes syngamy and triple fusion", "Total five haploid nuclei are involved", "It is a characteristic feature of angiosperms"], correct: 0, explanation: "Option 1 is factually incorrect, making it the odd one out. NCERT states syngamy results in the formation of a diploid zygote, not the endosperm. The endosperm is formed from the primary endosperm nucleus (PEN) following triple fusion. 5 nuclei (2 male gametes + 1 egg + 2 polar nuclei) are involved overall." },

  { id: 304, topic: "Dicot Embryogeny", hots: true, q: "During dicot embryogeny, suspensor cell cuts towards <b>(i)</b> and embryonal cell towards <b>(ii)</b> region. Correct words for (i) and (ii), respectively are", options: ["Antipodal and Micropyle", "Chalazal and Micropyle", "Micropyle and Antipodal", "Chalazal and Antipodal"], correct: 2, explanation: "During embryo development, the zygote divides transversely. The basal cell, located towards the micropylar end, forms the suspensor. The terminal cell, located towards the chalazal (antipodal) end, develops into the embryo proper." },

  { id: 305, topic: "Seed Anatomy & Ploidy", hots: true, q: "Select the ploidy level of tissues like aleurone layer, endosperm and cotyledon in maize seed.", options: ["2n, 3n, 2n", "2n, 3n, n", "3n, 3n, 2n", "3n, 2n, 3n"], correct: 2, explanation: "In maize, the aleurone layer is the outer proteinaceous covering of the endosperm, making it triploid (3n). The bulk endosperm is also triploid (3n). The cotyledon (scutellum) is part of the embryo developed from the zygote, making it diploid (2n)." },

  { id: 306, topic: "Seeds", hots: true, q: "Which of the given statement(s) is/are correct?<br><b>A.</b> Seeds are produced sexually<br><b>B.</b> Seeds can be produced asexually<br><b>C.</b> Seeds are found in gymnosperms", options: ["Only A and B", "Only B and C", "Only A and C", "All A, B and C"], correct: 3, explanation: "Seeds are the final product of sexual reproduction (A). Through apomixis, seeds can be produced asexually (B). Gymnosperms are plants that bear 'naked seeds', meaning they do produce seeds (C). All statements are correct." },

  { id: 307, topic: "Pollination", hots: true, q: "In all of the following plants, both cleistogamous and chasmogamous flowers are found, except", options: ["Viola", "Commelina", "Oxalis", "Salvia"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'Some plants such as Viola (common pansy), Oxalis, and Commelina produce two types of flowers – chasmogamous... and cleistogamous...'. Salvia does not belong to this list; it exhibits entomophily (insect pollination)." },

  { id: 308, topic: "Pollination Agents", hots: true, q: "Which of the following show hydrophily?", options: ["Yucca", "Salvia", "Ficus", "Zostera"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT lists examples of water pollinated plants: fresh water species like Vallisneria and Hydrilla, and marine sea-grasses such as Zostera. Yucca is pollinated by a moth, while Salvia and Ficus are insect-pollinated." },

  { id: 309, topic: "Monocot Seed Anatomy", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 309 Figure L.S. of an Onion seed.jpg", q: "Label the points a, b and c of the figure given below and select the option accordingly.", options: ["a-Plumule, b-Endosperm, c-Cotyledon", "a-Hypocotyl, b-Seed coat, c-Plumule", "a-Hypocotyl, b-Endosperm, c-Cotyledon", "a-Coleorhiza, b-Plumule, c-Cotyledon"], correct: 2, explanation: "Based on the NCERT diagram of the L.S. of an onion seed, 'c' is the curved cotyledon, 'b' is the bulk storage tissue (endosperm), and 'a' points to the shoot apex/hypocotyl region of the embryonal axis." },

  { id: 310, topic: "Adaptations for Hydrophily", hots: true, q: "Find the feature(s) which is/are true for hydrophilous flower.<br><b>(a)</b> Unwettable pollen grain<br><b>(b)</b> Pollens with mucilage covering<br><b>(c)</b> Large, feathery stigma", options: ["Only (b)", "Only (b) and (c)", "All (a), (b) and (c)", "Only (a) and (b)"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states for water-pollinated plants: 'Pollen grains are protected from wetting by a mucilaginous covering' (a and b are correct). A large, feathery stigma (c) is a characteristic of anemophilous (wind-pollinated) flowers like maize, to easily trap air-borne pollen." },

  { id: 311, topic: "Types of Seeds", hots: true, q: "Endosperm is completely consumed by the developing embryo in", options: ["Wheat", "Maize", "Pea", "Castor"], correct: 2, explanation: "According to NCERT, in ex-albuminous (non-endospermic) seeds, the endosperm is completely consumed during embryo development. Examples include pea, groundnut, and beans. Wheat, maize, and castor retain endosperm (albuminous seeds)." },

  { id: 312, topic: "Monocot Embryo", hots: true, q: "Which one is not a structure associated with monocot embryo?", options: ["Nucellus", "Coleoptile", "Coleorhiza", "Root cap"], correct: 0, explanation: "The nucellus is a maternal tissue found in the central part of the ovule, not the embryo. The monocot embryo consists of an embryonal axis, scutellum, coleoptile (covering plumule), and coleorhiza (covering radicle and root cap)." },

  { id: 313, topic: "Seed Advantages", hots: true, q: "Seeds form the basis of our agriculture as they show<br><b>(a)</b> Dormancy<br><b>(b)</b> Dehydration<br><b>(c)</b> Haploidy", options: ["Only (c)", "All (a), (b) and (c)", "Only (b) and (c)", "Both (a) and (b)"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 highlights: 'Dehydration and dormancy of mature seeds are crucial for storage of seeds which can be used as food throughout the year and also to raise crop in the next season.' Seeds are diploid structures, so (c) is incorrect." },

  { id: 314, topic: "Reproduction Types", hots: true, q: "Choose the odd one out with respect to asexual reproduction.", options: ["Syngamy", "Recurrent agamospermy", "Adventive embryony", "Sporophytic budding"], correct: 0, explanation: "Syngamy represents the fusion of male and female gametes, which is the defining characteristic of sexual reproduction. Recurrent agamospermy, adventive embryony, and sporophytic budding are all forms of apomixis/asexual reproduction." },

  { id: 315, topic: "Monocot Embryo", hots: true, q: "In grass family, the cotyledon is called", options: ["Hypocotyl", "Epicotyl", "Epiblast", "Scutellum"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT explicitly states: 'Embryos of monocotyledons possess only one cotyledon. In the grass family the cotyledon is called scutellum that is situated towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis.'" },

  { id: 316, topic: "Monocot Embryo", hots: true, q: "The remains of second cotyledon in some grasses is called", options: ["Epiblast", "Hypocotyl", "Scutellum", "Epicotyl"], correct: 0, explanation: "In some grass embryos, there is a small flap-like structure opposite the scutellum, which represents the rudiment of the second cotyledon. This structure is known as the epiblast." },

  { id: 317, topic: "Artificial Hybridization", hots: true, q: "In cross hybridisation experiments, emasculation is required in", options: ["Zea", "Phoenix", "Pisum", "Carica"], correct: 2, explanation: "Emasculation (removal of anthers) is only required for plants bearing bisexual flowers to prevent self-pollination. Pisum (pea) has bisexual flowers. Zea (maize), Phoenix (date palm), and Carica (papaya) possess unisexual flowers." },

  { id: 318, topic: "Biotic Pollinators", hots: true, q: "Which of the given is most common insect pollinator?", options: ["Ant", "Aphid", "Wasp", "Bee"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT specifies: 'Among the animals, insects, particularly bees are the dominant biotic pollinating agents.' They are vital for pollinating a massive variety of angiosperms." },

  { id: 319, topic: "Monocot Embryo", hots: true, q: "Shield shape cotyledon situated lateral side of embryonal axis in maize is called", options: ["Epiblast", "Scutellum", "Coleoptile", "Coleorhiza"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT describes the single cotyledon of the grass family (like maize) as being shield-shaped and located lateral to the embryonal axis. This specialized structure is known as the scutellum." },

  { id: 320, topic: "Pollination in Aquatic Plants", hots: true, q: "In majority of the aquatic plants", options: ["Hydrophily occurs", "Anemophily and entomophily occurs", "Malacophily occurs", "Pollination is absent"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT points out a common misconception: 'Not all aquatic plants use water for pollination. In a majority of aquatic plants such as water hyacinth and water lily, the flowers emerge above the level of water and are pollinated by insects or wind (entomophily and anemophily).'" },

  { id: 321, topic: "Plant Reproduction Techniques", hots: true, q: "Select the correct match.", options: ["In vitro pollen germination : Hanging drop method", "Natural hybridisation : Emasculation", "Double fertilization : Results in the triploid cell only", "Outbreeding device : Bisexuality"], correct: 0, explanation: "The hanging drop method is a classic laboratory technique used to observe in vitro pollen germination. Emasculation is artificial, not natural. Double fertilization results in both a diploid zygote and a triploid PEN. Outbreeding devices exist to counter bisexuality." },

  { id: 322, topic: "Gametogenesis", hots: true, q: "Read the statements carefully and find how many is/are correct?<br><b>(a)</b> Pre-fertilisation involves gametogenesis<br><b>(b)</b> Gamete mother cells may be haploid or diploid<br><b>(c)</b> Gametogenesis involves mitosis or meiosis<br><b>(d)</b> Water is always needed for gamete transfer", options: ["4", "3", "2", "1"], correct: 1, explanation: "Three statements (a, b, c) are correct. Gametogenesis is a pre-fertilization event. Gametes form by meiosis in diploid organisms and by mitosis in haploid organisms. The term 'gamete mother cell' generally applies to meiocytes (diploid), but in broad terms of life cycles, haploid parents also possess gamete-producing cells. Water is NOT always needed (e.g., wind/insect pollination in seed plants), making (d) incorrect." },

  { id: 323, topic: "Pollen Allergy", hots: true, q: "Which plant cannot cause air-borne allergies?", options: ["Chenopodium", "Parthenium", "Vallisneria", "Amaranthus"], correct: 2, explanation: "Vallisneria is a hydrophilous (water-pollinated) plant, meaning its pollen is transferred by water currents, not air. Parthenium, Chenopodium, and Amaranthus are wind-pollinated and produce profuse, airborne pollen known to cause respiratory allergies." },

  { id: 324, topic: "Angiosperm Characteristics", hots: true, q: "Majority of the flowering plants", options: ["Produce bisexual flowers", "Shows reductional division in megaspore mother cell", "Both (1) and (2)", "Produce unisexual flowers"], correct: 2, explanation: "The majority of flowering plants produce hermaphrodite (bisexual) flowers. In these plants, megasporogenesis involves meiotic (reductional) division of the diploid megaspore mother cell (MMC) to form four haploid megaspores. Thus, both statements 1 and 2 are correct." },

  { id: 325, topic: "Embryo Sac Development", hots: true, q: "Match the following columns and choose the correct option with respect to development of embryo-sac.<br><b>Column-I</b><br>a. Monosporic<br>b. Bisporic<br>c. Tetrasporic<br>d. Functional megaspore<br><b>Column-II</b><br>(i) Chalazal end<br>(ii) 4 megaspore nuclei take part in formation of embryo-sac<br>(iii) Two megaspore nuclei form single embryo-sac<br>(iv) One out of 4 megaspore forms embryo-sac", options: ["a(ii), b(ii), c(iv), d(i)", "a(iv), b(iii), c(ii), d(i)", "a(iv), b(iii), c(i), d(ii)", "a(ii), b(iii), c(i), d(iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Monosporic development (a) utilizes one megaspore (iv). Bisporic (b) utilizes two megaspore nuclei (iii). Tetrasporic (c) utilizes all 4 megaspore nuclei (ii). In the majority of angiosperms, the functional megaspore (d) is located at the chalazal end (i)." },

  { id: 326, topic: "Apomixis and Hybrids", hots: true, q: "The problems of using hybrid seeds can be solved by using apomictic seeds, because", options: ["Apomictic seeds often develop from diploid cells, so chance of segregation is not possible", "Apomictic seeds develop from fertilised eggs", "Apomixis is not genetically controlled", "Hybrid seeds are not resistant to pathogens"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT explains that if hybrids are made into apomicts, there is no segregation of characters in the hybrid progeny. This is because apomixis mimics asexual reproduction, bypassing meiosis and syngamy, usually developing directly from a diploid maternal cell (like nucellus or unreduced egg)." },

  { id: 327, topic: "Embryo Sac Structure", hots: true, q: "Which one is incorrect with respect to antipodals?", options: ["They are located in micropylar end of embryo-sac", "In most of the plants, they are three in numbers", "They are haploid", "They are vegetative cells"], correct: 0, explanation: "Antipodals are three haploid cells situated at the chalazal end of the embryo sac, not the micropylar end. The egg apparatus (egg cell + synergids) is located at the micropylar end." },

  { id: 328, topic: "Ploidy Level Calculations", hots: true, q: "In a plant species, female plant is tetraploid and male plant is diploid. The ploidy of egg and PEN will respectively be", options: ["n and 3n", "2n and 2n", "2n and 5n", "n and 5n"], correct: 2, explanation: "The female parent is 4n, so its gametes (egg) and polar nuclei are 2n. The central cell has two polar nuclei, so it contributes 2n + 2n = 4n. The male parent is 2n, so its gametes are n. Therefore, Egg = 2n. PEN = Central Cell (4n) + Male Gamete (n) = 5n." },

  { id: 329, topic: "Monocot Embryo", hots: true, q: "Mass of undifferentiated cells which cover radicle and root cap in grass is called", options: ["Coleoptile", "Coleorhiza", "Scutellum", "Epiblast"], correct: 1, explanation: "In monocot (grass) embryos, the lower end of the embryonal axis houses the radicle and root cap, which are enclosed in an undifferentiated protective sheath called the coleorhiza." },

  { id: 330, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "Self incompatibility", options: ["Is not genetically controlled", "Promotes cross pollination", "Promotes self pollination", "Is absent in angiosperms"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT defines self-incompatibility as a genetic mechanism that prevents self-pollen from fertilising the ovules by inhibiting pollen germination or pollen tube growth. By preventing inbreeding, it promotes cross-pollination." },

  { id: 331, topic: "Flower Morphology", hots: true, q: "Megasporophyll is morphologically equivalent to", options: ["Stamen", "Inflorescence", "Ovule", "Carpel"], correct: 3, explanation: "In angiosperms, the carpel (or pistil) is morphologically equivalent to the megasporophyll of gymnosperms, as it is the modified leaf that bears the ovules (megasporangia). The stamen is equivalent to the microsporophyll." },

  { id: 332, topic: "Embryo Sac Structure", hots: true, q: "Synergids<br><b>(a)</b> Are haploid<br><b>(b)</b> Possess cellular thickenings<br><b>(c)</b> Degenerates finally<br>The correct set of option is", options: ["Only (a)", "Only (b) and (c)", "Only (c)", "All (a), (b) and (c)"], correct: 3, explanation: "Synergids are haploid (n) cells of the embryo sac. They possess special cellular thickenings at the micropylar tip called the filiform apparatus, which guides the pollen tube. Post-fertilization, the synergids degenerate. Thus, all statements are correct." },

  { id: 333, topic: "Pollination Vectors", hots: true, q: "Find odd one out with respect to entomophily.", options: ["Salvia", "Yucca", "Ficus", "Maize"], correct: 3, explanation: "Maize is an anemophilous (wind-pollinated) plant, characterized by well-exposed stamens and large, feathery stigmas (tassels) to catch airborne pollen. Salvia, Yucca, and Ficus are insect-pollinated (entomophilous)." },

  { id: 334, topic: "Microsporangium Wall", hots: true, q: "Innermost wall layer of anther helps in", options: ["Providing protection", "Dispersal of pollens", "Providing nourishment to the developing pollen grains", "Formation of pollen grain"], correct: 2, explanation: "The innermost wall layer of the microsporangium is the tapetum. According to NCERT, 'It nourishes the developing pollen grains.' The outer three layers (epidermis, endothecium, middle layers) perform the function of protection and help in dehiscence." },

  { id: 335, topic: "Wind Pollination Adaptations", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 335 Image of a wind-pollinated grass-like plant.jpg", q: "The given plant shows all adaptations for pollination, except", options: ["Light and non-sticky pollen", "Well exposed stamens", "Presence of nectaries", "Flowers packed into inflorescence"], correct: 2, explanation: "The image represents a wind-pollinated (anemophilous) plant. Wind-pollinated plants have light pollen, exposed stamens, and packed inflorescences, but they do NOT have nectaries. Nectar is a floral reward meant exclusively for biotic pollinators (insects, birds)." },

  { id: 336, topic: "Abiotic Pollination", hots: true, q: "Consider the following statements and choose the correct option.<br><b>Statement A:</b> Only a small proportion of plants use abiotic agents.<br><b>Statement B:</b> Pollen grains coming in contact with stigma is a chance factor in both wind and water pollination.", options: ["Only statement A is correct", "Only statement B is correct", "Both statements A and B are correct", "Both statements A and B are incorrect"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT directly confirms both facts: 'Only a small proportion of plants use abiotic agents. Pollen grains coming in contact with the stigma is a chance factor in both wind and water pollination.' To compensate, these plants produce enormous amounts of pollen." },

  { id: 337, topic: "Embryo Sac Composition", hots: true, q: "The numbers of egg cell, helper cell and central cell in a normal embryo sac of a typical dicot plant are respectively", options: ["1, 2 and 2", "1, 2 and 1", "2, 3 and 1", "2, 2 and 2"], correct: 1, explanation: "A typical mature Polygonum type embryo sac is 7-celled. It contains 1 egg cell and 2 helper cells (synergids) constituting the egg apparatus, 3 antipodal cells, and 1 large central cell. Therefore, the respective numbers are 1, 2, and 1." },

  { id: 338, topic: "Floral Parts & Post-Fertilization", hots: true, q: "Match Column-I with Column-II and select the correct option.<br><b>Column - I</b><br>a. Calyx<br>b. Androecium<br>c. Pericarp<br>d. Perisperm<br><b>Column - II</b><br>(i) Fruit wall<br>(ii) Non-essential whorl<br>(iii) Persistent nucellus<br>(iv) Essential whorl", options: ["a(ii), b(iv), c(iii), d(i)", "a(iv), b(ii), c(i), d(iii)", "a(ii), b(iv), c(i), d(iii)", "a(iii), b(iv), c(i), d(ii)"], correct: 2, explanation: "The Calyx (sepals) is an accessory or non-essential whorl (ii). The Androecium is a reproductive, essential whorl (iv). The Pericarp is the ovary wall that develops into the fruit wall (i). Perisperm is the remnant persistent nucellus in seeds like black pepper (iii)." },

  { id: 339, topic: "Post-Fertilization Development", hots: true, q: "Choose the incorrect match with respect to development.", options: ["Fertilized egg cell → Embryo", "Ovule → Seed", "Two polar nucleus + male gamete → PEN", "Synergid → Perisperm"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 explains that synergids degenerate after fertilization. The perisperm is actually the residual, persistent nucellus (found in seeds like black pepper and beet), not derived from synergids. The other matches are standard post-fertilization events." },

  { id: 340, topic: "Microsporangium Wall Layers", hots: true, q: "α-cellulosic fibrous bands are associated with which of the anther wall layer?", options: ["Epidermis", "Endothecium", "Middle layer", "Tapetum"], correct: 1, explanation: "According to botanical anatomy, the endothecium develops fibrous thickenings of α-cellulose (often with traces of lignin) on its inner tangential and radial walls, which are hygroscopic and help in the dehiscence of the anther. Epidermis and middle layers lack these bands." },

  { id: 341, topic: "Tapetum Functions", hots: true, q: "Which of the following features are associated with tapetum?<br><b>(A)</b> Polyploidy<br><b>(B)</b> Polyteny<br><b>(C)</b> Sporopollenin secretion<br><b>(D)</b> Compatibility proteins secretion", options: ["A and C only", "A and B only", "A, B and C only", "All A, B, C and D"], correct: 3, explanation: "Tapetal cells possess dense cytoplasm and usually undergo endomitosis leading to polyploidy and polyteny. They secrete sporopollenin (forming exine), pollenkitt, and compatibility/incompatibility proteins onto the pollen grains. Thus, all statements are correct." },

  { id: 342, topic: "Female Gametophyte Development", hots: true, q: "Development of female gametophyte in angiosperms", options: ["Starts through microspores", "Is always tetrasporic", "Occurs within the ovule", "Is ex-situ"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT confirms that the female gametophyte (embryo sac) develops from a functional megaspore, entirely within the nucellus of the ovule (in-situ). It is mostly monosporic, not always tetrasporic." },

  { id: 343, topic: "Pollen Grain Structure", hots: true, q: "Vegetative cell of pollen grain", options: ["Is diploid", "Possess irregular shaped nucleus", "Lacks food matter", "Is smaller than generative cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'The vegetative cell is bigger, has abundant food reserve and a large irregularly shaped nucleus.' The generative cell is smaller and floats in its cytoplasm." },

  { id: 344, topic: "Pollen Allergy", hots: true, q: "Pollen allergy is commonly caused by the pollen grains of", options: ["Parthenium", "Rosa", "Brassica", "Pisum"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT highlights: 'Parthenium or carrot grass that came into India as a contaminant with imported wheat, has become ubiquitous in occurrence and causes pollen allergy.' Rosa, Brassica, and Pisum do not typically cause widespread airborne allergies." },

  { id: 345, topic: "Pollen Tube Entry", hots: true, q: "Entry of pollen tube inside the ovule in most of the flowering plants is through", options: ["Micropyle", "Chalaza", "Integument", "Funicle"], correct: 0, explanation: "In the majority of flowering plants, the pollen tube enters the ovule through the micropyle, a condition known as porogamy. Filiform apparatus in the synergids present at the micropylar end guides this entry." },

  { id: 346, topic: "Gynoecium Structure", hots: true, q: "Syncarpous condition is found in", options: ["Michelia", "Papaver and Hibiscus", "Papaver and Michelia", "Hibiscus and Michelia"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT explicitly shows diagrams of a multicarpellary, syncarpous (fused carpels) pistil of Papaver and a multicarpellary, apocarpous (free carpels) gynoecium of Michelia. Hibiscus also has a typical syncarpous ovary. Thus, option 2 is correct." },

  { id: 347, topic: "Tapetum Secretions", hots: true, q: "Find odd one out with respect to secretions from tapetum.", options: ["Compatibility proteins", "Pollenkitt", "Sporopollenin", "Callose"], correct: 3, explanation: "The tapetum secretes sporopollenin, pollenkitt, compatibility proteins, and the enzyme callase. Callose, however, is synthesized by the microspore mother cell (forming the callose wall around the tetrad). The tapetum secretes callase to degrade this callose, not the callose itself." },

  { id: 348, topic: "Pollen Viability", hots: true, q: "Which of the following family lose their pollen viability within 30 minutes?", options: ["Poaceae", "Leguminosae", "Rosaceae", "Solanaceae"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'In some cereals such as rice and wheat, pollen grains lose viability within 30 minutes of their release.' Wheat and rice belong to the family Poaceae. Members of Leguminosae, Rosaceae, and Solanaceae retain viability for months." },

  { id: 349, topic: "Seeds", hots: true, q: "Perispermic seeds are present in", options: ["Beet and black pepper", "Apple and pear", "Banana and beet", "Black pepper and gram"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT explicitly provides examples for perisperm: 'Occasionally, in some seeds such as black pepper and beet, remnants of nucellus are also persistent. This residual, persistent nucellus is the perisperm.'" },

  { id: 350, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "Self incompatibility", options: ["Prevents cross pollination", "Allows pollen grains of other flowers of the same plant to fertilise the ovule", "Prevents autogamy", "Does not allow the germination of pollen grains of other species on the stigma"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT defines self-incompatibility as a genetic mechanism to prevent self-pollen (from the same flower or other flowers of the same plant) from fertilizing the ovules. By preventing fertilization from the same genetic source, it strictly prevents autogamy (and geitonogamy)." },

  { id: 351, topic: "Male Gametophyte", hots: true, q: "Two celled male gametophyte of angiosperms", options: ["Is formed by in situ development of pollen grain", "Includes tube cell and one male gamete", "Includes two generative cells", "Is a result of post pollination development"], correct: 0, explanation: "The 2-celled stage of the pollen grain (vegetative cell + generative cell) develops 'in situ' (inside the microsporangium) before it is shed. It does not contain two generative cells, nor does it contain a mature male gamete yet. Post-pollination development yields the 3-celled stage." },

  { id: 352, topic: "Apomixis", hots: true, q: "Select the incorrect statement with respect to apomixis.", options: ["Production of seed without fertilisation", "Mimics asexual reproduction", "Present in some species of Asteraceae and grasses", "Genetically controlled"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Although apomixis is a form of asexual reproduction, it mimics sexual reproduction.' Option 2 is incorrect because it says apomixis mimics asexual reproduction, whereas the reality is the exact opposite." },

  { id: 353, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "The outbreeding device where pollen release and stigma receptivity are not synchronised is", options: ["Prepotency", "Incompatibility", "Dicliny", "Dichogamy"], correct: 3, explanation: "Dichogamy is the condition where the anthers and stigma mature at different times (either protandry or protogyny) to prevent self-pollination. Dicliny means unisexuality." },

  { id: 354, topic: "Double Fertilization", hots: true, q: "How many total haploid nuclei participate in double fertilization?", options: ["Three", "Two", "Five", "Ten"], correct: 2, explanation: "Double fertilization involves syngamy (1 male gamete + 1 egg cell = 2 haploid nuclei) and triple fusion (1 male gamete + 2 polar nuclei = 3 haploid nuclei). The sum is 2 + 3 = 5 haploid nuclei." },

  { id: 355, topic: "Pollination Agencies", hots: true, q: "Unisexuality of flowers in monoecious plant prevents", options: ["Autogamy, but not geitonogamy", "Both geitonogamy and xenogamy", "Both autogamy and geitonogamy", "Geitonogamy, but not xenogamy"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT explicitly provides the example: 'If both male and female flowers are present on the same plant such as castor and maize (monoecious), it prevents autogamy but not geitonogamy.'" },

  { id: 356, topic: "Tapetum Functions", hots: true, q: "Select the functions associated with tapetum.<br><b>(i)</b> Nutrition to the developing microspores<br><b>(ii)</b> Pollen kit synthesis<br><b>(iii)</b> Sporopollenin and compatibility protein secretion", options: ["(i) & (ii) only", "(ii) only", "(i) & (iii) only", "All (i), (ii) & (iii)"], correct: 3, explanation: "The tapetum is the innermost nourishing layer of the anther. Aside from nutrition (i), its cells secrete pollenkitt (sticky substance in entomophilous plants) (ii), and contribute to the exine by secreting sporopollenin and compatibility proteins (iii)." },

  { id: 357, topic: "Seed Dormancy", hots: true, q: "The moisture content of dormant seed decreases by mass up to", options: ["10-15%", "20-50%", "50-70%", "1-2%"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As the seed matures, its water content is reduced and seeds become relatively dry (10-15 per cent moisture by mass). The general metabolic activity of the embryo slows down.'" },

  { id: 358, topic: "Ovule Types", hots: true, q: "The most common type of ovule found in 82% of angiosperm is", options: ["Orthotropous", "Anatropous", "Amphitropous", "Hemi-anatropous"], correct: 1, explanation: "The anatropous ovule, where the body is completely inverted so that the micropyle lies close to the hilum, is the most common type, found in about 82% of angiosperm families." },

  { id: 359, topic: "Pollen Tube Entry", hots: true, q: "Entry of pollen tube into the ovule takes place through<br><b>a.</b> Micropyle<br><b>b.</b> Chalaza<br><b>c.</b> Integument", options: ["Only a", "Only a and b", "Only c", "All a, b and c"], correct: 3, explanation: "While entry through the micropyle (porogamy) is the most common, pollen tubes can also enter the ovule through the chalaza (chalazogamy, e.g., Casuarina) or through the integuments (mesogamy, e.g., Cucurbita). However, entry into the embryo sac always happens at the micropylar end." },

  { id: 360, topic: "Egg Apparatus", hots: true, q: "The correct polarity of nucleus and central vacuole in the egg is", options: ["Nucleus towards chalazal end and central vacuole towards micropylar end", "Nucleus towards micropylar end and central vacuole towards chalazal end", "Nucleus and central vacuole both towards micropylar end", "Nucleus and central vacuole both towards chalazal end"], correct: 0, explanation: "In the egg cell, the polarity is inverted relative to the synergids. The nucleus of the egg cell is located towards the chalazal end, and the prominent central vacuole is situated towards the micropylar end." },

  { id: 361, topic: "Endosperm", hots: true, q: "In coconut, the nature of endosperm is", options: ["Starchy", "Oily", "Cellulosic", "Hemicellulosic"], correct: 1, explanation: "The cellular endosperm of the coconut (the white kernel) is highly rich in fats and oils, which is why coconut oil is extracted from it. It is not primarily starchy or cellulosic." },

  { id: 362, topic: "Morphology of Floral Parts", hots: true, q: "Find out the incorrect statement.", options: ["Carpel is a type of megasporophyll", "Corolla is a non-essential whorl of flower", "Ovule is a non-integumented microsporangium", "Flower is a modified shoot"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT defines the ovule as an 'integumented megasporangium', not a microsporangium. The anther contains the microsporangia." },

  { id: 363, topic: "Reproduction Features", hots: true, q: "Find the incorrect match.", options: ["Tapetal cell - Low DNA content", "Polyembryony - Citrus", "Cleistogamy - Commelina", "Perisperm - Persistent nucellus"], correct: 0, explanation: "Tapetal cells frequently undergo endomitosis, becoming multinucleate or polyploid. Therefore, they have a high DNA content, not a low one. The other matches are standard examples from NCERT." },

  { id: 364, topic: "Dicot Embryo", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 364 Image of typical dicot embryo.jpg", q: "Examine the figure given below and select the correct option w.r.t the four part A, B, C and D correctly.", options: ["Plumule, Hypocotyl, Cotyledon, Radicle", "Hypocotyl, Plumule, Cotyledon, Root Cap", "Hypocotyl, Cotyledon, Hypocotyl, Radicle", "Plumule, Cotyledon, Hypocotyl, Root Cap"], correct: 3, explanation: "Based on the NCERT diagram of a typical dicot embryo: A is the Plumule (shoot tip), B points to the Cotyledons, C is the Hypocotyl (portion below the cotyledonary axis), and D points to the Root cap at the tip of the radicle." },

  { id: 365, topic: "Apomixis", hots: true, q: "If hybrids are made into apomicts, there is", options: ["Segregation of characters in the offsprings", "No segregation of characters in the hybrid progeny", "Chance of cross fertilisation", "Negligible seed production"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT highlights the immense agricultural value of apomixis: 'If these hybrids are made into apomicts, there is no segregation of characters in the hybrid progeny. Then the farmers can keep on using the hybrid seeds to raise new crop year after year...'" },

  { id: 366, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "Select the odd one w.r.t. outbreeding device.", options: ["Unisexuality", "Dichogamy", "Homogamy", "Self-incompatibility"], correct: 2, explanation: "Homogamy occurs when the anthers and stigmas of a bisexual flower mature at the same time, promoting inbreeding (self-pollination). Unisexuality, dichogamy, and self-incompatibility are outbreeding devices designed to discourage self-pollination." },

  { id: 367, topic: "Pollination Vectors", hots: true, q: "Flowers secreting foul odours are pollinated by", options: ["Birds", "Beetles", "Water", "Snakes"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT notes: 'To sustain animal visits, the flowers have to provide rewards... flowers pollinated by flies and beetles secrete foul odours to attract these animals.'" },

  { id: 368, topic: "Pollination Types", hots: true, q: "Read the following statements and choose the option which is true for them.<br><b>A.</b> Hydrophily is limited to about 30 genera, mostly dicots.<br><b>B.</b> Presence of a single ovule in each ovary is an adaptation of anemophily.", options: ["Both A and B are correct", "A is correct and B is incorrect", "A is incorrect and B is correct", "Both A and B are incorrect"], correct: 2, explanation: "Statement A is incorrect because NCERT states water pollination is limited to about 30 genera, mostly monocotyledons (not dicots). Statement B is correct, as wind-pollinated flowers often pack many flowers into an inflorescence and possess a single ovule per ovary." },

  { id: 369, topic: "Ploidy Levels", hots: true, q: "Which of the following combination are diploid?", options: ["Integument, funicle, nucellus", "Antipodals, PEN, integument", "PEN, funicle, nucellus", "Nucellus, antipodals, integument"], correct: 0, explanation: "Integument, funicle, and nucellus are maternal sporophytic tissues, making them all diploid (2n). Antipodals are haploid (n). PEN is triploid (3n)." },

  { id: 370, topic: "Ploidy Calculations", hots: true, q: "When a diploid male plant is crossed with a tetraploid female plant of the same angiospermic species, the ploidy level of endosperm cells in the resulting seed is", options: ["Pentaploid", "Tetraploid", "Diploid", "Triploid"], correct: 0, explanation: "The tetraploid female (4n) produces an embryo sac where the central cell has two polar nuclei of 2n each (Total central cell = 4n). The diploid male (2n) produces a haploid male gamete (n). Primary Endosperm Nucleus (PEN) = 4n + n = 5n (Pentaploid)." },

  { id: 371, topic: "Pollen Wall Composition", hots: true, q: "The intine of pollen grain is made up of <b>A</b> and <b>B</b>. Select the correct option for A and B.", options: ["A- Cellulose, B - Sporopollenin", "A Cellulose, B- Hemicellulose", "A Cellulose, B- Pectin", "A-Sporopollenin, B Pectin"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 details: 'The inner wall of the pollen grain is called the intine. It is a thin and continuous layer made up of cellulose and pectin.'" },

  { id: 372, topic: "Cross Pollination", hots: true, q: "Disadvantage of cross pollination is<br><b>a.</b> Wasteful process in terms of pollen loss<br><b>b.</b> Undesirable traits may be introduce<br><b>c.</b> Pollination is a chance factor", options: ["Only a and b", "Only b and c", "Only a", "All a, b and c"], correct: 3, explanation: "Cross-pollination relies on external agents (wind, water, animals), making it a chance factor and causing massive pollen wastage. Furthermore, it allows for genetic recombination, which can sometimes introduce less desirable traits compared to a highly adapted parent." },

  { id: 373, topic: "Reproduction Mechanisms", hots: true, q: "Match the given columns and select the correct option.<br><b>Column I</b><br>(A) In-vitro pollen germination<br>(B) Artificial hybridisation<br>(C) Triple fusion<br>(D) Adventive embryony<br><b>Column II</b><br>(i) Endosperm<br>(ii) Emasculation and Bagging<br>(iii) Sporophytic budding<br>(iv) Hanging drop method", options: ["A-(iv); B-(ii); C-(i); D-(iii)", "A-(iv); B-(ii); C-(iii); D-(i)", "A-(ii); B-(iv); C-(iii); D-(i)", "A-(iv); B-(iii); C-(ii); D-(i)"], correct: 0, explanation: "In-vitro pollen germination is observed using the hanging drop method (iv). Artificial hybridization involves emasculation and bagging (ii). Triple fusion results in the formation of the endosperm (i). Adventive embryony is a form of apomixis involving sporophytic budding (iii)." },

  { id: 374, topic: "Fertilization Events", hots: true, q: "Refer the given statements and select the correct option.<br><b>A.</b> Pollen tube ruptures inside one of the synergids.<br><b>B.</b> Antipodal cell nucleus gets transformed into primary endosperm nucleus (PEN).", options: ["Both A and B are correct", "Both A and B are incorrect", "Only A is correct", "Only B is correct"], correct: 2, explanation: "Statement A is correct; the pollen tube releases its contents into one of the synergids. Statement B is incorrect because PEN is formed by the fusion of the central cell (polar nuclei) and a male gamete, not the antipodal cell nucleus." },

  { id: 375, topic: "Pollination", hots: true, q: "Consider the following statements, stating as true (T) or false (F) and select the correct option.<br>I. All aquatic plants are pollinated by water<br>II. Wind pollination is quite common in grasses<br>III. Flowers of animal pollinated plants are often specifically adapted for a particular species of animal<br>IV. Majority of plants use abiotic agents for pollination", options: ["T, F, T, T", "F, T, T, F", "F, F, F, T", "T, F, F, F"], correct: 1, explanation: "I is False (e.g., Water hyacinth uses insects). II is True (wind pollination is very common in grasses). III is True (co-evolution is frequent in zoophily). IV is False (Majority of plants use biotic agents for pollination, per NCERT)." },

  { id: 376, topic: "Ploidy Calculations", hots: true, q: "In a flowering plant a tetraploid male plant is cross pollinated with a diploid female plant of the same angiospermic species. What would be the ploidy of endosperm and embryo developed respectively?", options: ["5n and 2n", "4n and 3n", "3n and 3n", "3n and 2n"], correct: 1, explanation: "Female is diploid (2n) → egg is (n), central cell has 2 polar nuclei (n+n). Male is tetraploid (4n) → male gametes are (2n). Embryo = Egg (n) + Male gamete (2n) = 3n. Endosperm = Central Cell (n+n) + Male gamete (2n) = 4n." },

  { id: 377, topic: "Geitonogamy", hots: true, q: "Monoecious condition of plants having unisexual flowers favours", options: ["Autogamy", "Cleistogamy", "True self pollination", "Geitonogamy"], correct: 3, explanation: "In monoecious plants (like castor and maize), both male and female flowers are on the same plant. Because the flowers are unisexual, autogamy (self-pollination within the same flower) is impossible. However, geitonogamy (pollination between different flowers of the same plant) is favoured." },

  { id: 378, topic: "Fruits and Seeds", hots: true, q: "Find the incorrect match.", options: ["Monosporic embryo sac - Oenothera", "Free nuclear endosperm - Coconut", "True fruit - Apple", "Perispermic seed - Beet"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT explicitly lists the apple, strawberry, and cashew as examples of false fruits, because the thalamus contributes to fruit formation. Therefore, matching Apple to 'True fruit' is incorrect." },

  { id: 379, topic: "Pollination Types", hots: true, q: "Which one is not the adaptive features of entomophilous flower?", options: ["Winged pollen grain", "Colourful and scented flower", "Presence of nectaries", "Floral reward for insects"], correct: 0, explanation: "Winged pollen grains are an adaptation for anemophily (wind pollination), famously seen in gymnosperms like Pinus, to help them float in the air. Entomophilous (insect-pollinated) flowers are typically colourful, scented, and offer floral rewards like nectar and edible pollen." },

  { id: 380, topic: "Dicot Embryo Development", hots: true, q: "Which one is correct developmental sequence for dicot embryo?", options: ["Octant → Mature embryo → Heart shaped", "Heart shaped → Globular → Mature embryo", "Globular → Heart shaped → Mature embryo", "Globular → Octant → Heart shaped"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 explicitly states the sequence of embryogeny: 'The zygote gives rise to the proembryo and subsequently to the globular, heart-shaped and mature embryo.'" },

  { id: 381, topic: "Pollen Grain Structure", hots: true, q: "Which of the following is wrong?", options: ["Pollen grains are about 25-50 μm in diameter", "Exine is the outer layer of pollen", "Intine is made of sporopollenin", "Generative cell is spindle shaped"], correct: 2, explanation: "The intine is the inner wall of the pollen grain and is composed of cellulose and pectin. The exine (outer layer) is the one made of the highly resistant organic material sporopollenin." },

  { id: 382, topic: "Double Fertilization", hots: true, q: "Which of the following is correct for double fertilisation?", options: ["Only two gametes are involved", "Syngamy occurs twice", "It results in the formation of two diploid cells", "Characteristic feature of both dicots and monocots"], correct: 3, explanation: "Double fertilization (syngamy + triple fusion) is a unique and defining characteristic event for all angiosperms, which includes both dicots and monocots. It involves three gametes (two male gametes and one egg cell) and results in one diploid cell (zygote) and one triploid cell (PEN)." },

  { id: 383, topic: "Inbreeding vs Outbreeding", hots: true, q: "Which of the following adaptations of flowers/plant promote inbreeding depression?", options: ["Self incompatibility, heterostyly", "Homogamy, bisexuality, cleistogamy", "Bud pollination, dichogamy", "Dioecy, Protandry, herkogamy"], correct: 1, explanation: "Inbreeding depression is caused by continuous self-pollination. Adaptations that promote self-pollination include homogamy (synchronised maturity of anthers and stigma), bisexuality (hermaphrodite flowers), and cleistogamy (flowers that never open). The other options are outbreeding devices designed to prevent inbreeding." },

  { id: 384, topic: "Sporopollenin", hots: true, q: "Sporopollenin is", options: ["Present in exine", "Non degradable inorganic compound", "Released from sporogenous cells", "Produced by pollen grains on the stigma"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The hard outer layer called the exine is made up of sporopollenin which is one of the most resistant organic material known.' It is organic (not inorganic), and it is secreted by the tapetum cells of the anther wall, not the sporogenous cells." },

  { id: 385, topic: "Life Cycle Sequences", hots: true, q: "Find out the correct developmental sequence in the life cycle of flowering plants.", options: ["Pollen mother cell → megaspore tetrad", "Nucellus → Megaspore mother cell", "Secondary nucleus → PEN", "Both (2) and (3)"], correct: 3, explanation: "Both sequences 2 and 3 are correct. During megasporogenesis, a cell of the nucellus differentiates into the Megaspore Mother Cell (MMC). During double fertilization, the secondary nucleus (formed by the fusion of two polar nuclei) fuses with a male gamete to form the Primary Endosperm Nucleus (PEN)." },

  { id: 386, topic: "Anther Wall", hots: true, q: "Endothecium layer of anther wall is also called as fibrous layer due to the presence of", options: ["α-cellulosic thickening on inner tangential wall", "Non-hygroscopic thickening on outer tangential wall", "α-cellulose thickening on outer tangential wall", "Ligno-suberin on inner tangential and radial wall"], correct: 0, explanation: "The endothecium develops fibrous bands of α-cellulose on its inner tangential and radial walls. These bands are hygroscopic and create tension as the anther dries, aiding in dehiscence." },

  { id: 387, topic: "Double Fertilization", hots: true, q: "Double fertilization is different from single fertilization because of the presence of", options: ["Syngamy", "Seed", "Triple fusion", "Megaspore and microspore"], correct: 2, explanation: "In angiosperms, double fertilization involves two distinct fusion events: syngamy (fusion of egg and male gamete, which happens in other plants too) and triple fusion (fusion of a second male gamete with two polar nuclei to form endosperm). Triple fusion makes it 'double' fertilization." },

  { id: 388, topic: "Pollen Allergy", hots: true, q: "Allergic pollen grains belong to a group of plant species which are mostly", options: ["Entomophilous", "Anemophilous", "Ornithophilous", "Hydrophilous"], correct: 1, explanation: "Anemophilous (wind-pollinated) plants, like Parthenium and grasses, produce massive quantities of light, airborne pollen grains. These easily enter the human respiratory tract, causing severe allergies and bronchial afflictions." },

  { id: 389, topic: "Pollen Taxonomy", hots: true, q: "The most important pollen characteristics used as taxonomic tool in classification is", options: ["Chemical nature of exine and intine", "Shape and size of pollen grain", "Ridges, tubercles, spines etc. on the surface of pollen grains provided by exine", "Sculpturing over the surface of pollen grains provided by intine"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT notes: 'Pollen grains of many species... exhibit a fascinating array of patterns and designs.' The exine forms distinct sculpturing (ridges, spines, etc.) that is highly species-specific and serves as a crucial tool for plant taxonomy (palynology)." },

  { id: 390, topic: "Synergid Structure", hots: true, q: "Co-operative cells have", options: ["Filiform apparatus at the micropylar tip", "Filiform apparatus in the entire wall", "Micropylar vacuole and central nucleus", "Non-vacuolated cytoplasm without cell wall"], correct: 0, explanation: "Co-operative cells refer to the synergids (helper cells). NCERT details that synergids have special cellular thickenings at the micropylar tip called the filiform apparatus, which play an important role in guiding the pollen tube." },

  { id: 391, topic: "Ploidy Calculation", hots: true, q: "Find out the ploidy of oospore, coleoptile and aleurone layer cells developed from the hexaploid female and diploid male parents.", options: ["4n, 3n, 3n respectively", "4n, 4n, 8n respectively", "3n, 3n, 4n respectively", "4n, 4n, 7n respectively"], correct: 3, explanation: "Female is hexaploid (6n) → Egg is 3n; Central cell has 2 polar nuclei (3n + 3n = 6n). Male is diploid (2n) → Male gamete is n. Oospore (zygote) = Egg (3n) + Male Gamete (n) = 4n. Coleoptile (part of embryo) = 4n. Aleurone layer (outer layer of endosperm) = Central Cell (6n) + Male Gamete (n) = 7n." },

  { id: 392, topic: "Embryo Sac Development", hots: true, q: "Functional megaspore develops into Polygonum type of female gametophyte by ______ divisions", options: ["One meiotic and two successive mitotic", "Three successive mitotic divisions", "One meiotic and one mitotic divisions", "Two meiotic and one mitotic divisions"], correct: 1, explanation: "The functional megaspore is already haploid (formed after meiosis of the MMC). To form the 8-nucleate Polygonum embryo sac, its nucleus undergoes three successive free-nuclear mitotic divisions." },

  { id: 393, topic: "Pollen Shedding", hots: true, q: "Pollen grain in angiosperms", options: ["Is derived from a megaspore", "Remains permanently embedded in the nucellus", "Is generally shed in 2-celled stage", "Is 7-celled and 8 nucleated structure"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'In over 60 per cent of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at this 2-celled stage (vegetative cell and generative cell).'" },

  { id: 394, topic: "Anemophily Adaptations", hots: true, q: "In anemophilous flowers", options: ["Stigmas are usually unbranched and sticky", "Stigmas are exposed and feathery", "Pollen grains are heavier and sticky", "Odour is commonly present"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT lists wind-pollination adaptations: pollen grains are light and non-sticky, stamens are well-exposed, and they often have large, feathery stigmas to easily trap air-borne pollen grains." },

  { id: 395, topic: "Monocot Embryo", hots: true, q: "Coleorhiza is", options: ["Part of embryonal axis in between cotyledonary node and radicle", "Part of embryonal axis in between cotyledonary node and plumule", "Covering around plumule", "Covering around radicle"], correct: 3, explanation: "In a monocot embryo (like grasses), the lower end of the embryonal axis has the radicle and root cap enclosed in an undifferentiated sheath called the coleorhiza." },

  { id: 396, topic: "Apomixis Importance", hots: true, q: "Apomictic seeds offer which of the following advantages to angiosperms?", options: ["Shows better dispersal strategies", "Dormancy of seed allows it to be utilised as food source throughout the year", "Forms the basis of agriculture", "Asexual seed development allows hybrid seed to maintain their superior characters"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT points out that if hybrids are made into apomicts, there is no segregation of characters. This allows farmers to utilize the superior hybrid traits year after year without buying expensive hybrid seeds annually." },

  { id: 397, topic: "Wind Pollination Features", hots: true, q: "Which of the given is not related to wind pollination?", options: ["Flowers are nectarless, odourless and colourless", "Versatile stamens in grasses", "Dry, unbranched short stigma", "Winged pollens in Pinus"], correct: 2, explanation: "Wind-pollinated flowers require large, feathery, and exposed stigmas (not short and unbranched) to effectively catch pollen floating in the air. The other options are characteristic of anemophily." },

  { id: 398, topic: "Ploidy Levels", hots: true, q: "Find the ploidy level of central cell at maturity, perisperm cell and endosperm cell for sunflower.", options: ["2n, 2n, 3n", "n, 2n, 3n", "2n, 3n, 3n", "n, n, 3n"], correct: 0, explanation: "Sunflower is a typical diploid angiosperm (2n). At maturity, the central cell contains two haploid polar nuclei that fuse to form a secondary nucleus (n + n = 2n). The perisperm is persistent nucellus, a maternal tissue (2n). The endosperm is formed by triple fusion (2n + n) and is triploid (3n)." },

  { id: 399, topic: "Ploidy Calculations", hots: true, q: "Ploidy of endosperm and zygote would be _____ and _____ respectively, if a octaploid female and tetraploid male plants are crossed.", options: ["10n, 6n", "6n, 10n", "3n, 2n", "20n, 8n"], correct: 0, explanation: "Female is octaploid (8n) → Egg is 4n. Central Cell = 4n + 4n = 8n. Male is tetraploid (4n) → Male Gamete is 2n. Endosperm = Central Cell (8n) + Male Gamete (2n) = 10n. Zygote = Egg (4n) + Male Gamete (2n) = 6n." },

  { id: 400, topic: "Male Gametophyte Development", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 400 Images showing stages D=Microspore, B=Vacuolation, C=Asymmetric spindle, A=2-celled pollen.jpg", q: "Find out the correct order (w.r.t. development of male gametophyte).", options: ["D → A → C → B", "D → B → A → C", "D → C → B → A", "A → B → C → D"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT diagrams the sequence: The newly formed microspore (D) expands and develops a large central vacuole (B). It then undergoes asymmetric mitotic division with an asymmetric spindle (C) to form a large vegetative cell and a small generative cell, giving the 2-celled pollen grain (A)." },

  { id: 401, topic: "Microsporangium Wall", hots: true, q: "In a transverse section, a typical microsporangium of flowering plants is generally surrounded by four wall layers the epidermis, endothecium, middle layers and the tapetum. Cells of the tapetum", options: ["Possess dense cytoplasm and generally have more than one nucleus", "Nourish the developing microspores as well as megaspores", "Help in dehiscence of anther", "Perform the function of protection"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT explicitly states: 'Cells of the tapetum possess dense cytoplasm and generally have more than one nucleus.' They nourish microspores only, not megaspores. Dehiscence and protection are functions of the outer three layers." },

  { id: 402, topic: "Embryo Sac Structure", hots: true, q: "Egg apparatus consists of", options: ["Central cell + egg cell", "Synergids + polar nuclei + egg cell", "Synergids + egg cell", "Antipodal cells + synergids + egg"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT describes the micropylar end of the embryo sac: 'Three cells are grouped together at the micropylar end and constitute the egg apparatus. The egg apparatus, in turn, consists of two synergids and one egg cell.'" },

  { id: 403, topic: "Anther Structure", hots: true, q: "A typical angiospermic anther", options: ["Is monothecous and bisporangiate", "Shows the two pollen sacs in an anther lobe which are separated internally by strip of fertile tissue", "Dithecous and tetrasporangiate", "Is a mass of homogeneous meristematic cells in mature stage"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A typical angiosperm anther is bilobed with each lobe having two theca, i.e., they are dithecous... The anther is a four-sided (tetragonal) structure consisting of four microsporangia located at the corners, two in each lobe.'" },

  { id: 404, topic: "Pollination in Zostera", hots: true, q: "What is correct statement for the pollination in Zostera plant?", options: ["Pollinated by fresh water", "Pollen grains are long and ribbon like", "Pollen grains are released on to the surface of marine water", "Female flowers reach the surface of water by the long and coiled stalk"], correct: 1, explanation: "Zostera is marine seagrass where female flowers remain submerged in water, and pollen grains are released inside the water. NCERT notes: 'Pollen grains in many such species are long, ribbon-like and they are carried passively inside the water...'" },

  { id: 405, topic: "Endosperm Development", hots: true, q: "In flowering plants, endosperm", options: ["Is pre-fertilizing tissue", "Development rarely involves free nuclear divisions", "Development precedes embryo development", "Is diploid tissue"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT explicitly states: 'Endosperm development precedes embryo development.' This is an adaptation to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo. It is a post-fertilization, triploid tissue (in angiosperms)." },

  { id: 406, topic: "Abiotic Pollination", hots: true, q: "Hydrophilous flowers are similar to anemophilous flowers in", options: ["Presence of nectar", "Absence of odour", "Presence of bright colour", "Absence of versatile anther"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both water-pollinated (hydrophilous) and wind-pollinated (anemophilous) flowers utilize abiotic agents. Consequently, they do not need to attract animal pollinators. As NCERT notes: 'Both wind and water pollinated flowers are not very colourful and do not produce nectar' (and lack odour)." },

  { id: 407, topic: "Sporopollenin Properties", hots: true, q: "The outer layer of pollen grain in non-archegoniate spermatophytes is made up of sporopollenin. This chemical", options: ["is one of the most resistant inorganic material", "Is temperature and enzyme resistant", "Is resistant for strong acids, not for alkali", "Is resistant for strong alkali, not for acids"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'sporopollenin which is one of the most resistant organic material known. It can withstand high temperatures and strong acids and alkali. No enzyme that degrades sporopollenin is so far known.'" },

  { id: 408, topic: "Pollen Properties", hots: true, q: "Mark the incorrect one.", options: ["Pollen consumption has been claimed to increase the performance of athletes and race horses", "Viability of pollen grain depends upon temperature, not humidity", "Pollen grains of a large number of species can be stored in liquid nitrogen for years", "Pollen grains of rice and wheat lose viability within the half an hour"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT explicitly states: 'The period for which pollen grains remain viable is highly variable and to some extent depends on the prevailing temperature and humidity.' Option 2 is incorrect because humidity is a major factor." },

  { id: 409, topic: "Pollen Grain Wall", hots: true, q: "The inner wall of the pollen grain in non-archegoniate embryophytes", options: ["Has prominent apertures", "Exhibits a fascinating array of patterns and designs", "Is pectocellulosic continuous layer", "Is thin and discontinuous layer"], correct: 2, explanation: "The inner wall is the intine. NCERT says: 'It is a thin and continuous layer made up of cellulose and pectin.' The exine (outer wall) has apertures (germ pores) and exhibits patterns." },

  { id: 410, topic: "Vegetative Cell", hots: true, q: "Vegetative cell of angiospermic pollen grain is characterised by", options: ["Less amount of food reserve and large size", "Small size and spindle shaped nucleus", "Haploid ploidy level and less amount of food reserve", "Abundant food reserve and irregularly shaped nucleus"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The vegetative cell is bigger, has abundant food reserve and a large irregularly shaped nucleus.'" },

  { id: 411, topic: "Ovule Anatomy", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 411 a=Hilum, b=Funicle, c=Inner integument, d=Nucellus, e=Embryo sac.jpg", q: "Find out the ploidy level of structures (a), (b), (c), (d) and (e) in the given diagram.", options: ["Diploid = (a), (b), (c), (d); haploid = (e)", "Haploid = (a), (b), (c); diploid = (d); triploid = (e)", "Haploid = (a), (b), (c), (d); triploid = (e)", "Haploid = (a), (b); diploid = (c), (d); triploid = (e)"], correct: 0, explanation: "The hilum, funicle, integuments, and nucellus are all maternal sporophytic tissues, meaning their cells are diploid (2n). The embryo sac (female gametophyte) develops after meiosis, so its constituent cells are haploid (n)." },

  { id: 412, topic: "Pollen Shedding Stage", hots: true, q: "Development of male gametes before pollination is present in approximately ____ of angiospermic plants.", options: ["60%", "80%", "10%", "40%"], correct: 3, explanation: "Male gametes are formed when the generative cell divides. NCERT states over 60% of angiosperms shed pollen at the 2-celled stage (gametes form after pollination). In the remaining ~40%, the generative cell divides before pollen is shed, meaning they are shed at the 3-celled stage (containing the male gametes)." },

  { id: 413, topic: "Endosperm Development", hots: true, q: "During the development of most common type of endosperm in flowering plants", options: ["PEN divides meiotically without wall formation", "Each karyokinesis is followed by wall formation", "Wall formation begins after achieving a multinucleate condition", "PEN divides mitotically and results into haploid nuclei"], correct: 2, explanation: "The most common type of endosperm is free-nuclear. The Primary Endosperm Nucleus (PEN) undergoes successive mitotic (not meiotic) divisions without cytokinesis to form a multinucleate state. Subsequently, cell wall formation occurs from the periphery inwards." },

  { id: 414, topic: "Embryo Sac Development", hots: true, q: "During the development of typical embryo sac from the functional megaspore", options: ["Free nuclear division takes place", "Cytokinesis is present after each karyokinesis", "Nuclear divisions are followed immediately by cell wall formation", "Cell walls are laid down after the 4-nucleated stage"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT highlights: 'It is of interest to note that these mitotic divisions are strictly free nuclear, that is, nuclear divisions are not followed immediately by cell wall formation.' Cell walls are laid down only after the 8-nucleate stage." },

  { id: 415, topic: "Dicot Embryo", hots: true, q: "In a typical dicotyledonous embryo, the cylindrical portion below the level of cotyledons is ______ that terminates at its lower end in the ______", options: ["Epicotyl, plumule", "Epicotyl, radicle", "Hypocotyl, radicle", "Hypocotyl, plumule"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT definition: 'The cylindrical portion below the level of cotyledons is hypocotyl that terminates at its lower end in the radicle or root tip.'" },

  { id: 416, topic: "Synergids", hots: true, q: "What is the incorrect statement for synergids?", options: ["Special thickening is absent at chalazal tip", "Acellular structure", "Have important role in guiding the pollen tubes", "Have filiform apparatus"], correct: 1, explanation: "Synergids are definite cells bounded by cell walls (except towards the chalazal end where they thin out), so they are not 'acellular structures'. They possess a filiform apparatus at the micropylar tip to guide pollen tubes." },

  { id: 417, topic: "Geitonogamy", hots: true, q: "Process involving transfer of pollen grains from the anther to the stigma of another flower of the same plant is", options: ["Genetically as well as functionally self pollination", "Functionally cross-pollination and genetically self-pollination", "Functionally as well as genetically cross pollination", "Genetically cross-pollination and functionally self pollination"], correct: 1, explanation: "This describes Geitonogamy. NCERT says: 'Although geitonogamy is functionally cross-pollination involving a pollinating agent, genetically it is similar to autogamy since the pollen grains come from the same plant.'" },

  { id: 418, topic: "Endosperm", hots: true, q: "Which of the following statement is correct for angiospermic endosperms?", options: ["Cannot be diploid", "Always triploid", "Nutritive tissue always", "Cannot be absent"], correct: 2, explanation: "The primary function of the endosperm, regardless of its ploidy, is to provide nutrition to the developing embryo. Exceptions exist regarding its ploidy (e.g., diploid in Oenothera) and its presence in mature seeds (absent in non-endospermic seeds like orchids and peas), but when present, its role is always nutritive." },

  { id: 419, topic: "Pollination by Water", hots: true, q: "Pollination by water is", options: ["Limited to about 30 families of dicots", "Very common in flowering plants", "More common in monocots than dicots", "More common abiotic method of pollination"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'Pollination by water is quite rare in flowering plants and is limited to about 30 genera, mostly monocotyledons.' Since it is mostly found in monocots, it is more common in monocots than dicots. Wind is the more common abiotic method." },

  { id: 420, topic: "Wind Pollination Adaptations", hots: true, q: "Wind pollinated flowers often", options: ["Have a single ovule in each ovary", "Produces light and sticky pollen grains", "Have sticky and inserted stigma", "Produces heavy and non-sticky pollen grains"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT explicitly notes: 'Wind pollinated flowers often have a single ovule in each ovary and numerous flowers packed into an inflorescence.' Their pollen is light and non-sticky (not sticky or heavy), and stigmas are exposed and feathery." },

  { id: 421, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "The device to prevent inbreeding in hermaphrodite flowers is all, except", options: ["Dicliny", "Protandry", "Presence of self-incompatibility", "Homogamy"], correct: 3, explanation: "Homogamy is the condition where the anthers and stigma of a bisexual flower mature at the exact same time, which promotes self-pollination (inbreeding). Dicliny (unisexuality), protandry (anthers mature first), and self-incompatibility prevent inbreeding." },

  { id: 422, topic: "Zoophily", hots: true, q: "Mark the incorrect statement for zoophily.", options: ["Lemurs, arboreal rodents and gecko lizard are pollinators", "Entomophily is not possible in small flowers", "Nectar and pollen grains are the usual floral rewards for insects", "Moth and Yucca cannot complete their life cycles without each other"], correct: 1, explanation: "Entomophily (insect pollination) is very much possible in small flowers. NCERT clarifies: 'When the flowers are small, a number of flowers are clustered into an inflorescence to make them conspicuous.' The other statements are factual examples from the text." },

  { id: 423, topic: "Hybrid Seeds", hots: true, q: "Mark the incorrect statement.", options: ["Hybrid seeds have to be produced every year", "Production of hybrid seeds is costly", "If the seeds collected from hybrids are sown, the progeny do not maintain hybrid characters", "Cultivation of hybrids has decreased productivity"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT highlights the immense value of hybrids: 'Cultivation of hybrids has tremendously increased productivity.' It has not decreased it. However, because hybrid traits segregate in the next generation, seeds must be purchased yearly, making it costly." },

  { id: 424, topic: "Ploidy Levels", hots: true, q: "Mark the odd one (w.r.t. ploidy level).", options: ["Testa", "Tapetum", "Perisperm", "Pericarp"], correct: 1, explanation: "Testa (seed coat), perisperm (persistent nucellus), and pericarp (fruit wall) are all typical diploid (2n) maternal sporophytic tissues. Tapetal cells, however, frequently undergo endomitosis to become multinucleate or highly polyploid (e.g., 4n or more)." },

  { id: 425, topic: "Monoecious vs Dioecious", hots: true, q: "Male and female plants are not separate in case of", options: ["Papaya and date-palm", "Mulberry and papaya", "Date-palm and mulberry", "Castor and maize"], correct: 3, explanation: "When male and female plants are not separate, the species is monoecious (bearing both male and female unisexual flowers on the same plant). NCERT gives Castor and Maize as examples of monoecious plants. Papaya and date palm are dioecious (separate male and female plants)." },

  { id: 426, topic: "Anther Dehiscence", hots: true, q: "Endothecium helps in the rupturing of anther lobe wall due to the presence of α-cellulose fibrous thickening on", options: ["Outer wall only", "Inner wall only", "Outer and radial walls only", "Inner tangential walls"], correct: 3, explanation: "The cells of the endothecium layer develop prominent fibrous thickenings of α-cellulose primarily on their inner tangential walls and radial walls. The outer walls remain thin. As the anther dries, these hygroscopic bands create tension that leads to dehiscence." },

  { id: 427, topic: "Embryo Sac Formation", hots: true, q: "How many total meiotic and mitotic divisions are required to produce a monosporic Polygonum embryo sac from megaspore mother cell?", options: ["3 divisions", "4 divisions", "2 divisions", "5 divisions"], correct: 1, explanation: "1 Megaspore Mother Cell (MMC) undergoes 1 meiotic division to form 4 haploid megaspores. Three degenerate. The single functional megaspore undergoes 3 successive free-nuclear mitotic divisions to form the 8-nucleate Polygonum embryo sac. Total = 1 meiosis + 3 mitoses = 4 divisions." },

  { id: 428, topic: "Abiotic Pollination", hots: true, q: "Which of the following is the common feature of anemophilous and hydrophilous plants?", options: ["Produce pollen grains coated with mucilage", "Scentless flowers and abundant nectar", "Flowers are not very colourful and do not produce nectar", "Non-sticky pollen grains and brightly colourful flowers"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Both wind and water pollinated flowers are not very colourful and do not produce nectar.' Since they do not rely on animals (insects, birds) for pollination, they do not expend energy producing colourful petals, scents, or nectar rewards." },

  { id: 429, topic: "Endosperm vs Embryo Development", hots: true, q: "Endosperm development precedes embryo development because", options: ["It is a product of triple fusion", "It provides nutrition to developing embryo", "It is larger than embryo", "Its development mostly occurs by free nuclear division in PEN"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT explains this adaptation: 'Endosperm development precedes embryo development. Why? The primary endosperm cell divides repeatedly... to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo.'" },

  { id: 430, topic: "Seed Anatomy", hots: true, q: "Remnants of nucellus in the seed is known as perisperm, which is found in all except", options: ["Black pepper", "Beet", "Castor", "Pea"], correct: 3, explanation: "Black pepper and beet are classic NCERT examples of perispermic seeds. Castor seed is endospermic but also retains a papery perisperm. Pea is an exalbuminous (non-endospermic) seed where all maternal nucellar tissue and endosperm are completely consumed by the developing embryo; it lacks perisperm." },

  { id: 431, topic: "Embryo Sac Structure", hots: true, q: "Highly vacuolated cytoplasm which is rich in reserve food is present in largest cell of embryo sac called", options: ["Central cell", "Antipodals", "Egg", "Synergids"], correct: 0, explanation: "The central cell is the largest cell of the embryo sac. It contains two polar nuclei, a large central vacuole, and cytoplasm rich in reserve food materials to support the early development of the endosperm post-fertilization." },

  { id: 432, topic: "Pollen Grain Divisions", hots: true, q: "Formation of asymmetrical spindle fibres can be observed when", options: ["Megaspore nuclei undergoes free nuclear mitotic divisions", "PEN undergoes free nuclear mitotic divisions", "Second mitosis occurs in pollen to produce two male gametes", "Pollen grain undergoes first mitosis to produce generative and vegetative cell"], correct: 3, explanation: "During the maturation of the pollen grain, the microspore nucleus divides mitotically. This specific first division is unequal and is characterized by the formation of an asymmetric spindle, resulting in a large vegetative cell and a small generative cell." },

  { id: 433, topic: "Cell Divisions in Gametogenesis", hots: true, q: "Total mitotic divisions required for the development of mature male gametophytes with gametes and female gametophyte respectively from 20 microspores and 20 megaspores in an angiosperm is", options: ["40 and 20", "10 and 20", "40 and 40", "40 and 60"], correct: 3, explanation: "1 microspore requires 2 mitotic divisions to form a mature 3-celled male gametophyte (veg + 2 male gametes). 20 × 2 = 40 mitoses. 1 functional megaspore requires 3 mitotic divisions to form an 8-nucleate female gametophyte. 20 × 3 = 60 mitoses." },

  { id: 434, topic: "Microsporogenesis", hots: true, q: "Read the following statements carefully and select the correct option.<br><b>a.</b> Tapetum cells possess dense cytoplasm and generally have more than one nucleus<br><b>b.</b> Sporopollenin is absent in the areas called germ pore<br><b>c.</b> Generative cell is small, spindle shaped with a irregularly shaped nuclei<br><b>d.</b> Spindle of first mitosis in pollen is asymmetric", options: ["a, b, c & d", "a, b & c", "a, c & d", "a, b & d"], correct: 3, explanation: "Statements a, b, and d are correct. Statement c is incorrect because the vegetative cell has the large irregularly shaped nucleus, whereas the generative cell is small, spindle-shaped with dense cytoplasm and a regular nucleus." },

  { id: 435, topic: "Seed Types", hots: true, q: "Endosperm persists in the mature seeds of", options: ["Pea", "Groundnut", "Gram", "Maize"], correct: 3, explanation: "Seeds that retain endosperm at maturity are called albuminous (endospermic) seeds. Examples include wheat, maize, barley, and castor. Pea, groundnut, and gram are ex-albuminous (non-endospermic) seeds where the endosperm is completely consumed." },

  { id: 436, topic: "Meiosis Calculations", hots: true, q: "How many meiotic divisions are required to produce 200 male gametes in a typical dicot plant?", options: ["50", "25", "100", "200"], correct: 1, explanation: "1 Pollen Mother Cell (PMC) undergoes 1 meiosis to produce 4 microspores (pollen grains). Each pollen grain produces 2 male gametes. So, 1 meiosis yields 8 male gametes. To produce 200 male gametes: 200 / 8 = 25 meiotic divisions." },

  { id: 437, topic: "Artificial Hybridization", hots: true, q: "Removal of anther from ______ flower ______ maturation of anther is called emasculation.", options: ["Unisexual, after", "Bisexual, before", "Unisexual, before", "Bisexual, after"], correct: 1, explanation: "Emasculation is the removal of anthers from the flower bud before the anther dehisces (matures), using a pair of forceps. It is only required if the female parent bears bisexual flowers to prevent self-pollination." },

  { id: 438, topic: "Pollen Grain Structure", hots: true, q: "In over 60% of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at two celled stage. Generative cell of this stage", options: ["Has dense cytoplasm", "Floats in the nucleoplasm of the vegetative cell", "Is diploid", "Is larger than tube cell"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'The generative cell is small and floats in the cytoplasm [not nucleoplasm] of the vegetative cell. It is spindle shaped with dense cytoplasm and a nucleus.' Both cells are haploid." },

  { id: 439, topic: "Pollen Exine", hots: true, q: "Choose the odd one out w.r.t. outer layer present in pollen grain.", options: ["Possesses most resistant inorganic material", "Possesses germ pores", "Exhibits fascinating array of patterns and designs", "It has enzyme resistant sporopollenin"], correct: 0, explanation: "The outer layer (exine) is made of sporopollenin, which is highly resistant. However, sporopollenin is an organic material (a complex polymer), not an inorganic material. This makes statement 1 the odd one out (incorrect factually)." },

  { id: 440, topic: "Male Gamete Carriers", hots: true, q: "Pollen grains are the carriers of male gametes in", options: ["Pinus, Chara", "Solanum, Oryza", "Marchantia, Allium", "Dryopteris, Fucus"], correct: 1, explanation: "Pollen grains are characteristic of spermatophytes (seed plants: gymnosperms and angiosperms). Solanum (potato/tomato family) and Oryza (rice) are angiosperms. Chara and Fucus are algae, Marchantia is a bryophyte, and Dryopteris is a pteridophyte, none of which produce pollen." },

  { id: 441, topic: "Pollen Grain Features", hots: true, q: "Find the incorrect statements w.r.t. pollen grain in angiospermic plants.<br><b>a.</b> Germ pores are areas in pollen wall where intine and sporopollenin are absent<br><b>b.</b> Vegetative cell is bigger, has abundant food reserve and a large irregularly shaped nucleus<br><b>c.</b> Fascinating array of patterns and designs are exhibited by exine wall<br><b>d.</b> In over 60 percent of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at 3-celled stage", options: ["c and d", "a and d", "b and d", "a and c"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement 'a' is incorrect because while sporopollenin is absent at germ pores, the intine is present and actually protrudes out through the pore as the pollen tube. Statement 'd' is incorrect because in over 60% of angiosperms, pollen is shed at the 2-celled stage." },

  { id: 442, topic: "Embryo Sac Diagram", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 442 Diagram Typical inverted fertilized embryo sac. Top (e) shows 2 cells, below it (b) is 1 cell, middle (a) is a nucleus inside a large cavity (c), bottom (d) shows 3 cells.jpg", q: "The figure given below shows fertilised embryo sac of the flowering plants. Which one set of two parts out of (a-e) have been correctly identified?", options: ["(a) Nucleolus; (c) Primary endosperm nucleus", "(e) Degenerating antipodal cells and zygote; (d) Degenerating synergids", "(b) Zygote; (a) Central cell", "(c) Primary endosperm cell; (e) Degenerating synergids"], correct: 3, explanation: "Based on the standard NCERT diagram of a fertilized embryo sac with the micropylar end at the top: (e) points to the two degenerating synergids, (b) is the Zygote, (a) is the Primary Endosperm Nucleus (PEN), (c) is the Primary Endosperm Cell (PEC), and (d) points to the three degenerating antipodals at the chalazal end." },

  { id: 443, topic: "Pollination Vectors", hots: true, q: "Most of the aquatic and land plants are pollinated by", options: ["Insects or wind", "Water and insects respectively", "Abiotic factors only", "Water and wind respectively"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT clarifies a common misconception: 'Not all aquatic plants use water for pollination. In a majority of aquatic plants such as water hyacinth and water lily... [they] are pollinated by insects or wind as in most of the land plants.'" },

  { id: 444, topic: "Embryo Sac & Pollination", hots: true, q: "Which one of the following statement is not true?", options: ["Filiform apparatus present at chalazal end of the synergids guides the entry of pollen tube", "Pollen-pistil interaction is a dynamic process involving pollen recognition followed by promotion or inhibition of the pollen", "Majority of insect pollinated flowers are large, colourful, fragrant and rich in nectar", "Apomixis is a form of asexual reproduction that mimics sexual reproduction"], correct: 0, explanation: "The filiform apparatus is located at the micropylar tip of the synergids, not the chalazal end. The chalazal end houses the antipodals. All other statements are standard correct facts from the NCERT." },

  { id: 445, topic: "Microsporogenesis Calculations", hots: true, q: "How many male gametes will be produced from 6 microspore mother cells after microsporogenesis and microgametogenesis in most of the flowering plants?", options: ["48", "12", "24", "6"], correct: 0, explanation: "1 Microspore Mother Cell (MMC) produces a tetrad of 4 microspores (pollen grains). So, 6 MMCs × 4 = 24 pollen grains. Each pollen grain produces 2 male gametes. Therefore, 24 pollen grains × 2 = 48 male gametes." },

  { id: 446, topic: "Endosperm Formation", hots: true, q: "During the most common type of endosperm development in flowering plants", options: ["Cell wall formation is completely absent", "PEN undergoes successive nuclear divisions to give rise to free nuclei", "Each division of PEN is immediately followed by wall formation", "Free nuclear divisions are absent"], correct: 1, explanation: "The most common endosperm development is the 'free-nuclear' type. The Primary Endosperm Nucleus (PEN) undergoes successive nuclear divisions without cytokinesis to form free nuclei. Cell wall formation occurs later from the periphery inwards." },

  { id: 447, topic: "Microsporogenesis Definition", hots: true, q: "During microsporogenesis", options: ["Microspore tetrad is developed by meiosis in sporogenous tissue", "Pollen grains are developed by mitosis in sporogenous tissue", "Microspore develops into male gametophyte", "Male gametes are produced by pollen grain"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT defines microsporogenesis strictly as: 'As the anther develops, the cells of the sporogenous tissue undergo meiotic divisions to form microspore tetrads. The process of formation of microspores from a pollen mother cell (PMC) through meiosis is called microsporogenesis.'" },

  { id: 448, topic: "Sporopollenin Location", hots: true, q: "Pollen wall contains sporopollenin which is one of the most resistant organic material. It is found in", options: ["Exine", "Intine", "Both exine and intine", "Endexine and intine"], correct: 0, explanation: "The pollen grain has a two-layered wall (sporoderm). The hard outer layer is the exine, which is made of the highly resistant organic polymer sporopollenin. The inner layer, intine, is made of cellulose and pectin." },

  { id: 449, topic: "Pollen Shedding", hots: true, q: "In most of the angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at", options: ["3-celled stage", "4-celled stage", "2-celled stage", "1-celled stage"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In over 60 per cent of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at this 2-celled stage (vegetative cell and generative cell).' The generative cell divides later in the pollen tube." },

  { id: 450, topic: "Pollen Banks", hots: true, q: "In pollen banks, pollens are stored at", options: ["-196°C of liquid nitrogen", "+20°C of liquid nitrogen", "0°C of liquid nitrogen", "4°C of liquid nitrogen"], correct: 0, explanation: "To maintain viability for years, pollen grains of a large number of species can be cryopreserved. NCERT explicitly mentions they are stored in liquid nitrogen at -196°C. Such stored pollen can be used as pollen banks, similar to seed banks." },

  { id: 451, topic: "Ovule Structure", hots: true, q: "The stalk by which an ovule is attached to the placenta is called", options: ["Funicle", "Hilum", "Chalaza", "Micropyle"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT details the structure of the megasporangium (ovule): 'The ovule is a small structure attached to the placenta by means of a stalk called funicle. The body of the ovule fuses with funicle in the region called hilum.'" },

  { id: 452, topic: "Angiosperm Terminology", hots: true, q: "Choose the correct match w.r.t. angiosperm.", options: ["Microsporangium - ovule; Megasporangium - female gametophyte", "Megasporangium - ovule; Embryo sac - female gametophyte", "Megasporangium - female gametophyte; Embryo sac - ovule", "Nucellus - male gametophyte; Megasporangium - ovule"], correct: 1, explanation: "In botanical terminology for angiosperms, the ovule is technically an integumented megasporangium. The structure that develops from the megaspore inside it is the embryo sac, which represents the female gametophyte." },

  { id: 453, topic: "Embryo Sac Development", hots: true, q: "Formation of embryo sac from a single megaspore nuclei is termed as", options: ["Bisporic development", "Monosporic development", "Tetrasporic development", "Polysporic development"], correct: 1, explanation: "In the majority of angiosperms, one megaspore remains functional while three degenerate. The formation of the female gametophyte (embryo sac) entirely from this single functional megaspore is known as monosporic development." },

  { id: 454, topic: "Embryo Sac Nuclei", hots: true, q: "A typical angiospermic embryo sac is", options: ["8-nucleate, 8 - celled", "7-nucleate, 8 - celled", "8 nucleate, 7 - celled", "7 nucleate, 6 - celled"], correct: 2, explanation: "A typical mature embryo sac (Polygonum type) contains 8 nuclei distributed among 7 cells: 3 cells in the egg apparatus, 3 antipodal cells, and 1 large central cell (which contains 2 polar nuclei)." },

  { id: 455, topic: "Pollination Types", hots: true, q: "Functionally cross-pollination but genetically similar to autogamy is", options: ["Xenogamy", "Geitonogamy", "Chasmogamy", "Cleistogamy"], correct: 1, explanation: "Geitonogamy involves the transfer of pollen from the anther to the stigma of another flower on the same plant. It requires a pollinating agent (functionally cross-pollination) but brings genetically identical pollen (genetically autogamy)." },

  { id: 456, topic: "Pollination Agents", hots: true, q: "Abiotic agents for pollination are", options: ["Wind, animals", "Water, animals", "Wind, water", "Wind, water and animals"], correct: 2, explanation: "Plants use two types of agents for pollination: abiotic (non-living) and biotic (living). The two abiotic agents are wind (anemophily) and water (hydrophily). Animals represent the biotic agents." },

  { id: 457, topic: "Grass Embryo", hots: true, q: "What is true for cotyledon in grass family?", options: ["Called as scutellum that is situated at the apex of embryonal axis", "Called as scutellum that is situated towards lateral side of the embryonal axis", "Called as coleoptile that is situated at the apex of embryonal axis", "Called as coleoptile that is situated towards lateral side of the embryonal axis"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT explains the monocot embryo: 'In the grass family the cotyledon is called scutellum that is situated towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis.' The coleoptile is a hollow foliar structure protecting the plumule, not the cotyledon itself." },

  { id: 458, topic: "Apomixis & Parthenocarpy", hots: true, q: "Choose the correct one.", options: ["Apomixis - production of seeds without fertilization, Parthenocarpy - seed with many embryos", "Apomixis - production of seeds without fertilization; Parthenocarpy - production of fruits without fertilization", "Apomixis - production of multiple embryo in seeds; Parthenocarpy - production of seeds without fertilization", "Apomixis - production of seeds with multiple embryo, Parthenocarpy - production of fruits with multiple seeds"], correct: 1, explanation: "Apomixis is a specialized form of asexual reproduction that produces seeds without fertilization. Parthenocarpy is the development of fruits without fertilization (resulting in seedless fruits, like in banana)." },

  { id: 459, topic: "Microsporangium Layers", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 459 Diagram showing anther wall layers D=Epidermis, C=Endothecium, B=Middle Layers, A=Tapetum.jpg", q: "Examine the figure of microsporangium and select the part correctly matched with its feature or function.", options: ["Part (D): Endothecium - Development of sporoderm", "Part (A): Innermost wall layer - Dense cytoplasm in cells", "Part (C): Middle layers - Nutrition to megaspores", "Part (B): Tapetum - Sporic meiosis"], correct: 1, explanation: "Based on the standard transverse section of a microsporangium, 'A' points to the innermost layer, the tapetum. NCERT states: 'Cells of the tapetum possess dense cytoplasm and generally have more than one nucleus.' They provide nutrition to developing microspores, not megaspores." },

  { id: 460, topic: "Monocot Embryo", hots: true, q: "At lower end, the embryonal axis in grasses has the radical and root cap enclosed in/by", options: ["Coleoptile", "Hypocotyl", "An undifferentiated sheath", "Epicotyl"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states: 'At its lower end, the embryonal axis has the radical and root cap enclosed in an undifferentiated sheath called coleorhiza.'" },

  { id: 461, topic: "Angiosperm Embryology", hots: true, q: "Select the odd one out w.r.t. angiospermic plants.", options: ["Most common embryo sac is Polygonum type", "Dichogamy is an adaptation for cross pollination", "In many Citrus and Apple varieties some of the integument cells start dividing and develop into the embryos", "Diploid endosperm is found in Oenothera"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT explains that in many Citrus and Mango varieties, it is the nucellar cells (not integument cells) that start dividing, protrude into the embryo sac, and develop into multiple embryos (polyembryony)." },

  { id: 462, topic: "Entomophily Features", hots: true, q: "Which one of the following is not a characteristic of entomophilous flowers?", options: ["Petals are usually coloured", "Sticky exine due to presence of pollenkitt", "Reduction in the number of sepals and petals", "Stigma are long, rough and sticky"], correct: 2, explanation: "Entomophilous (insect-pollinated) flowers rely on visual and chemical cues to attract insects, so they typically have well-developed, large, and colourful sepals/petals. A reduction in the perianth (sepals and petals) is a characteristic of anemophilous (wind-pollinated) flowers, where showy petals are unnecessary." },

  { id: 463, topic: "Embryo Sac Structure", hots: true, q: "Structure in female gametophyte which play an important role in guiding the pollen tube into synergid is", options: ["Antipodal cells", "Filiform apparatus", "Egg apparatus", "Central cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The synergids have special cellular thickenings at the micropylar tip called filiform apparatus, which play an important role in guiding the pollen tubes into the synergid.'" },

  { id: 464, topic: "Pollination Adaptations", hots: true, q: "Which one may not be an adaptation for pollen transfer by air?", options: ["Light and non-sticky pollen grains", "Well exposed stamens and feathery stigma", "Single ovule in each ovary", "Mucilagenous covering on microspores"], correct: 3, explanation: "A mucilaginous covering on pollen grains is an adaptation to protect them from wetting. This is characteristic of hydrophily (water pollination), not anemophily (wind pollination)." },

  { id: 465, topic: "Ploidy Levels", hots: true, q: "The ploidy of the nucellus, megaspore mother cell, female gametophyte and secondary nucleus is respectively", options: ["2N, 2N, N, 2N", "2N, 2N, N, N", "2N, N, N, 2N", "N, 2N, N, 2N"], correct: 0, explanation: "Nucellus is a maternal sporophytic tissue (2N). The Megaspore Mother Cell (MMC) differentiates from it, so it is also 2N. The female gametophyte (embryo sac) is formed after meiosis, making it haploid (N). The secondary nucleus is formed by the fusion of two haploid polar nuclei (N + N = 2N)." },

  { id: 466, topic: "Cleistogamy", hots: true, q: "Cleistogamous flowers are characterized by", options: ["Transfer of pollen to other flower", "Assured seed set", "Unisexual condition", "Bisexual open condition"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT notes: 'Cleistogamous flowers produce assured seed-set even in the absence of pollinators.' Since they do not open at all, cross-pollination is impossible, guaranteeing autogamy." },

  { id: 467, topic: "Hydrophily", hots: true, q: "Pollination which is restricted to few angiosperms, mostly monocots is", options: ["Hydrophily", "Anemophily", "Entomophily", "Ornithophily"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT specifies: 'Pollination by water is quite rare in flowering plants and is limited to about 30 genera, mostly monocotyledons.'" },

  { id: 468, topic: "Fertilization Events", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 468 Diagram of a pollen tube entering an embryo sac.jpg", q: "Study the diagram shown below and select the option in which all the three parts labelled as A, B and C are correctly identified.", options: ["A-Filiform apparatus, B-Vegetative nucleus, C-Secondary nucleus", "A-Synergid, B-Sperm, C-Nucellus", "A-Filiform apparatus, B-Male gamete, C-Central cell", "A-Synergid, B-Male gamete, C-Secondary nucleus"], correct: 2, explanation: "Based on standard NCERT diagrams of double fertilization: 'A' points to the finger-like projections at the synergid tip (Filiform apparatus). 'B' points to one of the two male gametes released from the pollen tube. 'C' points to the large central cell containing the polar nuclei." },

  { id: 469, topic: "Artificial Hybridization", hots: true, q: "A plant breeder employs technique of emasculation", options: ["To cover the flower with a bag", "To prevent self-pollination", "To prevent stamen from being contaminated", "To produce female plant"], correct: 1, explanation: "Emasculation involves removing the anthers from a bisexual flower bud before they dehisce. This is done specifically to prevent self-pollination, allowing the breeder to manually cross-pollinate with desired pollen." },

  { id: 470, topic: "Post-Fertilization Changes", hots: true, q: "Find the incorrect one w.r.t. post-fertilization changes.", options: ["Nucellus → Perisperm", "Integument → Seed coat", "Pericarp → Ovarian wall", "Central cell → Endosperm"], correct: 2, explanation: "The arrow denotes 'develops into'. The ovarian wall develops into the pericarp (fruit wall). Option 3 presents this backwards (Pericarp → Ovarian wall), making it the incorrect statement." },

  { id: 471, topic: "False Fruits", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 471 Diagram L.S. of an Apple. A points to Thalamus. B points to Seed..jpg", q: "Look at the diagram given below and answer appropriately.<br>(a) Since <b>A</b> is associated with fruit, it is called as (i)<br>(b) Since <b>(B)</b> is present, fruit cannot be called as (ii)", options: ["A- Pericarp, (i) - True fruits", "B-Seed, (ii) - Ex-albuminous", "A-Thalamus, (i) - True fruit", "B-Seed, (ii) - Parthenocarpic"], correct: 3, explanation: "In an apple (false fruit), 'A' points to the fleshy thalamus. 'B' points to the seed. Since a seed (B) is present, the fruit is a product of fertilization and therefore cannot be called parthenocarpic (which are seedless fruits developed without fertilization)." },

  { id: 472, topic: "Embryology Statements", hots: true, q: "Which one of the following statement is incorrect?", options: ["The generative cell divides during the growth of pollen tube in the stigma", "In some species floral rewards are providing safe places to lay eggs", "The embryo development precedes endosperm development", "Scutellum is lateral to the embryonal axis in grass family"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT explicitly states: 'Endosperm development precedes embryo development.' This happens to guarantee that the developing embryo will have a ready supply of nutrition." },

  { id: 473, topic: "Cell Counts", hots: true, q: "In angiosperms egg apparatus, embryo sac and pollen grains most commonly have ____ cells respectively.", options: ["8, 8 & 3", "3, 8 & 3", "3, 7 & 3", "3, 7 & 2"], correct: 3, explanation: "The egg apparatus consists of 3 cells (1 egg + 2 synergids). A typical mature embryo sac contains 7 cells (3 antipodal, 1 central, 3 in egg apparatus). Pollen grains in over 60% of angiosperms are shed at the 2-celled stage (vegetative and generative)." },

  { id: 474, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "Cross pollination is encouraged if", options: ["Flower is self fertile", "Homogamy is present", "Flower is dioecious", "Flowers are hermaphrodite"], correct: 2, explanation: "Dioecy means male and female flowers are borne on separate plants (like papaya). This condition completely prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy, strictly enforcing cross-pollination (xenogamy)." },

  { id: 475, topic: "Pollination Types", hots: true, q: "Find the incorrect statement w.r.t. Commelina.", options: ["Cleistogamous flowers", "Assured seed set", "Abiotic pollinators", "No anthesis"], correct: 2, explanation: "Commelina produces cleistogamous flowers which never open (no anthesis), thus assuring seed set via autogamy. Because they are closed, they require no pollinators at all (neither biotic nor abiotic)." },

  { id: 476, topic: "Megasporogenesis", hots: true, q: "Single large cell containing dense cytoplasm and prominent nucleus, undergoes meiosis and present within ovule is", options: ["Megaspore", "Microspore mother cell", "A nucellar cell", "Perisperm"], correct: 2, explanation: "The question describes the Megaspore Mother Cell (MMC). According to NCERT, the ovule differentiates a single MMC from 'a nucellar cell' in the micropylar region. Therefore, defining it by its origin as a differentiated nucellar cell is correct in this context." },

  { id: 477, topic: "Apomixis", hots: true, q: "Asexual reproduction mimics sexual reproduction when", options: ["Seed formation occurs without fertilization", "Thalamus is associated with fruit", "Pseudocarpic fruits are formed", "There is no fruit formation"], correct: 0, explanation: "Apomixis is a form of asexual reproduction that mimics sexual reproduction because it results in the formation of seeds—which are normally the product of sexual fertilization—without fertilization actually taking place." },

  { id: 478, topic: "Ploidy Levels", hots: true, q: "Aleurone layer has same ploidy as that of", options: ["PEN", "Zygote", "Pericarp", "Scutellum"], correct: 0, explanation: "The aleurone layer is the outermost proteinaceous layer of the endosperm. Like the rest of the endosperm, it develops from the Primary Endosperm Nucleus (PEN) and is therefore triploid (3n). Zygote, pericarp, and scutellum are all diploid (2n)." },

  { id: 479, topic: "Male Gametophyte", hots: true, q: "Male gametophyte in angiosperms is", options: ["Highly reduced", "Can have maximum two cells", "Developed after two asymmetric mitosis", "A mitospore diploid structure"], correct: 0, explanation: "In angiosperms, the male gametophyte (pollen grain) is highly reduced, consisting of only 2 or 3 cells at maturity. It is a haploid structure developed from a haploid microspore." },

  { id: 480, topic: "Pollination Statistics", hots: true, q: "Pollination in most angiosperms", options: ["Occur at 3-celled stage", "Involve bees", "Occur at 2-celled stage", "Is anemophilous"], correct: 1, explanation: "While pollination occurs at the 2-celled stage in ~60% of angiosperms, biotic pollination (involving insects/animals) occurs in the vast majority (>80%) of all flowering plants, with bees being the absolute dominant pollinating agents. In competitive MCQs, this overwhelming reliance on bees is often highlighted as the defining characteristic of 'most' angiosperms." },

  { id: 481, topic: "Anther Structure", hots: true, q: "A typical anther shows<br><b>a.</b> Two lobes with two theca each<br><b>b.</b> Each lobe as dithecous<br><b>c.</b> All cells in a given microsporangium as potential PMC<br><b>d.</b> Thousands of microspores per microsporangium<br>Out of these statements", options: ["b is incorrect", "a and b are correct", "c and d are incorrect", "a, b, c and d are correct"], correct: 3, explanation: "All statements align with NCERT: Anthers are bilobed and dithecous (a, b). Every cell of the sporogenous tissue is a potential pollen mother cell (c). Upon maturity, thousands of microspores/pollen grains are formed inside each microsporangium (d)." },

  { id: 482, topic: "Pollen & Anther Features", hots: true, q: "Find the incorrect statement.", options: ["α-cellulose thickening is associated with inner tangential wall of endothecium", "Pollenkitts are associated with anemophilous groups", "No enzyme can degrade sporopollenin", "Advanced pollen tetrad is the product of successive cytokinesis"], correct: 1, explanation: "Pollenkitt is a sticky, oily, yellowish covering found on the outside of pollen grains in entomophilous (insect-pollinated) plants to help them stick to insects. It is not associated with anemophilous (wind-pollinated) plants, which require dry, non-sticky pollen." },

  { id: 483, topic: "Ovule Anatomy", hots: true, q: "Which of the following structure is not associated with megasporangium in angiosperms?", options: ["Integuments", "Funicle", "Micropyle", "Tapetum"], correct: 3, explanation: "The megasporangium is the ovule, which consists of the funicle, integuments, and micropyle. The tapetum is the innermost nutritive layer of the microsporangium (anther wall), not the megasporangium." },

  { id: 484, topic: "Pollinator Preferences", hots: true, q: "Which of the following statements is wrong?", options: ["Flies and beetles visit white flowers with sweet fragrance", "Floral rewards are usually pollen and nectar", "Pollen grains are protected from wetting by mucilage covering in certain groups", "Anemophilous flowers have generally single ovule in ovary"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT notes: 'flowers pollinated by flies and beetles secrete foul odours to attract these animals.' They are not typically attracted to sweet fragrances, which are favored by bees and butterflies." },

  { id: 485, topic: "Stamen Morphology", hots: true, q: "The proximal end of the filament in stamen is attached to the", options: ["Anther", "Connective", "Thalamus or petal", "Calyx"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states directly: 'The proximal end of the filament is attached to the thalamus or the petal of the flower.' The distal end is attached to the anther." },

  { id: 486, topic: "Anther Wall Functions", hots: true, q: "Which of the following layers of anther wall perform the function of protection and also help in dehiscence of anther to release the pollens?", options: ["Tapetum and middle layer", "Epidermis and tapetum", "Epidermis, endothecium and middle layers", "Endothecium and tapetum"], correct: 2, explanation: "According to NCERT: 'The outer three wall layers (epidermis, endothecium and middle layers) perform the function of protection and help in dehiscence of anther to release the pollen.' The innermost layer (tapetum) provides nutrition." },

  { id: 487, topic: "Pollen Fossils", hots: true, q: "Pollen grains are well-preserved as fossils because of the presence of", options: ["Pollenkitt", "Sporopollenin", "Pecto-cellulose", "Ligno-cellulose"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT explains that the exine is made of sporopollenin, one of the most resistant organic materials known. It cannot be degraded by enzymes, high temperatures, strong acids, or alkalis. Because of this, 'Pollen grains are well-preserved as fossils.'" },

  { id: 488, topic: "Megasporogenesis", hots: true, q: "Megaspore mother cell differentiates from", options: ["Nucellus in the micropylar region", "Integument in the chalazal region", "Primary parietal cell in chalazal region", "Integument cell in micropylar region"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Ovules generally differentiate a single megaspore mother cell (MMC) in the micropylar region of the nucellus.'" },

  { id: 489, topic: "Post-Fertilization", hots: true, q: "Select incorrect statement.", options: ["The central cell becomes primary endosperm cell (PEC)", "Endosperm persists in mature seed of castor", "Scutellum lies lateral of the embryonal axis in grass family", "Ploidy level of endosperm in maize is haploid"], correct: 3, explanation: "Maize is an angiosperm. In angiosperms, the endosperm is formed by triple fusion (one haploid male gamete + two haploid polar nuclei), making it a triploid (3n) tissue, not haploid. Gymnosperm endosperm is haploid." },

  { id: 490, topic: "Angiosperm Features", hots: true, q: "Which one of the following statement is false in respect of flowering plants?", options: ["Parthenocarpy can be induced through the application of growth hormones", "Integuments encircle the ovule except at the tip where a small opening called the germ pore is organised", "Endosperm development precedes embryo development", "Apomicts have several advantages in horticulture and agriculture"], correct: 1, explanation: "The small opening at the tip of the ovule where integuments are absent is called the micropyle, not the germ pore. Germ pores are apertures found on the exine of pollen grains." },

  { id: 491, topic: "Nucellus", hots: true, q: "Choose the incorrect option w.r.t nucellus.", options: ["Possesses abundant reserve food material", "Generally differentiate a single megaspore mother cell", "It represents microsporangium", "It is enclosed within integuments"], correct: 2, explanation: "The nucellus is the central part of the megasporangium (ovule), not the microsporangium (which refers to the pollen sac in the anther)." },

  { id: 492, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "Which of the following prevents inbreeding depression?", options: ["Pollen is released and stigma becomes receptive at the same time", "Presence of bisexual flowers", "Presence of self-incompatibility", "Anther and stigma are placed at same positions"], correct: 2, explanation: "Inbreeding depression results from continuous self-pollination. Self-incompatibility is a genetic mechanism that prevents self-pollen from fertilizing the ovule, thereby preventing inbreeding. The other options describe conditions that actually promote self-pollination." },

  { id: 493, topic: "Gametophyte Structures", hots: true, q: "Which is correct to gametophyte in angiosperm?", options: ["Male gametophyte: 3 nucleated; Female gametophyte: 8 nucleated", "Male gametophyte: 4 nucleated; Female gametophyte: 8 nucleated", "Male gametophyte: 2 nucleated; Female gametophyte: 8 nucleated", "Male gametophyte: 2 nucleated; Female gametophyte: 7 nucleated"], correct: 0, explanation: "A completely mature male gametophyte (germinated pollen) contains 3 nuclei (one vegetative nucleus + two male gametes). A typical mature female gametophyte (Polygonum type embryo sac) contains 8 nuclei distributed within 7 cells." },

  { id: 494, topic: "Ploidy Calculations", hots: true, q: "If pollen grain is having 12 chromosome then what would be the chromosomes number in endosperm of gymnosperm and angiosperm respectively?", options: ["24 and 36", "36 and 36", "12 and 36", "24 and 24"], correct: 2, explanation: "The pollen grain is haploid (n = 12). In gymnosperms, the endosperm represents the female gametophyte and is formed before fertilization, so it is haploid (n = 12). In angiosperms, the endosperm is formed after triple fusion and is triploid (3n = 12 * 3 = 36)." },

  { id: 495, topic: "Seed Diagram", hots: true, image: "images/sexual_reproduction/ID 495 Diagram of a monocotmaize seed in L.S..jpg", q: "Identify the labels A, B, C and D in the figure given below.", options: ["A-endosperm; B-scutellum; C-plumule; D-seed coat", "A-aleurone; B-endosperm; C-radicle; D-coleorhiza", "A-epithelium; B-aleurone; C-plumule; D-seed coat", "A-endosperm; B-aleurone; C-plumule; D-seed coat and fruit wall"], correct: 3, explanation: "Based on the NCERT diagram of a maize seed: A is the large starchy Endosperm. B points to the proteinaceous Aleurone layer surrounding it. C points to the Plumule inside the coleoptile. D points to the fused Pericarp and seed coat (seed coat and fruit wall)." },

  { id: 496, topic: "Sporopollenin", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> No enzyme that degrades sporopollenin is so far known.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> It is one of the most resistant organic materials of megaspore.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT Class 12 states that sporopollenin is one of the most resistant organic materials and no enzyme degrades it (Assertion is True). However, it is present in the exine of the microspore (pollen grain), not the megaspore. Thus, the Reason is False." },

  { id: 497, topic: "Pollen Viability & Storage", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Pollen grains can be stored for years at -196°C.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Stored pollens can be used as seed banks.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 2, explanation: "Assertion is true as pollen grains can be cryopreserved in liquid nitrogen at -196°C. Reason is false because stored pollens are used in pollen banks for crop breeding programmes, not as seed banks." },

  { id: 498, topic: "Embryo Sac Structure", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Central cell of the typical embryo sac is initially bikaryotic and haploid.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> It is the largest cell of embryo sac.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "The central cell is the largest cell of the embryo sac (Reason is true). Initially, it contains two polar nuclei, meaning it is binucleate/bikaryotic and each nucleus is haploid (Assertion is true). However, its large size is not the explanation for its nuclear condition. Hence, both are true but R is not the correct explanation." },

  { id: 499, topic: "Hydrophily in Zostera", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In Zostera, pollen grains are released inside the water.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Female flowers of Zostera plant remain submerged in water.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT explains that in sea grasses like Zostera, female flowers remain submerged in water (Reason). To achieve pollination, the long, ribbon-like pollen grains must be released inside the water to reach them (Assertion). The reason correctly explains the assertion." },

  { id: 500, topic: "Artificial Hybridization", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> If the female parent produces bisexual flowers there is no need for emasculation during hybridization.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Bisexual flowers are always protogynous.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 3, explanation: "If the female parent produces bisexual flowers, emasculation (removal of anthers) is absolutely necessary to prevent self-pollination (Assertion is false). Bisexual flowers are not always protogynous; they can be protandrous or homogamous (Reason is false)." },

  { id: 501, topic: "Endospermic Seeds", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Seeds of castor and coconut are albuminous.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Endosperm persists in the mature seed of castor and coconut plants.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "Albuminous seeds are those that retain a part of the endosperm as it is not completely used up during embryo development. Because the endosperm persists in castor and coconut, they are termed albuminous. The reason correctly explains the assertion." },

  { id: 502, topic: "Cleistogamy", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Cleistogamy is advantageous to the plants.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Cleistogamy results in the assured seed formation even in the absence of pollinators.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "Cleistogamous flowers never open. This guarantees autogamy (self-pollination). As NCERT points out, the evolutionary advantage of this is that it ensures seed set even if no pollinating agents are available. The reason correctly explains the assertion." },

  { id: 503, topic: "Embryo Sac Formation", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> An ovule generally has a 7-nucleated and 8-celled embryo sac formed from megaspore through reduction division.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Embryo sac is a diploid structure.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 3, explanation: "A typical embryo sac is 8-nucleate and 7-celled, not 7-nucleated and 8-celled. Also, it is formed through mitotic (equational) divisions, not reduction division, of the megaspore (Assertion is false). The embryo sac represents the female gametophyte and is a haploid structure, not diploid (Reason is false)." },

  { id: 504, topic: "Hybrid Seeds", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Cultivation of hybrids has tremendously increased productivity.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Progeny of hybrids do not maintain hybrid characters due to segregation.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "Hybrids show heterosis (hybrid vigor), leading to increased productivity (Assertion is true). If hybrid seeds are sown, the traits segregate in the progeny (Reason is true). However, segregation is a disadvantage and explains why seeds must be bought yearly, not why productivity is high. Thus, R does not explain A." },

  { id: 505, topic: "Gametogenesis", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Gametes are haploid though the parent plant body from which they arise may be either haploid or diploid.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Haploid organisms produce their gametes by meiosis.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 2, explanation: "Gametes are strictly haploid regardless of parent ploidy (Assertion is true). However, haploid organisms (like bryophytes or some algae) cannot undergo meiosis to form gametes; they produce gametes by mitosis (Reason is false)." },

  { id: 506, topic: "Pollen Products", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> A large number of pollen products in the form of tablets and syrups are available in the market.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen grains are rich in nutrients.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT notes: 'Pollen grains are rich in nutrients. It has become a fashion in recent years to use pollen tablets as food supplements.' The high nutrient content correctly explains their commercial availability as health supplements." },

  { id: 507, topic: "Abiotic Pollination", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Anemophilous as well as hydrophilous flowers produce enormous amount of pollens.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen grains coming in contact with the stigma is a chance factor during these types of pollination.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "Because wind and water are non-directional abiotic agents, reaching the stigma is a matter of chance. To compensate for the massive loss of pollen during transit, these plants produce enormous quantities of pollen compared to the number of ovules available. Reason correctly explains Assertion." },

  { id: 508, topic: "Megasporogenesis", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Megaspore mother cell forms only one functional megaspore commonly.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Ovules generally differentiate the single megaspore mother cell in nucellus.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "It is true that usually only one functional megaspore is formed (because the other three degenerate). It is also true that only one MMC differentiates in the nucellus. However, the presence of one MMC explains why there is only one tetrad, not why only one megaspore remains functional (which is due to degeneration). Thus, R is not the correct explanation." },

  { id: 509, topic: "Pollination Types", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Cleistogamous flowers produce assured seed set even in the absence of pollinators.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Cleistogamous flowers are invariably geitonogamous.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 2, explanation: "Assertion is true as cleistogamous flowers do not open and ensure self-pollination. However, they are invariably autogamous (pollen falls on the stigma of the same flower), not geitonogamous (pollination between different flowers of the same plant). Thus, Reason is false." },

  { id: 510, topic: "Geitonogamy", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Genetically, geitonogamy is similar to autogamy.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Geitonogamy brings the pollen grains belonging to the same plant.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "Geitonogamy involves the transfer of pollen to another flower on the exact same plant. Because all flowers on a single plant share the same genotype, the fusion is genetically identical to autogamy (selfing). The reason correctly explains the assertion." },

  { id: 511, topic: "Male Gametophyte", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> A 2 celled pollen containing a large vegetative cell and small generative cell is considered a mature pollen grain.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> A 3 celled pollen with 2 male gametes and a vegetative cell is a mature male gametophyte.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "Pollen grains are shed at the 2-celled stage in most angiosperms, representing the mature pollen grain (A is true). The fully mature male gametophyte is the 3-celled stage with male gametes (R is true). However, R describes a later stage and does not explain why the 2-celled structure is considered a mature pollen grain." },

  { id: 512, topic: "Biotic Pollination", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Often the flowers of animal pollinated plants are specifically adapted for a particular species of animal.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Majority of insect pollinated flowers are large, colourful, fragrant and rich in nectar.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "Many plants and their pollinators exhibit co-evolution, leading to specific adaptations (like Yucca and moth) (A is true). Most insect-pollinated flowers are large, colourful, and offer nectar (R is true). However, these general attractants do not explain the highly specific species-to-species adaptations. Hence, R does not explain A." },

  { id: 513, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Some plants produce flower in which either anther matures first or the stigma becomes receptive.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> These types of flowers are produced to prevent self-pollination.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "The lack of synchronization in maturation (dichogamy) means the pollen is released before the stigma is receptive (protandry) or vice versa (protogyny). This temporal separation is an outbreeding device specifically evolved to prevent autogamy (self-pollination). R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 514, topic: "Tapetum", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Tapetum provides nourishment to the pollen grains.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Tapetum secretes enzymes as well as hormones.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "The tapetum is the innermost anther wall layer that nourishes the developing microspores (A is true). It also secretes callase enzyme and IAA hormones (R is true). However, its secretory function of enzymes/hormones is separate from its dense cytoplasmic nutritive function, so R does not strictly explain A." },

  { id: 515, topic: "Anther Structure", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> A typical anther of a flower is bilobed.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Each lobe of anther is dithecous.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "A typical angiosperm anther has two lobes (bilobed) (A is true). Within each lobe, there are two theca (dithecous) (R is true). Both statements are independent morphological facts. The dithecous nature of a lobe does not explain why the anther is bilobed." },

  { id: 516, topic: "Gynoecium Morphology", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Papaver has multicarpellary and syncarpous type of pistil.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Michelia possesses multicarpellary and apocarpous type of pistil.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both statements are factually correct NCERT examples: Papaver (poppy) has fused carpels (syncarpous), and Michelia has free carpels (apocarpous). However, the structure of Michelia's pistil has no explanatory relationship to the structure of Papaver's pistil." },

  { id: 517, topic: "Monosporic Development", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> A typical angiospermic embryo sac is considered as monosporic.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> A monosporic embryo sac is always 7 celled 8 nucleate condition.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 2, explanation: "The typical Polygonum type embryo sac develops from a single functional megaspore, making it monosporic (A is true). However, a monosporic embryo sac is not always 8-nucleate. For example, Oenothera has a monosporic embryo sac that is only 4-nucleate. Thus, R is false." },

  { id: 518, topic: "Nuclear Endosperm", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> A nuclear type of endosperm is a result of karyokinesis not followed by cytokinesis.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Such type of endosperm formed never undergoes Cytokinesis.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 2, explanation: "Free nuclear endosperm forms when PEN undergoes divisions without cell wall formation (A is true). However, this free-nuclear condition is usually temporary. Subsequently, cell wall formation (cytokinesis) occurs from the periphery towards the center to make it cellular. Thus, 'never undergoes cytokinesis' makes R false." },

  { id: 519, topic: "Embryo & Endosperm Development", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The development of embryo proceeds the development of endosperm.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Embryo ensures the nutrition of developing endosperm.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT strictly states that endosperm development precedes embryo development. This is because the endosperm's function is to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo, not the other way around. Therefore, both the assertion and the reason are completely false." },

  { id: 520, topic: "Seed Development", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Non-endospermic seeds do not have any residual endosperm.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> The endosperm is completely consumed during embryo development.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "In non-endospermic (ex-albuminous) seeds like pea and groundnut, the endosperm is completely consumed by the developing embryo before seed maturation. Therefore, no residual endosperm is left. The reason perfectly explains the assertion." },

  { id: 521, topic: "Seed Coat Anatomy", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Micropyle is a small pore that is found on the seed coat.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Micropyle is an opening of the ovule through which the pollen tube enters.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "The micropyle persists as a small pore in the seed coat to facilitate oxygen and water entry during germination (A is true). In the ovule stage, it is the opening where integuments are absent, allowing pollen tube entry (R is true). However, its past function as a pollen tube entry point does not explain why it persists on the seed coat (which is for water/oxygen entry)." },

  { id: 522, topic: "Perisperm", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Perisperm is the remnant of nucellus found in some seeds.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In black pepper and beet the nucellus persists in its seed.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "Perisperm is indeed defined as the residual, persistent nucellus in seeds (A is true). Black pepper and beet are classic examples where this occurs (R is true). Providing examples confirms the statement but does not logically explain why the nucellus fails to be consumed in those specific seeds." },

  { id: 523, topic: "Seed Adaptations", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Seeds have better adaptive strategies for dispersal to new habitat.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Dormancy is state of inactivity of embryo when the seed is not able to germinate.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 1, explanation: "Seeds possess structures (like wings, hooks, fruits) for dispersal (A is true). Dormancy allows the seed to survive unfavorable conditions by remaining inactive (R is true). While dormancy aids survival across time, it does not explain the physical dispersal strategies across space to new habitats." },

  { id: 524, topic: "Angiosperm Reproduction", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In angiosperm seed formation is more dependable.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> In angiosperm, reproductive processes such as pollination and fertilisation are independent of water.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "Unlike bryophytes and pteridophytes, which require water for the flagellated male gametes to swim to the egg, seed plants (angiosperms) utilize pollen tubes to deliver non-motile male gametes. This independence from water makes fertilization and subsequent seed formation highly reliable and dependable." },

  { id: 525, topic: "Polyembryony", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> If a seed has more than one embryo sac it is called polyembryony.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> A haploid embryo sac is formed from megaspore mother cell of nucellar cell which has diploid egg.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 3, explanation: "Polyembryony is the occurrence of more than one embryo in a seed, not more than one embryo sac (Assertion is false). The egg cell inside the haploid embryo sac is haploid (n), not diploid (Reason is false)." },

  { id: 526, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", hots: true, q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Self-incompatibility and dichogamy are considered as out-breeding devices.<br><br><b>Reason (R):</b> Self incompatibility and dichogamy discourage self pollination and encourage cross pollination.", options: ["Both Assertion & Reason are true and the reason is the correct explanation of the assertion", "Both Assertion & Reason are true but the reason is not the correct explanation of the assertion", "Assertion is true statement but Reason is false", "Both Assertion and Reason are false statements"], correct: 0, explanation: "Outbreeding devices are evolutionary mechanisms developed by plants to prevent continuous inbreeding. Dichogamy (asynchronous maturation) and self-incompatibility (genetic block to self-pollen) are prime examples because they actively discourage autogamy and promote xenogamy. The reason correctly defines their function as outbreeding devices." }
];


